player can concede the game at any time. A player who concedes leaves the game immediately. He or she loses the game.\par \par }\pard\plain \s19\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {101. Starting the Game\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 101.1. At the start of a game, each player shuffles his or her own deck so that the cards are in a random order. Each player may then shuffle his or her opponent\rquote s deck. The players\rquote  decks become their libraries.\par \par 101.2. After the decks have been shuffled, the players determine who chooses which player goes first using any mutually agreeable method (flipping a coin, rolling dice, etc.). In a match of several games, the loser of the previous game decides who will take the first turn. If the previous game was a draw, the person who determined who would take the first turn in the previous game decides.\par \par 101.3. Once the starting player has been determined, each player sets his or her life total to 20 and draws a hand of seven cards.\par \par 101.4. A player who is dissatisfied with his or her initial hand may mulligan. First, the starting player takes any mulligans. To take a mulligan, that player shuffles his or her hand back into the deck and then draws a new hand of six cards. He or she may repeat this process as many times as desired, drawing one fewer card each time, until the hand size reaches zero cards. Once the starting player has decided to keep a hand, the other player may take any number of mulligans. A player can\rquote t take any mulligans once he or she has decided to keep a hand.\par \par 101.5. Once both players are satisfied with their hands, the starting player takes his or her turn. The player who plays first skips the draw step (see rule 304, \ldblquote Draw Step\rdblquote ) of his or her first turn.\par \par }\pard\plain \s19\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {102. Winning and Losing\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 102.1. If a player\rquote s life total is 0 or less, he or she loses the game the next time a player would receive priority. (This is a state-based effect. See rule 420.)\par \par 102.2. When a player is required to draw more cards than are left in his or her library, he or she draws the remaining cards, and then loses the game the next time a player would receive priority. (This is a state-based effect. See rule 420.)\par \par 102.3. A game immediately ends when a player loses or wins or when the game is a draw.\par \par 102.4. If both players lose simultaneously, the game is a draw.\par \par 102.5. If a player would both win and lose simultaneously, he or she loses.\par \par 102.6. If the game somehow enters a \ldblquote loop,\rdblquote  repeating a sequence of events with no way to stop, the game is a draw. Loops that contain an optional action don\rquote t result in a draw.\par \par 102.7. A player who concedes a game leaves the game immediately. He or she loses the game.\par \par 102.8. If a player has ten or more poison counters, he or she loses the game the next time a player would receive priority. (This is a state-based effect. See rule 420.)\par \par }\pard\plain \s19\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {103. The }{\b Magic}{ Golden Rules\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 103.1. Whenever a card\rquote s text directly contradicts these rules, the card takes precedence. The card overrides only the rule that applies to that specific situation. The only exception is that the rules in section 100, \ldblquote General,\rdblquote  and section 101, \ldblquote Starting the Game,\rdblquote  can\rquote t be overridden by the cards. Those rules apply at all times, regardless of what the cards say.\par \par 103.2. When one effect says something can happen and another says it can\rquote t, the \ldblquote can\rquote t\rdblquote  effect wins. For example, if one effect reads \ldblquote You may play an additional land this turn\rdblquote  and another reads \ldblquote You can\rquote t play land cards this turn,\rdblquote  the effect that keeps you from playing lands wins out. Note that adding abilities to objects and removing abilities from objects don\rquote t fall under this rule. See rule 407, \ldblquote Adding and Removing Abilities.\rdblquote \par \par 103.3. If an instruction requires taking an impossible action, it\rquote s ignored. (In many cases the card will specify consequences for this; if it doesn\rquote t, there\rquote s no effect.)\par \par 103.4. If both players would take an action at the same time, the active player (the player whose turn it is) makes any choices required, then the nonactive player makes any choices required, then the actions happen simultaneously. This rule is often referred to as the \ldblquote Active Player, Nonactive Player (APNAP) rule.\rdblquote \par }\pard\plain \s23\li1200\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ A card reads \ldblquote Each player sacrifices a creature.\rdblquote  First, the active player chooses a creature he or she controls. Then the nonactive player chooses a creature he or she controls. Then both creatures are sacrificed simultaneously.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par }\pard\plain \s19\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {104. Numbers and Symbols\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 104.1. The }{\b Magic}{ game uses only natural numbers. You may not choose a fractional number, deal fractional damage, and so on. When a spell or ability could generate a fractional number, the spell or ability will tell you whether to round up or down.\par \par 104.2. If a creature\rquote s power or toughness, a mana cost, a player\rquote s life total, or an amount of damage would be less than 0, it\rquote s treated as 0 for all purposes except changing that total. If anything needs to use a number that can\rquote t be determined, it uses 0 instead.\par }\pard\plain \s23\li1200\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ If a 3/3 creature gets -5/-0, it deals 0 damage in combat. But to raise its power back to 1, you\rquote d have to give it +3/+0 (3 minus 5 plus 3 is 1).\par }{\b Example:}{ If you control no permanents, the \ldblquote highest converted mana cost among permanents you control\rdblquote  can\rquote t be determined, so 0 is used instead.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 104.3. The mana symbols are \{oW\}, \{oU\}, \{oB\}, \{oR\}, \{oG\}, \{oX\}, \{oY\}, \{oZ\} and the numerals \{o0\}, \{o1\}, \{o2\}, \{o3\}, \{o4\}, and so on.\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {104.3a Each of the colored mana symbols represents one colored mana: \{oW\} is white, \{oU\} blue, \{oB\} black, \{oR\} red, and \{oG\} green.\par \par 104.3b Numeral symbols (such as \{o1\}) are generic mana costs and represent an amount of mana that can be paid with any color of, or colorless, mana.\par \par 104.3c The symbols \{oX\}, \{oY\}, and \{oZ\} represent unspecified amounts of mana; when playing a spell or activated ability with \{oX\}, \{oY\}, or \{oZ\} in its cost, its controller decides the value of that variable.\par \par 104.3d Numeral symbols (such as \{o1\}) and variable symbols (such as \{oX\}) can also represent colorless mana if they appear in the effect of a spell or ability that reads \ldblquote add [mana symbol] to your mana pool\rdblquote  or something similar.\par \par 104.3e The symbol \{o0\} represents zero mana and is used as a placeholder when a spell or activated ability costs nothing to play. A spell or ability whose cost is \{o0\} must still be played the same way as one with a cost greater than zero; it won\rquote t play itself automatically.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 104.4. The tap symbol is \{oT\}. The tap symbol in an activation cost means \ldblquote Tap this permanent.\rdblquote  A permanent that\rquote s already tapped can\rquote t be tapped again to pay the cost. Creatures that haven\rquote t been under a player\rquote s control continuously since the beginning of his or her most recent turn can\rquote t use any ability with the tap symbol in the cost. See rule 212.3d.\par \par 104.5. A tombstone icon appears to the left of the name of many }{\i Odyssey\u8482\'aa}{ block cards with abilities that are relevant in a player\rquote s graveyard. The purpose of the icon is to make those cards stand out when they\rquote re in a graveyard. This icon has no effect on game play.\par \par }\pard\plain \s17\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\f4\lang1033\cgrid {\page 2. Parts of the Game\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par }\pard\plain \s19\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {200. General\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 200.1. When a rule or text on a card refers to a \ldblquote card,\rdblquote  it means a }{\b Magic}{ card with a }{\b Magic}{ card front and the }{\b Magic}{ card back. Tokens aren\rquote t considered cards\emdash even a card that represents a token isn\rquote t considered a card for rules purposes.\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {200.1a A card\rquote s owner is the player who started the game with it in his or her deck or, for cards that didn\rquote t start the game in a player\rquote s deck, the player who brought the card into the game.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 200.2. Use the Oracle\u8482\'aa card reference when determining a card\rquote s wording. It can be found at }{\field\fldedit{\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK "http://www.wizards.com/default.asp?x=dci/oracle"}{{\*\datafield 00d0c9ea79f9bace118c8200aa004ba90b0200000003000000e0c9ea79f9bace118c8200aa004ba90b6000000068007400740070003a002f002f007700770077002e00770069007a0061007200640073002e0063006f006d002f00640065006600610075006c0074002e006100730070003f0078003d006400630069002f006f007200610063006c0065000000}}}{\fldrslt {\ul\cf2 www.wizards.c{\*\bkmkstart _Hlt43632592}o{\*\bkmkend _Hlt43632592}m/defaul{\*\bkmkstart _Hlt43632626}t{\*\bkmkend _Hlt43632626}.asp{\*\bkmkstart _Hlt50800007}?{\*\bkmkend _Hlt50800007}x=dci/oracle}}}{.\par \par 200.3. A }{\i player}{ is one of the two people in the game. A player\rquote s }{\i opponent}{ is the other player. The }{\i active player}{ is the player whose turn it is. The other player is the }{\i nonactive player.}{\par \par 200.4. A }{\i token}{ is a marker used to represent any permanent that isn\rquote t represented by a card. (See rule 216, \ldblquote Tokens.\rdblquote )\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {200.4a A token\rquote s owner is the player who controlled the spell or ability that put it into play. A token\rquote s controller is the player who put it into play.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 200.5. A }{\i spell}{ is a card or copy of a spell that\rquote s on the stack. (See rule 213, \ldblquote Spells.\rdblquote )\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {200.5a A spell\rquote s owner is the same as the owner of the card that represents it. A spell\rquote s controller is the player who played it.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 200.6. A }{\i permanent}{ is a card or token that\rquote s in play. (See rule 214, \ldblquote Permanents.\rdblquote )\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {200.6a A nontoken permanent\rquote s owner is the same as the owner of the card that represents it. A permanent\rquote s controller is the player who put it into play.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 200.7. An }{\i ability}{ can be one of two things. First, it can be an activated or triggered ability on the stack. Second, it can be text on an object that explains what the object does. (See rule 402, \ldblquote Abilities,\rdblquote  and section 4, \ldblquote Spells, Abilities, and Effects.\rdblquote )\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {200.7a The owner of an ability on the stack is the player who controlled its source when it was played or triggered. The controller of an ability on the stack is the player who played the ability, or the player who controlled the ability\rquote s source when it triggered.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 200.8. An }{\i object}{ is an ability on the stack, a card, a copy of a card, a token, a spell, or a permanent. The term \ldblquote object\rdblquote  is used in these rules when a rule applies to abilities on the stack, cards, tokens, spells, and permanents. Combat damage on the stack is also an object, although many uses of the term \ldblquote object\rdblquote  in these rules don\rquote t apply to it.\par \par 200.9. If a spell or ability uses a type, supertype, or subtype without either the word \ldblquote card,\rdblquote  \ldblquote spell,\rdblquote  or \ldblquote source,\rdblquote  it means a permanent of that type in play.\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {200.9a If a spell or ability uses a type, supertype, or subtype in conjunction with the word \ldblquote card,\rdblquote  and the name of a zone, it means a card with that type in the stated zone.\par \par 200.9b If a spell or ability uses a type, supertype, or subtype in conjunction with the word \ldblquote spell,\rdblquote  it means a spell of that type on the stack.\par \par 200.9c If a spell or ability uses a type, supertype, or subtype in conjunction with the word \ldblquote source,\rdblquote  it means a source of that type\emdash either a source of an ability or a source of damage. See rule 419.8 \ldblquote Sources of Damage.\rdblquote \par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 200.10. A }{\i counter}{ is a marker placed on an object or player, either modifying its characteristics or interacting with an ability. A counter is not a token, and a token is not a counter. A +X/+Y counter on a permanent, where X and Y are numbers, adds X to that permanent\rquote s power and Y to that permanent\rquote s toughness. Similarly, -X/-Y counters subtract from power and toughness. Counters with the same name or description are interchangeable.\par \par }\pard\plain \s19\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {201. Characteristics\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 201.1. The parts of a card are name, mana cost, illustration, type line, expansion symbol, text box, power and toughness, illustration credit, legal text, and collector number. Some cards may have more than one of any or all of these parts.\par \par 201.2. An object\rquote s characteristics are name, mana cost, color, type, subtype, supertype, expansion symbol, rules text, abilities, power, and toughness. Objects can have some or all of these characteristics. Any other information about an object isn\rquote t a characteristic. Characteristics don\rquote t include any other information, such as whether a permanent is tapped, a spell\rquote s target, an object\rquote s owner or controller, what a local enchantment enchants, and so on.\par \par }\pard\plain \s19\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {202. Name\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 202.1. The name of a card is printed on its upper left corner.\par \par 202.2. Text that refers to the object it\rquote s on by name means just that particular object and not any other duplicates of it, regardless of any name changes caused by game effects.\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {202.2a If an ability of an object uses a phrase such as \ldblquote this [something]\rdblquote  to identify an object, where [something] is a category or characteristic, it is referring to that particular object, even if it isn\rquote t the appropriate category or characteristic at the time.\par }\pard\plain \s24\li1500\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ An ability reads \ldblquote Target creature gets +2/+2 until end of turn. Destroy that creature at end of turn.\rdblquote  The ability will destroy the object it gave +2/+2 at the end of the turn, even if that object isn\rquote t a creature anymore.\par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 202.2b If an object grants to another object an ability that includes the first object\rquote s name, the name refers only to the object granting the ability, not to any other object with the same name.\par }\pard\plain \s24\li1500\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ Saproling Burst has an ability that reads \ldblquote Remove a fade counter from Saproling Burst: Put a green Saproling creature token into play. It has \lquote This creature\rquote s power and toughness are each equal to the number of fade counters on Saproling Burst.\rquote \rdblquote  The ability granted to the token only looks at the Saproling Burst that created the token, not at any other Saproling Burst in play.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 202.3. Two cards have the same name if the English versions of their names are identical, regardless of anything else printed on the cards.\par \par }\pard\plain \s19\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {203. Mana Cost and Color\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 203.1. The mana cost of a card is indicated by mana symbols printed on its upper right corner. Tokens and lands have a mana cost of \{o0\}. Paying an object\rquote s mana cost requires matching the color of any colored mana symbols as well as paying the generic mana cost indicated.\par \par 203.2. An object is the color or colors of the mana symbols in its mana cost, regardless of the color of its frame.\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {203.2a Objects with no colored mana symbols in their mana costs are colorless.\par \par 203.2b An object with two or more different colored mana symbols in its mana cost is each of the colors of those mana symbols. Multicolored cards are printed with a gold frame, but this is not a requirement for a card to be multicolored.\par \par 203.2c The five colors are white, blue, black, red, and green. The white mana symbol is represented by \{oW\}, blue by \{oU\}, black by \{oB\}, red by \{oR\}, and green by \{oG\}.\par }\pard\plain \s23\li1200\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ An object with a mana cost of \{o2\}\{oW\} is white, an object with a mana cost of \{o2\} is colorless, and one with a mana cost of \{o2\}\{oW\}\{oB\} is both white and black.\par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 203.2d If a player is asked to choose a color, he or she must choose one of the five colors. \ldblquote Multicolored\rdblquote  is not a color.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 203.3. The converted mana cost of an object is a number equal to the total amount of mana in its mana cost, regardless of color. Some effects ask a player to pay mana equal to an object\rquote s converted mana cost; this is a generic mana cost\emdash it may be paid with any combination of colored and/or colorless mana, regardless of the colors in the object\rquote s mana cost.\par }\pard\plain \s23\li1200\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ A mana cost of \{o3\}\{oU\}\{oU\} translates to a converted mana cost of 5.}{\b \par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 203.4. Any additional cost listed in an object\rquote s rules text or imposed by an effect isn\rquote t part of the mana cost. (See rule 409, \ldblquote Playing Spells and Activated Abilities.\rdblquote ) Such costs are paid at the same time as the spell\rquote s other costs.\par  \par }\pard\plain \s19\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {204. Illustration\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 204.1. The illustration is printed on the upper half of a card and has no game significance. For example, a creature doesn\rquote t have the flying ability unless stated in its rules text, even if it\rquote s depicted as flying.\par \par }\pard\plain \s19\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {205. Type Line\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 205.1. The type (and subtype and supertype, if applicable) of a card is printed directly below the illustration. (See rule 212, \ldblquote Type, Supertype, and Subtype.\rdblquote )\par \par 205.2. Types\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {205.2a The types are artifact, creature, enchantment, instant, land, and sorcery.\par \par 205.2b. Some objects can have more than one type (for example, an artifact creature). Such objects satisfy the criteria for any effect that applies to any of their types.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 205.3. Subtypes\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {205.3a A card can have one or more subtypes printed on its type line.\par \par 205.3b Artifact, creature, and land subtypes are always single words and are listed after a long dash. Each word after the dash is a separate subtype. Artifact subtypes are also called }{\i artifact types.}{ Creature subtypes are also called }{\i creature types.}{ Land subtypes are also called }{\i land types.}{ Artifacts, creatures, and lands may have multiple subtypes.\par }\pard\plain \s24\li1500\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ \ldblquote Basic Land \emdash  Mountain\rdblquote  means the card is a land with the Mountain subtype. \ldblquote Creature \emdash  Goblin Wizard\rdblquote  means the card is a creature with the subtypes Goblin and Wizard. \ldblquote Artifact \emdash  Equipment\rdblquote  means the card is an artifact with the subtype Equipment.\par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 205.3c Enchantment subtypes consist of the word \ldblquote enchant\rdblquote  and the word(s) that follows it: \ldblquote enchant creature,\rdblquote  \ldblquote enchant land,\rdblquote  etc. A card with the type \ldblquote enchantment\rdblquote  has no subtype. An enchantment\rquote s subtype specifies what the enchantment can be legally attached to. (See also rule 212.4, \ldblquote Enchantments.\rdblquote )\par \par 205.3d Instants and sorceries don\rquote t have subtypes.\par \par 205.3e If an artifact creature card has subtypes printed on its type line, those subtypes are creature types. If an artifact land card has subtypes printed on its type line, those types are land types.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 205.4. Supertypes\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {205.4a A card can also have one or more }{\i supertypes.}{ These are printed directly before the card\rquote s types. If an object\rquote s types or subtypes change, any supertypes it has are kept, although they may not be relevant to the new type.\par \par 205.4b Any land with the supertype \ldblquote basic\rdblquote  is a basic land. Any land that doesn\rquote t have this supertype is a nonbasic land.\par }\pard\plain \s24\li1500\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ Note that cards printed in sets prior to the }{\i0 Eighth Edition}{ core set didn\rquote t use the word \ldblquote basic\rdblquote  to indicate a basic land. Cards from those sets with the following names are basic lands: Forest, Island, Mountain, Plains, Swamp, Snow-Covered Forest, Snow-Covered Island, Snow-Covered Mountain, Snow-Covered Plains, and Snow-Covered Swamp.\par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 205.4c Any permanent with the supertype \ldblquote legendary\rdblquote  is subject to the rules for Legends and legendary permanents. See rule 215, \ldblquote Legends and Legendary Objects.\rdblquote \par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par }\pard\plain \s19\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {206. Expansion Symbol\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 206.1. The expansion symbol indicates which }{\b Magic}{ set a card is from. It\rquote s printed below the right edge of the illustration.\par \par 206.2. The color of the expansion symbol indicates the rarity of the card within its set. A gold symbol signifies the card is rare; silver, uncommon; and black, common or basic land. (Prior to the }{\i Exodus\u8482\'aa}{ set, all expansion symbols were black, regardless of rarity. Also, prior to the }{\i Sixth Edition}{ core set, }{\b Magic}{ core sets didn\rquote t have expansion symbols at all.)\par \par 206.3. A spell or ability that affects cards from a particular set \ldblquote looks\rdblquote  only for that set\rquote s expansion symbol. A card reprinted in the core set receives the core set\rquote s expansion symbol; any reprinted version of the card no longer counts as part of its original set unless it was reprinted with that set\rquote s expansion symbol. The first five editions of the core set had no expansion symbol.\par \par }\pard\plain \s19\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {207. Text Box\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 207.1. The text box is printed on the lower half of the card. It usually contains rules text defining the card\rquote s abilities.\par \par 207.2. The text box may also contain italicized reminder text (in parentheses), which summarizes a rule that applies to that card, and italicized flavor text, which has no game function, but like the illustration, adds artistic appeal to the game.\par \par }\pard\plain \s19\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {208. Power/Toughness\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 208.1. A creature card has two numbers separated by a slash printed on its lower right corner. The first number is the creature\rquote s power (the amount of damage it deals in combat); the second is its toughness (the amount of damage needed to destroy it). For example, 2/3 means the creature has power 2 and toughness 3. Power and toughness can be modified or set to particular values by effects.\par \par 208.2. Some objects have power and/or toughness of *, where * is a value determined by the abilities of the object. As long as the object is in play, the ability sets the value of *. The * is 0 while the object is not in play.}{\i \par }{\par }\pard\plain \s19\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {209. Illustration Credit\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 209.1. The illustration credit for a card is printed directly below the text box. The credit has no effect on game play.\par \par }\pard\plain \s19\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {210. Legal Text\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 210.1. Legal text (the fine print at the bottom of the card) lists the copyright information. It has no effect on game play.\par \par }\pard\plain \s19\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {211. Collector Number\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 211.1. Some card sets feature collector numbers. This information is printed in the form [card number]/[total cards in the set], immediately following the legal text. These numbers have no effect on game play.\par \par }\pard\plain \s19\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {212. Type, Supertype, and Subtype\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 212.1. General\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {212.1a Cards, tokens, permanents, and spells can all have types, supertypes, and subtypes. Abilities don\rquote t have types, supertypes, or subtypes. Instead, there are various categories of abilities. (See rule 402, \ldblquote Abilities.\rdblquote )\par \par 212.1b. When an object\rquote s type changes, the new type(s) replaces any existing types. Counters, effects, and damage affecting the object remain with it, even if they are meaningless to the new type. Similarly, when the subtypes of one of an object\rquote s types change, the new subtype(s) replaces any existing subtypes of that type. If an object\rquote s type is removed, the subtypes of its old type don\rquote t exist in any way under the new type. Those subtypes disappear completely for the entire time the object\rquote s type is removed. Removing an object\rquote s subtype doesn\rquote t affect its types at all.\par \par 212.1c Some effects change an object\rquote s type or subtype but specify that the object retains a prior type or subtype. In such cases, all the object\rquote s prior types and subtypes are retained. (This is a reversal of previous rules.) This rule applies to effects that use the phrase \ldblquote in addition to its types\rdblquote  or that state that something is \ldblquote still a [type].\rdblquote  Some effects state that an object becomes an \ldblquote artifact creature\rdblquote ; these effects also allow the object to retain all of its prior types and subtypes.\par }\pard\plain \s24\li1500\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ An ability reads, \ldblquote All lands are 1/1 creatures that are still lands.\rdblquote  The affected lands now have two types: creature and land. If there were any lands that also had the artifact type before the ability\rquote s effect applied to them, those lands would become \ldblquote artifact land creatures,\rdblquote  not just \ldblquote creatures,\rdblquote  or \ldblquote land creatures.\rdblquote  The effect allows them to retain both the artifact type and the land type.\par }{\b Example:}{ An ability reads, \ldblquote All artifacts are 1/1 artifact creatures.\rdblquote  If a permanent is both an artifact and an enchantment, it will become an \ldblquote artifact enchantment creature.\rdblquote \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 212.1d An object\rquote s supertype is independent of its type and subtype. Changing an object\rquote s type or subtype won\rquote t change its supertype. Changing an object\rquote s supertype won\rquote t change its type or subtype.\par }\pard\plain \s24\li1500\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ An ability reads, \ldblquote All lands are 1/1 creatures that are still lands.\rdblquote  If any of the affected lands were legendary, they are still legendary.\par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 212.1e If an instruction requires choosing a subtype, you must choose one, and only one, existing subtype, and the subtype you choose must be for the appropriate type. For example, you can\rquote t choose a land type if an instruction requires choosing a creature type. (Use the Oracle card reference to determine whether a creature type exists; see rule 200.2. You can also find a complete list of creature types in the \ldblquote Creature Types\rdblquote  entry in the glossary at the end of this document.)\par }\pard\plain \s24\li1500\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ When choosing a creature type, \ldblquote Merfolk\rdblquote  or \ldblquote Wizard\rdblquote  is acceptable, but \ldblquote Merfolk Wizard\rdblquote  is not. Words like \ldblquote artifact,\rdblquote  \ldblquote opponent,\rdblquote  \ldblquote Swamp,\rdblquote  or \ldblquote truck\rdblquote  can\rquote t be chosen because they aren\rquote t creature types.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 212.2. Artifacts\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {212.2a A player may play an artifact card from his or her hand during a main phase of his or her turn, when he or she has priority and the stack is empty. Playing an artifact as a spell uses the stack. (See rule 409, \ldblquote Playing Spells and Activated Abilities.\rdblquote )\par \par 212.2b When an artifact spell resolves, its controller puts it into play under his or her control.\par \par 212.2c Artifact subtypes are always a single word and are listed after a long dash: \ldblquote Artifact \emdash  Equipment.\rdblquote  Artifact subtypes are also called }{\i artifact types.}{ Artifacts may have multiple subtypes.\par \par 212.2d Artifacts have no characteristics specific to their type. Because artifacts have no colored mana in their mana costs, they\rquote re colorless. Effects can give artifacts one or more colors, however, and colored objects can become artifacts without losing any colors they had.\par \par 212.2e Artifact creatures combine the characteristics of both the creature and artifact types and are subject to spells and abilities that affect either or both types.\par \par 212.2f Artifact lands combine the characteristics of both the land and artifact types, and are subject to spells and abilities that affect either or both types. Artifact lands can only be played as lands. They can\rquote t be played as spells.\par \par 212.2g Some artifacts have the subtype \ldblquote Equipment.\rdblquote  An Equipment can be attached to a creature. It can\rquote t legally be attached to an object that isn\rquote t a creature.\par \par 212.2h An Equipment is played and comes into play just like any other artifact. An Equipment doesn\rquote t come into play attached to a creature. The equip keyword ability moves the Equipment onto a creature you control (see rule 502.33, \ldblquote Equip\rdblquote ). Control of the creature matters only when the equip ability is played and resolved.\par \par 212.2i An Equipment that\rquote s also a creature can\rquote t equip a creature. Equipment that loses the subtype \ldblquote Equipment\rdblquote  can\rquote t equip a creature. An Equipment can\rquote t equip itself. An Equipment that equips an illegal or nonexistent permanent stops equipping that permanent, but remains in play. (This is a state-based effect. See rule 420.)\par \par 212.2j The creature an Equipment is attached to is called the \ldblquote equipped creature.\rdblquote  The Equipment is attached to, or \ldblquote equips,\rdblquote  that creature.\par \par 212.2k An Equipment\rquote s controller is separate from the equipped creature\rquote s controller; the two need not be the same. Changing control of the creature doesn\rquote t change control of the Equipment, and vice versa. Only the Equipment\rquote s controller can play its abilities. However, if the Equipment adds an ability to the equipped creature (with \ldblquote gains\rdblquote  or \ldblquote has\rdblquote ), the equipped creature\rquote s controller is the only one who can play that ability.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 212.3. Creatures\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {212.3a A player may play a creature card from his or her hand during a main phase of his or her turn, when he or she has priority and the stack is empty. Playing a creature as a spell uses the stack. (See rule 409, \ldblquote Playing Spells and Activated Abilities.\rdblquote )\par \par 212.3b When a creature spell resolves, its controller puts it into play under his or her control.\par \par 212.3c Creature subtypes are always a single word and are listed after a long dash: \ldblquote Creature \emdash  Minotaur,\rdblquote  \ldblquote Artifact Creature \emdash  Golem Legend,\rdblquote  etc. Creature subtypes are also called creature types. Creatures may have multiple subtypes.\par }\pard\plain \s24\li1500\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ \ldblquote Creature \emdash  Goblin Wizard\rdblquote  means the card is a creature with the subtypes Goblin and Wizard.\par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 212.3d A creature\rquote s activated ability with the tap symbol in its activation cost can\rquote t be played unless the creature has been under its controller\rquote s control since the start of his or her most recent turn. A creature can\rquote t attack unless it has been under its controller\rquote s control since the start of his or her most recent turn. This rule is informally called the \ldblquote summoning sickness\rdblquote  rule. Ignore this rule for creatures with haste (see rule 502.5).\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 212.4. Enchantments\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {212.4a A player may play an enchantment card from his or her hand during a main phase of his or her turn, when he or she has priority and the stack is empty. Playing an enchantment as a spell uses the stack. (See rule 409, \ldblquote Playing Spells and Activated Abilities.\rdblquote )\par \par 212.4b When an enchantment spell resolves, its controller puts it into play under his or her control.\par \par 212.4c A global enchantment simply has \ldblquote enchantment\rdblquote  as its type. Local enchantments use the word \ldblquote enchant,\rdblquote  followed by what it can enchant. Examples of enchantment subtypes include enchant artifact, enchant artifact creature, enchant creature, enchant permanent, enchant player, and enchant Swamp. If a local enchantment\rquote s subtype includes more than one word after \ldblquote enchant,\rdblquote  the enchanted permanent must match each of those words.}{\cf6 \par }{\par 212.4d A local-enchantment spell requires a target whose properties are indicated by the enchantment\rquote s subtype. The local-enchantment permanent the spell puts into play can only enchant that type of permanent or player and comes into play attached to the permanent or player the spell targeted. Any additional restrictions on what it can enchant are indicated by phrases like \ldblquote [This local enchantment] can enchant only a [permanent or player with specified properties].\rdblquote  These restrictions also limit what the local-enchantment spell can target. Similar restrictions can limit what a permanent can be enchanted by. For example, a permanent might have an ability that reads \ldblquote [This permanent] can\rquote t be enchanted by [local enchantments with specified properties].\rdblquote  These restrictions limit whether local-enchantment spells can target the permanent.\par }\pard\plain \s24\li1500\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ An enchant creature spell requires a target creature; an enchant creature in play must enchant a creature.\par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 212.4e If a local enchantment is coming into play by any other means than being played, and the effect putting it into play doesn\rquote t specify what it will enchant, the player putting it into play chooses a permanent or player for it to enchant as it comes into play. In this case, the enchantment doesn\rquote t target the permanent, but the player who is putting it into play still must choose a permanent or player that the enchantment can enchant. If no legal permanent or player is available, the enchantment remains in the zone from which it attempted to move instead of coming into play. The same rule applies to moving a local enchantment from one permanent to another or from one player to another. The permanent or player to which the enchantment is to be moved must be able to be enchanted by it. If it isn\rquote t legal, the enchantment doesn\rquote t move.\par \par 212.4f If a local enchantment is enchanting an illegal permanent or player, or the permanent or player it was attached to no longer exists, the enchantment is put into its owner\rquote s graveyard. (This is a state-based effect. See rule 420.)\par \par 212.4g A local enchantment can\rquote t be attached to itself, and a local enchantment that\rquote s also a creature can\rquote t be attached to another object. If this occurs somehow, the local enchantment is put into its owner\rquote s graveyard. (This is a state-based effect. See rule 420.)\par \par 212.4h The permanent or player a local enchantment is attached to is called }{\i enchanted.}{ The enchantment \ldblquote enchants\rdblquote  or, in more casual terms, \ldblquote is attached to\rdblquote  that permanent.\par \par 212.4i A local enchantment\rquote s controller is separate from the enchanted permanent\rquote s controller; the two need not be the same. Changing control of the permanent doesn\rquote t change control of the enchantment, and vice versa. Only the enchantment\rquote s controller can play its abilities. However, if the enchantment adds an ability to the enchanted permanent (with \ldblquote gains\rdblquote  or \ldblquote has\rdblquote ), that enchanted permanent\rquote s controller is the only one who can play that ability.\par \par 212.4j An object that is an \ldblquote enchant world\rdblquote  is a global enchantment. It\rquote s subject to the state-based effect for enchant worlds. (See rule 420.5i.)\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 212.5. Instants\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {212.5a A player may play an instant card from his or her hand any time he or she has priority. Playing an instant as a spell uses the stack. (See rule 409, \ldblquote Playing Spells and Activated Abilities.\rdblquote )\par \par 212.5b When an instant spell resolves, the actions stated in its rules text are followed. Then it\rquote s put into its owner\rquote s graveyard.\par \par 212.5c Instants have no subtypes.\par \par 212.5d Instants can\rquote t come into play. If an instant would come into play, it remains in its previous zone instead.\par \par 212.5e If text states that a player may do something \ldblquote any time he or she could play an instant,\rdblquote  it means only that the player must have priority. The player doesn\rquote t need to have an instant he or she could actually play.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 212.6. Land\par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 212.6a A player may play a land card from his or her hand only during a main phase of his or her turn, and only when he or she has priority and the stack is empty. A land card isn\rquote t a spell card, and at no time is it a spell. When a player plays a land card, it\rquote s simply put into play. The land card doesn't go on the stack, so players can\rquote t respond to it with instants or activated abilities.}{\cf6 \par }{\par 212.6b}{\cf6  }{A player may play only one land card during each of his or her own turns. Effects may allow the playing of additional lands; playing an additional land in this way doesn\rquote t prevent a player from taking the normal action of playing a land. Players can\rquote t begin to play a land that an effect prohibits from being played. As a player plays a land, he or she announces whether he or she is using the once-per-turn action of playing a land. If not, he or she specifies which effect is allowing the additional land play. Effects may also allow you to \ldblquote put\rdblquote  lands into play. This isn\rquote t the same as \ldblquote playing a land\rdblquote  and doesn\rquote t count as the player\rquote s one land played during his or her turn.}{\cf6 \par }{\par 212.6c}{\cf6  }{Land subtypes are always a single word and are listed after a long dash. Land subtypes are also called }{\i land types.}{ Lands may have multiple subtypes.\par }\pard\plain \s24\li1500\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ \ldblquote Basic Land \endash  Mountain\rdblquote  means the card is a land with the Mountain subtype.\par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 212.6d The basic land types are Plains, Island, Swamp, Mountain, and Forest. If an object uses the words \ldblquote basic land type,\rdblquote  it\rquote s referring to one of these subtypes. A land with a basic land type has an intrinsic ability to produce colored mana. (See rule 406, \ldblquote Mana Abilities.\rdblquote ) The land is treated as if its text box included, \ldblquote \{oT\}: Add [mana symbol] to your mana pool,\rdblquote  even if the text box doesn\rquote t actually contain text. Plains produce white mana; Islands, blue; Swamps, black; Mountains, red; and Forests, green.}{\cf6 \par }{\par 212.6e If an effect changes a land\rquote s type to one or more of the basic land types, the land no longer has its old land type. It loses any rules text it had in its text box, other than the rules text for the snow-covered ability, and it gains the rules text for the appropriate mana ability for each of its basic land types. Note that this doesn\rquote t remove any abilities that were granted to the land by other effects. Changing a land\rquote s type doesn\rquote t add or remove any types (such as creature) or supertypes (such as basic and legendary) the land may have. If a land gains one or more land types in addition to its own, it keeps its land types and rules text, and it gains the new land types and mana abilities.\par \par 212.6f}{\cf6  }{Any land with the supertype \ldblquote basic\rdblquote  is a basic land. Any land that doesn\rquote t have this supertype is a nonbasic land.\par \par 212.6g If an object is both a land and another type, it can be played only as a land. It can\rquote t be played as a spell.}{\cf6 \par }{\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {212.7. Sorceries\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {212.7a A player may play a sorcery card from his or her hand during a main phase of his or her turn, when he or she has priority and the stack is empty. Playing a sorcery as a spell uses the stack. (See rule 409, \ldblquote Playing Spells and Activated Abilities.\rdblquote )\par \par 212.7b When a sorcery spell resolves, the actions stated in its rules text are followed. Then it\rquote s put into its owner\rquote s graveyard.\par \par 212.7c Sorceries have no subtypes.\par \par 212.7d Sorceries can\rquote t come into play. If a sorcery would come into play, it remains in its previous zone instead.\par \par 212.7e If a spell, ability, or effect states that a player can do something only \ldblquote any time he or she could play an sorcery,\rdblquote  it means only that the player must have priority, it must be during the main phase of his or her turn, and the stack must be empty. The player doesn\rquote t need to have an sorcery he or she could actually play.\par }\pard\plain \s20\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par }\pard\plain \s19\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {213. Spells\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 213.1. Every nonland card is a spell while it\rquote s being played (see rule 409, \ldblquote Playing Spells and Activated Abilities\rdblquote ) and while it\rquote s on the stack. Once it\rquote s played, a card remains a spell until it resolves, is countered, or otherwise leaves the stack. For more information, see rule 401, \ldblquote Spells on the Stack.\rdblquote \par \par 213.2. }{\i Spell type}{ is the type of a spell on the stack. A spell\rquote s type, supertype, and subtype are the same as those of its card.\par \par 213.3. The term \ldblquote spell\rdblquote  is used to refer to a card while it\rquote s on the stack. The term \ldblquote card\rdblquote  isn\rquote t used to refer to a card that\rquote s on the stack as a spell. It\rquote s only used to refer to a card that\rquote s not in play or on the stack, such as a creature card in a player\rquote s hand.\par \par 213.4. Every spell has a controller. By default, a spell\rquote s controller is the player who played it.\par \par 213.5. If an effect changes any characteristics of a spell that becomes a permanent, the effect continues to apply to the permanent when the spell resolves.\par }\pard\plain \s23\li1200\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ If an effect changes a black creature spell to white, the creature is white when it comes into play and remains white for the duration of the effect changing its color.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par }\pard\plain \s19\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {214. Permanents\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 214.1. A permanent is a card or token in play. Permanents stay in play unless moved to another zone by an effect or rule. There are four types of permanents: artifacts, creatures, enchantments, and lands. Instant and sorcery cards can\rquote t come into play.\par \par 214.2. }{\i Permanent type}{ is the type of a card or token that\rquote s in play. A nontoken permanent\rquote s types, supertypes, and subtypes are the same as those printed on its card. A token\rquote s types, supertypes, and subtypes are set by the spell or ability that created it.\par \par 214.3. A card or token becomes a permanent when it comes into play and it stops being a permanent when it leaves play. Permanents come into play untapped. The term \ldblquote permanent\rdblquote  is used to refer to a card or token while it\rquote s in play. The term \ldblquote card\rdblquote  isn\rquote t used to refer to a card that\rquote s in play as a permanent. It\rquote s only used to refer to a card that\rquote s not in play and not on the stack, such as a creature card in a player\rquote s hand. For more information, see rule 217, \ldblquote Zones.\rdblquote \par \par 214.4. Every permanent has a controller and is either tapped or untapped. By default, a permanent\rquote s controller is the player who put it into play.\par }\pard \s20\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\par }\pard\plain \s19\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {215. Legends and Legendary Objects\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 215.1. The word Legend or legendary may appear as an object\rquote s subtype or supertype. Permanents with the subtype Legend or the supertype legendary are subject to the Legend rule (see rule 420, \ldblquote State-Based Effects\rdblquote ) as well as any other rules for their types, subtypes, and supertypes.\par \par 215.2. Legend is a creature type; legendary is not. If a legendary noncreature permanent becomes a creature, it\rquote s still legendary, but it doesn\rquote t get the creature type Legend. If a creature of type Legend becomes a noncreature permanent, it loses the creature type Legend, but it doesn\rquote t become legendary.\par \par }\pard\plain \s19\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {216. Tokens\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 216.1. Some effects put token creatures into play. A token is controlled by whomever put it into play and owned by the controller of the spell or ability that created it. The spell or ability may define any number of characteristics for the token. A token doesn\rquote t have any characteristics not defined by the spell or ability that created it. The spell or ability that creates the token sets both its name and creature type at the same time. A \ldblquote Goblin creature token,\rdblquote  for example, is named \ldblquote Goblin\rdblquote  and has the creature subtype Goblin. If a token\rquote s name is two words or more, it has the creature subtype for each of those words. For example, a \ldblquote Goblin Scout creature token\rdblquote  is named \ldblquote Goblin Scout\rdblquote  and has two creature subtypes: Goblin and Scout. Once a token is in play, changing its name doesn\rquote t change its creature type, and vice versa.\par \par 216.2. A token is subject to anything that affects permanents in general or that affects the token\rquote s type or subtype. A token isn\rquote t a card (even if represented by cards from other games or }{\i Unglued}{ cards).\par \par 216.3. A token in a zone other than the in-play zone ceases to exist. This is a state-based effect. (Note that a token changing zones will set off triggered abilities before the token ceases to exist.) Once a token has left play, it can\rquote t be returned to play by any means.\par \par }\pard\plain \s19\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {217. Zones\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 217.1. A zone is a place where objects can be during a game. There are normally six zones: library, hand, graveyard, in play, stack, and removed from the game. Some older cards also use the ante and phased-out zones. Each player has his or her own library, hand, and graveyard. The other zones are shared by all players.\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {217.1a If an object would go to any library, graveyard, or hand other than its owner\rquote s, it goes to the corresponding zone of its owner\rquote s instead. If an instant or sorcery card would come into play, it remains in its previous zone instead.\par \par 217.1b The order of objects in a library, in a graveyard, or on the stack can\rquote t be changed except when effects or rules allow it. Objects in other zones can be arranged however their owners wish, although who controls those objects, whether they\rquote re tapped, and what enchants or equips them must remain clear to both players.\par \par 217.1c An object that moves from one zone to another is treated as a new object. Effects connected with its previous location will no longer affect it. There are two exceptions to this rule: Effects that edit the characteristics of an artifact, creature, or enchantment spell on the stack will continue to apply to the permanent that spell creates, and abilities that trigger when an object moves from one zone to another (for example, \ldblquote When Rancor is put into a graveyard from play\rdblquote ) can find the object in the zone it moved to when the ability triggered.\par \par 217.1d If an object would move from one zone to another, first determine what event is moving the object. Then apply any appropriate replacement effects to that event. If an effect or rule tries to do two or more contradictory or mutually exclusive things to a particular object, that object\rquote s controller\emdash or its owner if it has no controller\emdash chooses what the effect does to the object. Then the event moves the object.\par \par 217.1e An object is }{\i outside the game}{ if it\rquote s in the removed-from-the-game zone, or if it isn\rquote t in any of the game\rquote s zones. All other objects are inside the game. Outside the game is not a zone.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 217.2. Library\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {217.2a When a game begins, each player\rquote s deck becomes his or her library.\par \par 217.2b Each library must be kept in a single face-down pile. Players can\rquote t look at or change the order of cards in a library.\par \par 217.2c Any player may count the number of cards remaining in either player\rquote s library at any time.\par \par 217.2d If an effect puts two or more cards on the top or bottom of a library at the same time, the owner of those cards may arrange them in any order. That library\rquote s owner doesn\rquote t reveal the order in which the cards go into his or her library.\par \par 217.2e Some effects tell a player to play with the top card of his or her library revealed. If the top card of the player\rquote s library changes while a spell or ability is being played, the new top card won\rquote t be revealed until the spell or ability becomes played (see rule 409.1i).\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 217.3. Hand\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {217.3a The hand is where a player holds cards that have been drawn but not yet played. At the beginning of the game, each player draws a hand of seven cards. (See rule 101, \ldblquote Starting the Game.\rdblquote )\par \par 217.3b Each player has a maximum hand size, which is normally seven cards. A player may have any number of cards in his or her hand, but as part of his or her cleanup step, the player must discard excess cards down to the maximum hand size.\par \par 217.3c A player may arrange his or her hand in any convenient fashion and look at it as much as he or she wishes. A player can\rquote t look at the cards in another player\rquote s hand but may count those cards at any time.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 217.4. Graveyard\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {217.4a A graveyard is a discard pile. Any object that\rquote s countered, discarded, destroyed, or sacrificed is put on top of its owner\rquote s graveyard, as is any instant or sorcery spell that\rquote s finished resolving. Each player\rquote s graveyard starts out empty.\par \par 217.4b Each graveyard is kept in a single face-up pile. A player can examine the cards in any graveyard at any time but can\rquote t change their order.\par \par 217.4c If an effect or rule puts two or more cards into the same graveyard at the same time, the owner of those cards may arrange them in any order.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 217.5. In Play\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {217.5a Most of the area between the players represents the in-play zone. The in-play zone starts out empty. Permanents a player controls (other than local enchantments enchanting the other player\rquote s permanents) are kept in front of him or her in the in-play zone.\par \par 217.5b A spell or ability affects and checks only the in-play zone unless it specifically mentions a player or another zone. Permanents exist only in the in-play zone.\par \par 217.5c Whenever a permanent enters the in-play zone, it\rquote s considered a brand-new permanent and has no relationship to any previous permanent represented by the same object. This is also true for any objects entering any zone (see rule 217.1c).\par \par 217.5d An object not in the in-play zone isn\rquote t \ldblquote in play\rdblquote  and isn\rquote t considered tapped or untapped. Objects that aren\rquote t either in play or on the stack aren\rquote t controlled by either player.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 217.6. Stack\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {217.6a When a spell is played, the physical card is put on the stack. When an ability is played, it goes on top of the stack without any card associated with it. (See rule 409.1, \ldblquote Playing Spells and Activated Abilities.\rdblquote )\par \par 217.6b The stack keeps track of the order that spells and/or abilities were added to it. Each time an object is put on the stack, it is put on top of all objects already there. (See rule 408, \ldblquote Timing of Spells and Abilities.\rdblquote )\par \par 217.6c Each spell has all the characteristics of the card associated with it. Each activated or triggered ability that\rquote s on the stack has the text of the ability that created it and no other characteristics. The controller of a spell is the person who played the spell. The controller of an activated ability is the player who played the ability. The controller of a triggered ability is the player who controlled the ability\rquote s source when it triggered.\par \par 217.6d When both players pass in succession, the top (last-added) spell or ability on the stack resolves. If the stack is empty when both players pass, the current step or phase ends and the next begins.\par \par 217.6e Combat damage also uses the stack, in the same way as other objects that use the stack.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 217.7. Removed from the Game\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {217.7a Effects can remove objects from the game. Some effects may provide a way for a card to return to a zone and use the term \ldblquote set aside.\rdblquote  Cards that are set aside this way are still removed from the game, even though that removal may be temporary. Objects that aren\rquote t cards can\rquote t be returned in any way.\par \par 217.7b Cards in the removed-from-the-game zone are kept face up and may be examined by either player at any time. Cards \ldblquote removed from the game face down\rdblquote  can\rquote t be examined by either player except when instructions allow it.\par \par 217.7c Cards that might return to play should be kept in separate piles to keep track of their respective ways of returning.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 217.8. Phased-Out\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {217.8a Permanents that phase out are placed in the phased-out zone. (See rule 502.15, \ldblquote Phasing.\rdblquote )\par \par 217.8b Face-up objects in the phased-out zone may be examined by either player at any time. Face-down objects in the phased-out zone are covered by the rules for face-down creatures. (See rule 502.26, \ldblquote Morph,\rdblquote  and rule 504, \ldblquote Face-Down Spells and Permanents.\rdblquote )\par \par 217.8c Phased-out objects are not in play, so they do not count as tapped or untapped, nor are they controlled by anyone. However, an object in this zone \ldblquote remembers\rdblquote  the state of the permanent as it phased out and returns to play in the same state as when it left. (See rule 502.15, \ldblquote Phasing.\rdblquote ) This is an exception to rule 217.1c.\par  \par 217.8d Tokens in the phased-out zone cease to exist. This is a state-based effect (see rule 420, \ldblquote State-Based Effects\rdblquote ). Any phased-out local enchantments or Equipment that were attached to those tokens remain phased out for the rest of the game.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 217.9. Ante\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {217.9a Earlier versions of the }{\b Magic}{ rules included an ante rule as a way of playing \ldblquote for keeps.\rdblquote  Playing }{\b Magic}{ games for ante is now considered an optional variation on the game, and it\rquote s allowed only where it\rquote s not forbidden by law or by other rules. Playing for ante is strictly forbidden under the DCI Universal Tournament Rules (}{\field\fldedit{\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK "http://www.wizards.com/default.asp?x=dci/utr/intro"}{{\*\datafield 00d0c9ea79f9bace118c8200aa004ba90b0200000003000000e0c9ea79f9bace118c8200aa004ba90b6600000068007400740070003a002f002f007700770077002e00770069007a0061007200640073002e0063006f006d002f00640065006600610075006c0074002e006100730070003f0078003d006400630069002f007500740072002f0069006e00740072006f000000}}}{\fldrslt {\cs22\ul\cf2 www.wizards.com/default{\*\bkmkstart _Hlt51483318}.{\*\bkmkend _Hlt51483318}asp?{\*\bkmkstart _Hlt43634296}x{\*\bkmkend _Hlt43634296}=dci{\*\bkmkstart _Hlt50881100}/{\*\bkmkend _Hlt50881100}utr/intro}}}{).\par \par 217.9b When playing for ante, each player puts one random card from his or her deck into the ante zone at the beginning of the game. Cards in the ante zone may be examined by either player at any time. At the end of the game, the winner becomes the owner of all the cards in the ante zone.\par \par 217.9c A few cards have the text \ldblquote Remove [this card] from your deck before playing if you\rquote re not playing for ante.\rdblquote  These are the only cards that can add or remove cards from a player\rquote s ante zone or change a card\rquote s owner.\par \par 217.9d To }{\i ante}{ an object is to put that object into the ante zone from whichever zone it\rquote s currently in. The owner of an object is the only person who can ante that object.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par }\pard\plain \s17\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\f4\lang1033\cgrid {\page 3. Turn Structure\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par }\pard\plain \s19\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {300. General\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 300.1. A turn consists of five phases, in this order: beginning, precombat main, combat, postcombat main, and end. Each of these phases takes place every turn, even if nothing happens during the phase. The beginning, combat, and end phases are further broken down into steps, which proceed in order.\par \par 300.2. A phase or step ends when the stack is empty and both players pass in succession. No game events can occur between turns, phases, or steps. Simply having the stack become empty doesn\rquote t cause the phase or step to end; both players have to pass with the stack empty. Because of this, each player always gets a chance to add new things to the stack before the current phase or step ends.\par \par 300.3. When a phase ends (but not a step), any unused mana left in a player\rquote s mana pool is lost. That player loses 1 life for each one mana lost this way. This is called mana burn. Note that mana burn is loss of life, not damage, so it can\rquote t be prevented or altered by effects that affect damage. This game action doesn\rquote t use the stack. (See rule 406, \ldblquote Mana Abilities.\rdblquote )\par \par 300.4. When a phase or step ends, any effects scheduled to last \ldblquote until end of\rdblquote  that phase or step expire. When a phase or step begins, any effects scheduled to last \ldblquote until\rdblquote  that phase or step expire. Effects that last \ldblquote until end of combat\rdblquote  expire at the end of the combat phase, not at the beginning of the end of combat step. Effects that last \ldblquote until end of turn\rdblquote  are subject to special rules; see rule 314.2.\par \par 300.5. When a phase or step begins, any abilities that trigger \ldblquote at the beginning of\rdblquote  that phase or step are added to the stack.\par \par 300.6. Some effects can give a player extra turns. They do this by adding the turns directly after the current turn. If a player gets multiple extra turns or if both players get extra turns during a single turn, the extra turns are added one at a time. The most recently created turn will be taken first.\par \par 300.7. Some effects can add phases to a turn. They do this by adding the phases directly after the specified phase. If multiple extra phases are created after the same phase, the most recently created phase will occur first.\par \par 300.8. Some effects can add steps to a phase. They do this by adding the steps directly after a specified step (or directly before a specified step). If multiple extra steps are created after the same step, the most recently created step will occur first.\par \par 300.9. Some effects can cause a step, phase, or turn to be skipped. To skip a step, phase, or turn is to proceed past it as though it didn\rquote t exist. See rule 419.6e and rule 419.6f.\par \par }\pard\plain \s19\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {301. Beginning Phase\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 301.1. The beginning phase consists of three steps, in this order: untap, upkeep, and draw.\par \par }\pard\plain \s19\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {302. Untap Step\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 302.1 First, all permanents with phasing that the active player controls phase out, and all phased-out objects that the active player controlled when they phased out simultaneously phase in (this game action doesn\rquote t use the stack). See rule 217.8, \ldblquote Phased-Out,\rdblquote  and rule 502.15, \ldblquote Phasing.\rdblquote \par \par 302.2. Next the active player determines which permanents he or she controls will untap. Then he or she untaps them all simultaneously (this game action doesn\rquote t use the stack). Normally, all of a player\rquote s permanents untap, but effects can keep one or more of a player\rquote s permanents from untapping.\par \par 302.3. No player receives priority during the untap step, so no spells or abilities can be played or resolved. Any ability that triggers during this step will be held until a player would receive priority during the upkeep step. (See rule 303, \ldblquote Upkeep Step.\rdblquote )\par \par }\pard\plain \s19\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {303. Upkeep Step\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 303.1. As the upkeep step begins, any abilities that trigger at the beginning of that upkeep step and any abilities that triggered during the turn\rquote s untap step go on the stack. (See rule 410, \ldblquote Handling Triggered Abilities.\rdblquote ) Then the active player gets priority and players may play spells and abilities.\par \par }\pard\plain \s19\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {304. Draw Step\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 304.1 First, the active player draws a card. This special action doesn\rquote t use the stack. (This is a reversal of previous rules.) Then any abilities that trigger at the beginning of the draw step and any other abilities that have triggered go on the stack. Then the active player gets priority and players may play spells and abilities.\par \par }\pard\plain \s19\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {305. Main Phase\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 305.1. There are two main phases in a turn. In each turn, the first main phase, known as the precombat main phase, and the second main phase, known as the postcombat main phase, are separated by the combat phase (see rule 306, \ldblquote Combat Phase\rdblquote ). The precombat and postcombat main phases are individually and collectively known as the }{\i main phase.}{\par \par 305.2. The main phase has no steps, so a main phase ends when both players pass in succession while the stack is empty.\par \par 305.3. As the main phase begins, any abilities that trigger at the beginning of that main phase go on the stack. (See rule 410, \ldblquote Handling Triggered Abilities.\rdblquote ) Then the active player gets priority and players may play spells and abilities. (This is the only phase in which a player can normally play artifact, creature, enchantment, and sorcery spells, and only the active player may play these spells.)\par \par 305.4. During either main phase, the active player may play one land card from his or her hand if the stack is empty, if the player has priority, and if he or she hasn\rquote t yet taken this special action this turn. (See rule 212.6, \ldblquote Lands.\rdblquote ) This action doesn\rquote t use the stack and it isn\rquote t a spell or ability of any kind. It can\rquote t be countered, and players can\rquote t respond to it with instants or activated abilities.\par \par }\pard\plain \s19\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {306. Combat Phase\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 306.1. The combat phase has five steps, which proceed in order: beginning of combat, declare attackers, declare blockers, combat damage, and end of combat. The declare blockers and combat damage steps are skipped if no creatures are declared as attackers (see rule 308.4). There are two combat damage steps if any attacking or blocking creature has first strike (see rule 502.2) or double strike (see rule 502.28).\par \par 306.2. A creature is removed from combat if it leaves play (such as by being destroyed or removed from the game), if it regenerates (see rule 419.6b), if its controller changes, if it stops being a creature, or if an effect removes it from combat. }{\i Removed from combat}{ means the creature stops being an attacking, blocking, blocked, and/or unblocked creature.\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {306.2a Once a creature has been declared as an attacking or blocking creature, spells or abilities that would have kept that creature from attacking or blocking don\rquote t remove the creature from combat.\par \par 306.2b Tapping or untapping a creature that\rquote s already been declared as an attacker or blocker doesn\rquote t remove it from combat and doesn\rquote t prevent its combat damage.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 306.3. During the combat phase, the active player is }{\i attacking}{ and is the }{\i attacking player.}{ The nonactive player is }{\i being attacked}{ and is the }{\i defending player.}{\par \par 306.4. An attacking creature is }{\i attacking alone}{ if no other creatures are attacking. A blocking creature is }{\i blocking alone}{ if no other creatures are blocking.\par \par }\pard\plain \s19\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {307. Beginning of Combat Step\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 307.1. As the beginning of combat step begins, any abilities that trigger at the beginning of combat go on the stack. (See rule 410, \ldblquote Handling Triggered Abilities.\rdblquote ) Then the active player gets priority and players may play spells and abilities.\par \par }\pard\plain \s19\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {308. Declare Attackers Step\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 308.1. As the declare attackers step begins, the active player declares attackers (this game action doesn\rquote t use the stack). Then any abilities that triggered on attackers being declared go on the stack. (See rule 410, \ldblquote Handling Triggered Abilities.\rdblquote ) Then the active player gets priority and players may play spells and abilities.\par \par 308.2. To declare attackers, the active player follows the steps below, in order. If at any point during the declaration of attackers, the active player is unable to comply with any of the steps listed below, the declaration was illegal; the game returns to the moment before the declaration (see rule 422, \ldblquote Handling Illegal Actions,\rdblquote  and rule 500, \ldblquote Legal Attacks and Blocks\rdblquote ).\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {308.2a The active player either chooses to not attack, or chooses one or more creatures he or she controls and then determines whether this set of creatures could attack. Only creatures can attack, and the following creatures can\rquote t attack: tapped creatures (even those that can attack without tapping), creatures with creature type Wall, and creatures the active player didn\rquote t control continuously since the beginning of the turn (except those with haste). Other effects may also affect whether or not a set of creatures could attack. (See rule 500, \ldblquote Legal Attacks and Blocks.\rdblquote )\par \par 308.2b If any of the chosen creatures have banding or a }{\i bands with other}{ ability, the active player announces which creatures, if any, are banded with which. (See rule 502.10, \ldblquote Banding.\rdblquote )\par \par 308.2c The active player taps the chosen creatures. Tapping a creature when it\rquote s declared as an attacker isn\rquote t a cost; attacking simply causes creatures to become tapped.\par \par 308.2d If any of the creatures require paying costs to attack, the active player determines the total cost to attack. Costs may include paying mana, tapping permanents, sacrificing permanents, discarding cards, and so on. Once the total cost is determined, it becomes \ldblquote locked in.\rdblquote  If effects would change the total cost after this time, ignore this change.\par \par 308.2e If any of the costs require mana, the active player then has a chance to play mana abilities (see rule 411, \ldblquote Playing Mana Abilities\rdblquote ).\par \par 308.2f Once the player has enough mana in his or her mana pool, he or she pays all costs in any order. Partial payments are not allowed.\par \par 308.2g Each chosen creature becomes an attacking creature if all costs have been paid, but only if it\rquote s still controlled by the active player. It remains an attacking creature until it\rquote s removed from combat or the combat phase ends, whichever comes first. See rule 306.2.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 308.3. Abilities that trigger on a creature attacking trigger only at the point the creature starts to attack. They will not trigger if a creature attacks and the characteristics of that creature are then changed to match the ability\rquote s trigger condition.\par }\pard\plain \s23\li1200\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ A permanent has the ability \ldblquote Whenever a green creature attacks, destroy that creature at end of combat.\rdblquote  If a blue creature attacks and is later turned green, the ability will not trigger.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 308.4. If no creatures are declared as attackers, finish the declare attackers step, but skip the declare blockers and combat damage steps.\par \par }\pard\plain \s19\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {309. Declare Blockers Step\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 309.1. As the declare blockers step begins, the defending player declares blockers (this game action doesn\rquote t use the stack). Then any abilities that triggered on blockers being declared go on the stack. (See rule 410, \ldblquote Handling Triggered Abilities.\rdblquote ) Then the active player gets priority and players may play spells and abilities.\par \par 309.2. To declare blockers, the defending player follows the steps below, in order. If at any point during the declaration of blockers, the defending player is unable to comply with any of the steps listed below, the declaration was illegal; the game returns to the moment before the declaration (see rule 422, \ldblquote Handling Illegal Actions,\rdblquote  and rule 500, \ldblquote Legal Attacks and Blocks\rdblquote ).\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {309.2a The defending player chooses zero or more creatures he or she controls, chooses one attacking creature for each one to block, then determines whether this set of blocks is legal. Only untapped creatures can block, but blocking does not cause creatures to tap. Other effects may also affect whether or not a set of creatures could block. (See rule 500, \ldblquote Legal Attacks and Blocks.\rdblquote )\par \par 309.2b If any of the creatures require paying costs to block, the defending player determines the total cost to block. Costs may include paying mana, tapping permanents, sacrificing permanents, discarding cards, and so on. Once the total cost is determined, it becomes \ldblquote locked in.\rdblquote  If effects would change the total cost after this time, ignore this change.\par \par 309.2c If any of the costs require mana, the defending player then has a chance to play mana abilities (see rule 411, \ldblquote Playing Mana Abilities\rdblquote ).\par \par 309.2d Once the player has enough mana in his or her mana pool, he or she pays all costs in any order. Partial payments are not allowed.\par \par 309.2e Each chosen creature becomes a blocking creature, but only if it\rquote s controlled by the defending player. Each one is blocking the attacking creature chosen for it. It remains a blocking creature until it\rquote s removed from combat or the combat phase ends, whichever comes first. See rule 306.2.\par \par 309.2f An attacking creature with one or more creatures declared as blockers for it becomes a blocked creature; one with no blockers becomes an unblocked creature. The creature\rquote s status remains unchanged until the creature is removed from combat or the combat phase ends, whichever comes first. (Some effects can change a creature\rquote s status.)\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 309.3. Abilities that trigger on a creature blocking or becoming blocked trigger only at the point the creature blocks or becomes blocked. They will not trigger if a creature blocks or becomes blocked, and then the characteristics of that creature are changed to match the ability\rquote s trigger condition.\par }\pard\plain \s23\li1200\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ A creature has the ability \ldblquote Whenever this creature becomes blocked by a white creature, destroy that creature at end of combat.\rdblquote  If that creature is blocked by a black creature that is later turned white, the ability will not trigger.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par }\pard\plain \s19\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {310. Combat Damage Step\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 310.1. As the combat damage step begins, the active player announces how each attacking creature will assign its combat damage. Then the defending player announces how each blocking creature will assign its combat damage. All assignments of combat damage go on the stack as a single object. Then any abilities that triggered on damage being assigned go on the stack. (See rule 410, \ldblquote Handling Triggered Abilities.\rdblquote ) Then the active player gets priority and players may play spells and abilities.\par \par 310.2. A player may divide a creature\rquote s combat damage as he or she chooses among the legal recipients. Dividing combat damage is subject to the following restrictions:\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {310.2a Each attacking creature and each blocking creature will assign combat damage equal to its power. Creatures with 0 or less power don\rquote t assign combat damage.\par \par 310.2b An unblocked attacking creature will assign all its combat damage to the defending player.\par \par 310.2c A blocked creature will assign combat damage, divided as its controller chooses, to the creatures blocking it. If no creatures are currently blocking it (if, for example, they were destroyed or removed from combat), it will assign no combat damage.\par 310.2d A blocking creature will assign combat damage, divided as its controller chooses, to the attacking creatures it\rquote s blocking. If it isn\rquote t currently blocking any creatures (if, for example, they were destroyed or removed from combat), it will assign no combat damage.\par \par 310.2e An effect that states a creature deals its combat damage in a different manner than normal affects the assignment of combat damage.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 310.3. Although combat-damage assignments go on the stack as an object, they aren\rquote t spells or abilities, so they can\rquote t be countered.\par \par 310.4. Combat damage resolves as an object on the stack. When it resolves, it\rquote s all dealt at once, as originally assigned. After combat damage finishes resolving, the active player gets priority.\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {310.4a Combat damage is dealt as it was originally assigned even if the creature dealing damage is no longer in play, its power has changed, or the creature receiving damage has left combat.\par \par 310.4b The source of the combat damage is the creature as it currently exists, or as it most recently existed if it is no longer in play.\par \par 310.4c If a creature that was supposed to receive combat damage is no longer in play or is no longer a creature, the damage assigned to it isn\rquote t dealt.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 310.5. At the start of the combat damage step, if at least one attacking or blocking creature has first strike (see rule 502.2) or double strike (see rule 502.28), creatures without first strike or double strike don\rquote t assign combat damage. Instead of proceeding to end of combat, the phase gets a second combat damage step to handle the remaining creatures. In the second combat damage step, surviving attackers and blockers that didn\rquote t assign combat damage in the first step, plus any creatures with double strike, assign their combat damage.\par \par }\pard\plain \s19\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {311. End of Combat Step\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 311.1. All \ldblquote at end of combat\rdblquote  abilities trigger and go on the stack. (See rule 410, \ldblquote Handling Triggered Abilities.\rdblquote ) Then the active player gets priority and players may play spells and abilities.\par \par 311.2. As soon as the end of combat step ends, all creatures are removed from combat. After the end of combat step ends, the combat phase is over and the postcombat main phase begins.\par \par }\pard\plain \s19\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {312. End Phase\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 312.1. The end phase consists of two steps: end of turn and cleanup.\par \par }\pard\plain \s19\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {313. End of Turn Step\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 313.1. As the end of turn step begins, all abilities that trigger \ldblquote at end of turn\rdblquote  go on the stack. (See rule 410, \ldblquote Handling Triggered Abilities.\rdblquote ) Then the active player gets priority and players may play spells and abilities.\par \par 313.2. If \ldblquote at end of turn\rdblquote -triggered abilities are created or if cards with \ldblquote at end of turn\rdblquote -triggered abilities come into play after preexisting ones have already gone on the stack at the beginning of the end of turn step, those abilities won\rquote t go on the stack until the next turn\rquote s end phase. In other words, the step doesn\rquote t \ldblquote back up\rdblquote  so new \ldblquote at end of turn\rdblquote -triggered abilities can go on the stack. This only applies to triggered abilities that say \ldblquote at end of turn.\rdblquote  It doesn\rquote t apply to continuous effects whose durations say \ldblquote until end of turn\rdblquote  or \ldblquote this turn.\rdblquote  (See rule 314, \ldblquote Cleanup Step.\rdblquote )\par \par }\pard\plain \s19\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {314. Cleanup Step\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 314.1. If the active player\rquote s hand contains more cards than his or her maximum hand size (normally seven), he or she discards enough cards to reduce the hand size to that number (this game action doesn\rquote t use the stack).\par \par 314.2 Simultaneously, all damage is removed from permanents and all \ldblquote until end of turn\rdblquote  and \ldblquote this turn\rdblquote  effects end (this game action doesn\rquote t use the stack).\par \par 314.3 If the conditions for any state-based effects exist or if any triggered abilities are waiting to be put onto the stack, the active player gets priority and players may play spells and abilities. Once the stack is empty and both players pass, another cleanup step begins. Otherwise, no player receives priority and the step ends.\par \par }\pard\plain \s17\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\f4\lang1033\cgrid {\page 4. Spells, Abilities, and Effects\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par }\pard\plain \s19\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {400. General\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 400.1. An ability is something an object does or can do. Abilities generate effects. An object\rquote s abilities are defined in the object\rquote s text box (if it has one) or by the effect that created the object. Abilities can also be granted to objects by effects. Reminder text and flavor text are not abilities. Reminder text and flavor text always appear in italics.\par \par 400.2. Spells, activated abilities, and triggered abilities generate effects when they resolve. Static abilities generate continuous effects. Text itself is never an effect.\par \par }\pard\plain \s19\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {401. Spells on the Stack\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 401.1. A card on the stack is a spell. As the first step of being played, the card becomes a spell and goes on the stack from the zone it was played from (usually the player\rquote s hand). (See rule 217.6, \ldblquote Stack.\rdblquote ) A copy of a spell is also a spell, even if it has no card associated with it.\par \par 401.2. A spell stops being a spell when it resolves (see rule 413, \ldblquote Resolving Spells and Abilities\rdblquote ), is countered (see rule 414, \ldblquote Countering Spells and Abilities\rdblquote ), or otherwise leaves the stack.\par }\pard\plain \s23\li1200\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ A played creature card is a creature spell until it resolves, is countered, or leaves the stack.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 401.3. Instant and sorcery spells have abilities, just like any other objects. These abilities are instructions that are followed when the spells resolve, unless the instructions can only be applied at some other time.\par }\pard\plain \s23\li1200\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ Some abilities that are not followed when the spell resolves are activated abilities or triggered abilities, any abilities that define the zone from which it can be played (see rule 401.4), any abilities that apply while the spell is in a zone from which it can be played (see rule 401.5), or any abilities that apply while the spell is on the stack (see rule 401.6).\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 401.4. Any object can have static abilities that allow it to be played from a zone other than a player\rquote s hand. These abilities are active while the object is in that zone.\par \par 401.5. Any object can have static abilities that apply while the object is in a zone from which it can be played. These include restrictions on playing the object and abilities that allow the object to be played at a time that it otherwise could not or in a manner that it otherwise could not.\par \par 401.6. Any spell can have static abilities that apply while the spell is on the stack. These include, but are not limited to, additional costs, alternative costs, and cost reductions. See rule 409, \ldblquote Playing Spells and Activated Abilities.\rdblquote \par \par 401.7. As the final part of an instant or sorcery spell\rquote s resolution, the card is put into its owner\rquote s graveyard. As the final part of an artifact, creature, or enchantment spell\rquote s resolution, the card becomes a permanent and is put into the in-play zone under the control of the spell\rquote s controller. If any spell is countered, the card is put into its owner\rquote s graveyard as part of the resolution of the countering spell or ability. (See rule 413, \ldblquote Resolving Spells and Activated Abilities.\rdblquote )\par \par }\pard\plain \s19\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {402. Abilities\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 402.1. An ability is text on an object that\rquote s not reminder text or flavor text (see rule 400.1). The result of following such an instruction is an effect. (See rule 416, \ldblquote Effects.\rdblquote ) Abilities can affect the objects they\rquote re on; they can also affect other objects and/or players. Abilities can grant abilities to other objects or to the objects they\rquote re on; they do so when the words \ldblquote has,\rdblquote  \ldblquote have,\rdblquote  \ldblquote gains,\rdblquote  or \ldblquote gain\rdblquote  are used.\par \par 402.2. There are three general categories of abilities: activated, triggered, and static. Activated and triggered abilities can also be mana abilities. Abilities can generate one-shot effects or continuous effects. Some effects are replacement effects or prevention effects.\par \par 402.3. Abilities can be beneficial or detrimental. For example, \ldblquote [This creature] can\rquote t block\rdblquote  is an ability.\par \par 402.4. An additional cost or alternative cost to play a card is an ability of the card.\par \par 402.5. An ability isn\rquote t a spell and therefore can\rquote t be countered by anything that counters only spells. Abilities can be countered by effects that specifically counter abilities, as well as by the rules (for example, an ability with one or more targets is countered if all its targets become illegal).\par \par 402.6. Once activated or triggered, an ability exists independently of its source as an ability on the stack. Destruction or removal of the source after that time won\rquote t affect the ability. Note that some abilities cause a source to do something (for example, \ldblquote Prodigal Sorcerer deals 1 damage to target creature or player\rdblquote ) rather than the ability doing anything directly. In these cases, any activated or triggered ability that references information about the source will check that information when the ability resolves, or will use the source\rquote s last known information if it\rquote s no longer in play.\par \par 402.7. An object may have multiple abilities. Aside from certain defined abilities that may be strung together on a single line (see rule 502, \ldblquote Keyword Abilities\rdblquote ), each paragraph break in a card\rquote s text marks a separate ability. An object may also have multiple instances of the same ability. Each instance functions independently. This may or may not produce more effects than a single instance; refer to the specific ability for more information.\par \par 402.8. Abilities function only while the permanent with the ability is in play unless the ability is a characteristic-setting ability that sets type or color, an ability of an instant or sorcery, an additional cost, an alternative cost, or a play restriction. Abilities can also function in other zones if they state otherwise or if the ability can only trigger or be played in a zone other than the in-play zone. An ability whose cost or effect specifies that it moves the object it\rquote s on out of a particular zone functions only in that zone.\par }\pard\plain \s23\li1200\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ An ability with a cost that includes \ldblquote Discard this card from your hand\rdblquote  can be played only if the card is in your hand.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 402.9. Some objects have activated abilities that can be played when the object is not in play. Some objects have triggered abilities that can trigger while the object is in a zone other than the in-play zone.\par \par }\pard\plain \s19\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {403. Activated Abilities\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 403.1. An activated ability is written as \ldblquote [cost]: [effect].\rdblquote  The activation cost is everything before the colon (:). An ability\rquote s activation cost must be paid by the player who is playing it.\par \par 403.2. Only an object\rquote s controller (or its owner, if it doesn\rquote t have a controller) can play its activated ability unless the object specifically says otherwise.\par \par 403.3. If an activated ability has a restriction on its use (for example, \ldblquote Play this ability only once each turn\rdblquote ), the restriction continues to apply to that object even if its controller changes.\par \par 403.4. A creature\rquote s activated ability with the tap symbol (\{oT\}) in its activation cost can\rquote t be played unless the creature has been under its controller\rquote s control since the start of his or her most recent turn. Creatures with haste may ignore this rule (see rule 502.5).\par \par 403.5. Activated abilities that read \ldblquote Play this ability only any time you could play a sorcery\rdblquote  mean the player must follow the timing rules for playing a sorcery, though the ability isn\rquote t actually a sorcery. Activated abilities that read \ldblquote Play this ability only any time you could play an instant\rdblquote  mean the player must follow the timing rules for playing an instant, though the ability isn\rquote t actually an instant.\par \par }\pard\plain \s19\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {404. Triggered Abilities\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 404.1. A triggered ability begins with the word \ldblquote when,\rdblquote  \ldblquote whenever,\rdblquote  or \ldblquote at.\rdblquote  The phrase containing one of these words is the trigger condition, which defines the trigger event.\par \par 404.2. Triggered abilities aren\rquote t played. Instead, a triggered ability automatically \ldblquote triggers\rdblquote  each time its trigger event occurs. Once an ability has triggered, it goes on the stack the next time a player would receive priority. See rule 408.1, \ldblquote Timing, Priority, and the Stack,\rdblquote  and rule 410, \ldblquote Handling Triggered Abilities.\rdblquote \par \par 404.3. A triggered ability may read \ldblquote When/Whenever/At . . . , if [condition], [effect].\rdblquote  The ability checks for the stated condition to be true when the trigger event occurs. If it is, the ability triggers. On resolution, the ability rechecks the condition. If the condition isn\rquote t true at either of those times, the ability does nothing. This rule is referred to as the \ldblquote intervening \lquote if\rquote  clause\rdblquote  rule. Note that the word \ldblquote if\rdblquote  has only its normal English meaning anywhere else in the text of a card; this rule only applies to an \ldblquote if\rdblquote  that immediately follows a trigger condition.\par \par 404.4. An effect may create a delayed triggered ability that can do something at a later time. A delayed triggered ability will contain \ldblquote when,\rdblquote  \ldblquote whenever,\rdblquote  or \ldblquote at,\rdblquote  although that word won\rquote t usually begin the ability.\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {404.4a Delayed triggered abilities come from spells or other abilities that create them on resolution. That means a delayed triggered ability won\rquote t trigger until it has actually been created, even if its trigger event occurred just beforehand. Other events that happen earlier may make the trigger event impossible.\par }\pard\plain \s24\li1500\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ Part of an effect reads \ldblquote When this creature leaves play,\rdblquote  but the creature in question leaves play before the spell or ability creating the effect resolves. In this case, the delayed ability never triggers. As another example, if an effect reads \ldblquote When this creature becomes untapped\rdblquote  and the named creature becomes untapped before the effect resolves, the ability waits for the next time that creature untaps.\par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 404.4b A delayed triggered ability will trigger only once\emdash the next time its trigger event occurs\emdash unless it has a stated duration, such as \ldblquote this turn.\rdblquote \par \par 404.4c A delayed triggered ability that refers to a particular object still affects it even if the object changes characteristics.\par }\pard\plain \s24\li1500\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ An ability reading, \ldblquote At end of turn, destroy that creature\rdblquote  will destroy the permanent even if it\rquote s no longer a creature during the end of turn step.\par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 404.4d A delayed triggered ability that refers to a particular permanent will fail if the permanent leaves play (even if it returns again before the specified time). Similarly, abilities that create a one-shot effect that applies to an object in a particular zone will fail if the object leaves that zone.\par }\pard\plain \s24\li1500\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ An ability reading, \ldblquote At end of turn, remove this creature from the game\rdblquote  won\rquote t do anything if the creature leaves play before the end of turn step.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 404.5. Some objects have a static ability that\rquote s linked to a triggered ability. These objects combine both abilities into one paragraph, with the static ability first, followed by the triggered ability. A very few objects have triggered abilities which are written with the trigger condition in the middle of the ability, rather than at the beginning.\par }\pard\plain \s23\li1200\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ An ability that reads \ldblquote Reveal the first card you draw each turn. Whenever you reveal a basic land card this way, draw a card\rdblquote  is a static ability linked to a triggered ability.\par }\pard \s23\li1200\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 {\b Example:}{ An ability that reads \ldblquote The controller of enchanted creature sacrifices it at the end of his or her turn\rdblquote  is a triggered ability.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par }\pard\plain \s19\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {405. Static Abilities\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 405.1. A static ability does something all the time rather than being activated or triggered. The ability isn\rquote t played\emdash it just \ldblquote exists.\rdblquote  Such abilities apply only while the ability is on a permanent in play, unless the ability is covered by rule 402.8 or 402.9.\par \par 405.2. Some objects have static abilities which state that the object \ldblquote has\rdblquote  one or more abilities or characteristic values; \ldblquote is\rdblquote  a particular type, supertype, subtype, or color; or that one or more of its characteristics \ldblquote is\rdblquote  or \ldblquote are\rdblquote  a particular value. These abilities are characteristic-setting abilities. Abilities of an object that affect the characteristics of another object are not characteristic-setting abilities. See rule 201, \ldblquote Characteristics,\rdblquote  and rule 418.5a.\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {405.2a A characteristic-setting ability that states that an object is a particular type, supertype, subtype, or color applies no matter which zone the object it\rquote s on is in. This rule doesn\rquote t apply to other characteristic-setting abilities.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par }\pard\plain \s19\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {406. Mana Abilities\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 406.1. A mana ability is either }{\i (a)}{ an activated ability that could put mana into a player\rquote s mana pool when it resolves or }{\i (b)}{ a triggered ability that triggers from a mana ability and could produce additional mana. A mana ability can generate other effects at the same time it produces mana.\par \par 406.2. Spells that put mana into a player\rquote s mana pool aren\rquote t mana abilities. They\rquote re played and resolved exactly like any other spells. Triggered abilities that put mana into a player\rquote s mana pool aren\rquote t mana abilities if they trigger from events other than activating mana abilities. They go on the stack and resolve like any other triggered abilities.\par \par 406.3. A mana ability remains a mana ability even if the game state doesn\rquote t allow it to produce mana.\par }\pard\plain \s23\li1200\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ A permanent has an ability that reads \ldblquote \{oT\}: Add \{oG\} to your mana pool for each creature you control.\rdblquote  This is still a mana ability even if you control no creatures or if the permanent is already tapped.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 406.4. A mana ability can be activated or triggered. Mana abilities are played and resolved like other abilities, but they don\rquote t go on the stack, so they can\rquote t be countered or responded to. See rule 411, \ldblquote Playing Mana Abilities,\rdblquote  and rule 408.2, \ldblquote Actions That Don\rquote t Use the Stack.\rdblquote \par \par 406.5. Abilities (other than mana abilities) that trigger on playing mana abilities do use the stack.\par \par 406.6. If a mana ability would produce one or more mana of an undefined type, it produces no mana instead.\par }\pard\plain \s23\li1200\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ If you control no lands, an ability that reads \ldblquote \{oT\}: Add to your mana pool one mana of any type that a land you control could produce\rdblquote  will not produce any mana.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par }\pard\plain \s19\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {407. Adding and Removing Abilities\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 407.1. Effects can add or remove abilities of objects. An effect that adds an ability will state that the object \ldblquote gains\rdblquote  or \ldblquote has\rdblquote  that ability. An effect that removes an ability will state that the object \ldblquote loses\rdblquote  that ability. If two or more effects add and remove the same ability, in general the most recent one prevails. (See rule 418.5, \ldblquote Interaction of Continuous Effects.\rdblquote )\par \par 407.2. An effect that sets an object\rquote s characteristic, or simply states a quality of that object, is different from an ability granted by an effect. When an object \ldblquote gains\rdblquote  or \ldblquote has\rdblquote  an ability, that ability can be removed by another effect. If an effect defines a characteristic of the object (\ldblquote [permanent] is [characteristic value]\rdblquote ), it\rquote s not granting an ability. (See rule 405.2.)\par }\pard\plain \s23\li1200\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ An effect reads, \ldblquote Enchanted creature has \lquote This creature is an artifact creature.\rquote \rdblquote  This effect grants an ability to the creature that can be removed by other effects. Another effect reads, \ldblquote Enchanted creature is an artifact creature.\rdblquote  This effect simply defines a characteristic of the creature. It doesn\rquote t grant an ability, so effects that would cause the creature to lose its abilities wouldn\rquote t cause the enchanted creature to stop being an artifact.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 407.3. Effects that remove an ability remove all instances of it.\par }\pard\plain \s23\li1200\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ If a creature with flying is enchanted with Flight, it has two instances of the flying ability. A single effect that reads \ldblquote Target creature loses flying\rdblquote  will remove both.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par }\pard\plain \s19\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {408. Timing of Spells and Abilities\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 408.1. Timing, Priority, and the Stack\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {408.1a Spells and activated abilities can be played only at certain times and follow a set of rules for doing so.\par \par 408.1b Spells and activated abilities are played by players (if they choose) using a system of priority, while other types of abilities and effects are automatically generated by the game rules. Each time a player would get priority, all applicable state-based effects resolve first as a single event (see rule 420, \ldblquote State-Based Effects\rdblquote ). Then, if any new state-based effects have been generated, they resolve as a single event. This process repeats until no more applicable state-based effects are generated. Then triggered abilities are added to the stack (see rule 410, \ldblquote Handling Triggered Abilities\rdblquote ). These steps repeat in order until no further state-based effects or triggered abilities are generated. Then the player who would have received priority does so and may play a spell or ability, take a special action (such as playing a land), or pass, as governed by the rules for that phase or step.\par \par 408.1c The active player gets priority at the beginning of most phases and steps, after any game actions are dealt with and abilities that trigger at the beginning of that phase or step go on the stack. No player gets priority during the untap step and players usually don\rquote t get priority during the cleanup step (see rule 314.3). The player with priority may either play a spell or ability, take a special action, or pass. If he or she plays a spell or ability, or takes a special action, the player again receives priority; otherwise, his or her opponent receives priority. If both players pass in succession (that is, if both players pass without taking any actions in between passing), the top object on the stack resolves, then the active player receives priority. If the stack is empty when both players pass in succession, the phase or step ends and the next one begins.\par \par 408.1d A player may play a spell or activated ability only when he or she has priority. Spells other than instants can be played only during a player\rquote s main phase, when that player has priority, and only when the stack is empty.\par \par 408.1e When a spell is played, it goes on top of the stack. When an activated ability is played, it goes on top of the stack.\par \par 408.1f Triggered abilities can trigger at any time, including during the playing or resolution of a spell or another ability. However, nothing actually happens at the time the abilities trigger. Each time a player would receive priority, each ability that has triggered is put on the stack (if it hasn\rquote t already been put on the stack). Then the player gets priority and may play spells or abilities. (See rule 410, \ldblquote Handling Triggered Abilities.\rdblquote )\par \par 408.1g Combat damage goes on the stack once it\rquote s been assigned. For more information, see rule 310, \ldblquote Combat Damage Step.\rdblquote \par \par 408.1h Static abilities aren\rquote t played\emdash they continuously affect the game. Priority doesn\rquote t apply to them. (See rule 405, \ldblquote Static Abilities,\rdblquote  rule 418, \ldblquote Continuous Effects,\rdblquote  and rule 419, \ldblquote Replacement and Prevention Effects.\rdblquote )\par \par 408.1i Special actions don\rquote t use the stack. The special actions are playing a land (see rule 408.2d), turning a face-down creature face up (see rule 408.2h), ending continuous effects or preventing delayed triggered abilities (see rule 408.2i), and suspending or ignoring continuous effects (see rule 408.2j).\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 408.2. Actions That Don\rquote t Use the Stack\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {408.2a Effects don\rquote t go on the stack; they\rquote re the result of spells and abilities resolving. Effects may create delayed triggered abilities, however, and these may go on the stack when they trigger (see rule 404.4).\par \par 408.2b Static abilities continuously generate effects and don\rquote t go on the stack.\par \par 408.2c State-based effects (see rule 420) resolve whenever a player would receive priority as long as the required game condition is true.\par \par 408.2d Playing a land is a special action consisting of putting that land into play. (See rule 212.6, \ldblquote Lands.\rdblquote ) A player can play a land only during a main phase of his or her turn, when he or she has priority and the stack is empty. The player who played the land gets priority after this special action.\par \par 408.2e Mana abilities resolve immediately. If a mana ability produces both mana and another effect, both the mana and the other effect happen immediately. If a player had priority before a mana ability was played, that player gets priority after it resolves. (See rule 406, \ldblquote Mana Abilities.\rdblquote )\par \par 408.2f Characteristic-setting abilities, such as \ldblquote [This object] is red,\rdblquote  are simply read and followed as applicable. (See also rule 405.2.)\par \par 408.2g Game actions\emdash phasing in and out during the untap step, untapping during the untap step, drawing a card during the draw step, declaring attacking or blocking creatures, cleanup, and mana burn\emdash don\rquote t use the stack.\par \par 408.2h The controller of a face-down permanent may turn it face up. This is a special action. (See rule 504, \ldblquote Face-Down Spells and Permanents.\rdblquote ) A player can turn a face-down permanent face up only when he or she has priority. That player gets priority after this special action.\par \par 408.2i Some effects allow a player to take an action at a later time, usually to end a continuous effect or to stop a delayed triggered ability. This is a special action. A player can end a continuous effect or stop a delayed triggered ability only if the effect or ability allows it and only when he or she has priority. The player who took the action gets priority after this special action.\par \par 408.2j Some effects from static abilities allow a player to take an action to ignore or suspend the effect from that ability for a duration. This is a special action. A player can take an action to ignore or suspend an effect only when he or she has priority. The player who took the action gets priority after this special action.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par }\pard\plain \s19\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {409. Playing Spells and Activated Abilities\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 409.1. Playing a spell or activated ability follows the steps listed below, in order. If, at any point during the playing of a spell or ability, a player is unable to comply with any of the steps listed below, the spell was played illegally; the game returns to the moment before that spell or ability was played (see rule 422, \ldblquote Handling Illegal Actions\rdblquote ). Announcements and payments can\rquote t be altered after they\rquote ve been made.\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {409.1a The player announces that he or she is playing the spell or activated ability. It moves from the zone it\rquote s in to the stack and remains there until it\rquote s countered or resolves. In the case of spells, the physical card goes onto the stack. In the case of activated abilities, the ability goes onto the stack without any card associated with it. Each spell has all the characteristics of the card associated with it. Each activated ability that\rquote s on the stack has the text of the ability that created it, and no other characteristics. The controller of a spell is the player who played the spell. The controller of an activated ability is the player who played the ability.\par \par 409.1b If the spell or ability is modal (uses the phrase \ldblquote Choose one \emdash \rdblquote  or \ldblquote [specified player] chooses one \emdash \rdblquote ), the player announces the mode choice. If the spell or ability has a variable mana cost (indicated by \{oX\}) or some other variable cost, the player announces the value of that variable at this time. If the spell or ability has alternative, additional, or other special costs (such as buyback or kicker costs), the player announces his or her intentions to pay any or all of those costs (see rule 409.1f). You can\rquote t apply two alternative methods of playing or two alternative costs to a single spell or ability. Previously made choices (such as choosing to play a spell with flashback from his or her graveyard or choosing to play a creature with morph face down) may restrict the player\rquote s options when making these choices.\par \par 409.1c If the spell or ability requires any targets, the player first announces how many targets he or she will choose (if the spell or ability has a variable number of targets), then announces the targets themselves. A spell or ability can\rquote t be played unless the required number of legal targets are chosen. The same target can\rquote t be chosen multiple times.\par \par 409.1d If the spell or ability targets one or more targets only if an alternative, additional, or special cost (such as a buyback or kicker cost) is paid for it, or if a particular mode is chosen for it, its controller chooses those targets only if he or she announced the intention to pay that cost or chose that mode. Otherwise, the spell or ability is played as though it did not have those targets.\par \par 409.1e If the spell or ability affects several targets in different ways, the player announces how it will affect each target. If the spell or ability requires the player to divide or distribute an effect (such as damage or counters) among one or more targets, or any number of untargeted objects or players, the player announces the division. Each of these targets, objects, or players must receive at least one of whatever is being divided.\par \par 409.1f The player determines the total cost of the spell or ability. Usually this is just the mana cost (for spells) or activation cost (for abilities). Some cards list additional or alternative costs in their text, and some effects may increase or reduce the cost to pay. Costs may include paying mana, tapping permanents, sacrificing permanents, discarding cards, and so on. The total cost is the mana cost, activation cost, or alternative cost, plus all cost increases and minus all cost reductions. Once the total cost is determined, it becomes \ldblquote locked in.\rdblquote  If effects would change the total cost after this time, they have no effect.\par \par 409.1g The player then has a chance to play mana abilities (see rule 411, \ldblquote Playing Mana Abilities\rdblquote ). Mana abilities must be played before costs are paid.\par \par 409.1h The player pays the total cost in any order. Partial payments are not allowed.\par }\pard\plain \s24\li1500\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ You play Death Bomb, which costs \{o3\}\{oB\} and has an additional cost of sacrificing a creature. You sacrifice Thunderscape Familiar, whose effect makes your black spells cost \{o1\} less to play. Because a spell\rquote s total cost is \ldblquote locked in\rdblquote  before payments are actually made, you pay \{o2\}\{oB\}, not \{o3\}\{oB\}, even though you\rquote re sacrificing the Familiar.\par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 409.1i Once the steps described in 409.1a\endash 409.1h are completed, the spell or ability becomes played. Any abilities that trigger on a spell or ability being played or put onto the stack trigger at this time. The spell or ability\rquote s controller gets priority.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 409.2. Some spells and abilities specify that their controller\rquote s opponent does something the controller would normally do while it\rquote s being played, such as choose a mode, choose targets, or choose how the spell or ability will affect its targets. In these cases, the opponent does so when the spell or ability\rquote s controller normally would do so. If the spell or ability instructs both players to do something at the same time as it\rquote s being played, the spell\rquote s controller goes first, then his or her opponent. This is an exception to rule 103.4.\par \par 409.3. Playing a spell or ability that alters costs won\rquote t do anything to spells and abilities that are already on the stack.\par \par 409.4 A player can\rquote t begin to play a spell or activated ability that\rquote s prohibited from being played by an effect.\par \par }\pard\plain \s19\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {410. Handling Triggered Abilities\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 410.1. Because they aren\rquote t played, triggered abilities can trigger even when it isn\rquote t legal to play spells and abilities, and effects that prevent abilities from being played don\rquote t affect them.\par \par 410.2. Whenever a game event or game state matches a triggered ability\rquote s trigger event, that ability triggers. When a phase or step begins, all abilities that trigger \ldblquote at the beginning of\rdblquote  that phase or step trigger. The ability doesn\rquote t do anything when it triggers but automatically puts the ability on the stack as soon as a player would receive priority. The ability is controlled by the player who controlled its source at the time it triggered. It has the text of the ability that created it, and no other characteristics.\par \par 410.3. If multiple abilities have triggered since the last time a player received priority, the abilities controlled by the active player go on the stack first, in any order he or she chooses, then those controlled by the opponent go on the stack in any order that opponent chooses. Then players once again check for and resolve state-based effects until none are generated, then abilities that triggered during this process go on the stack. This process repeats until no new state-based effects are generated and no abilities trigger. Then the appropriate player gets priority.\par \par 410.4. When a triggered ability goes on the stack, the controller of the ability makes any choices that would be required while playing an activated ability, following the same procedure (see rule 409, \ldblquote Playing Spells and Activated Abilities\rdblquote ). If no legal choice can be made (or if a rule or a continuous effect otherwise makes the ability illegal), the ability is simply removed from the stack.\par \par 410.5. Some triggered abilities\rquote  effects are optional (they contain \ldblquote may,\rdblquote  as in \ldblquote At the beginning of your upkeep, you may draw a card\rdblquote ). These abilities go on the stack when they trigger, regardless of whether their controller intends to exercise the ability\rquote s option or not. The choice is made when the ability resolves. Likewise, triggered abilities that have an effect \ldblquote unless\rdblquote  something is true or a player chooses to do something will go on the stack normally; the \ldblquote unless\rdblquote  part of the ability is dealt with when the ability resolves.\par \par 410.6. An ability triggers only once each time its trigger event occurs. However, it can trigger repeatedly if one event contains multiple occurrences. See also rule 410.9.\par }\pard\plain \s23\li1200\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ A permanent has an ability whose trigger condition reads, \ldblquote Whenever a land is put into a graveyard from play, . . . .\rdblquote  If someone plays a spell that destroys all lands, the ability will trigger once for each land put into the graveyard during the spell\rquote s resolution.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 410.7. An ability triggers only if its trigger event actually occurs. An event that\rquote s prevented or replaced won\rquote t trigger anything.\par }\pard\plain \s23\li1200\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ An ability that triggers on damage being dealt won\rquote t trigger if all the damage is prevented.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 410.8. Triggered abilities with a condition directly following the trigger event (for example, \ldblquote When/Whenever/At [trigger], if [condition], [effect]\rdblquote ), check for the condition to be true as part of the trigger event; if it isn\rquote t, the ability doesn\rquote t trigger. The ability checks the condition again on resolution. If it\rquote s not satisfied, the ability does nothing. Note that this mirrors the check for legal targets. Note that this rule doesn\rquote t apply to any triggered ability with an \ldblquote if\rdblquote  condition elsewhere within its text. This rule is referred to as the \ldblquote intervening \lquote if\rquote  clause\rdblquote  rule.\par \par 410.9. Some abilities trigger when creatures block or are blocked in combat. (See rules 306\endash 311 and section 500, \ldblquote Legal Attacks and Blocks.\rdblquote ) They may trigger once or repeatedly, depending on the wording of the ability.\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {410.9a An ability that reads \ldblquote Whenever [this creature] blocks\rdblquote  or \ldblquote Whenever [this creature] becomes blocked\rdblquote  triggers only once each combat for that creature, even if it blocks or is blocked by multiple creatures. An effect that causes the creature to become blocked (if the creature wasn\rquote t already blocked) will also trigger such abilities.\par \par 410.9b An ability that reads \ldblquote Whenever [this creature] blocks a creature\rdblquote  triggers once for each attacking creature the named creature blocks.\par \par 410.9c An ability that reads \ldblquote Whenever a creature blocks [this creature]\rdblquote  triggers once for each creature that blocks the named creature. It doesn\rquote t trigger if the attacking creature becomes blocked by an effect rather than a blocking creature.\par \par 410.9d If an ability triggers when a creature blocks or is blocked by a particular number of creatures, the ability triggers only if the creature blocks or is blocked by that many creatures when the attack or block declaration is made. Effects that add or remove blockers can cause such abilities to trigger. This also applies to abilities that trigger on a creature blocking or being blocked by at least a certain number of creatures.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 410.10. Trigger events that involve objects changing zones are called \ldblquote zone-change triggers.\rdblquote  Many abilities with zone-change triggers attempt to do something to that object after it changes zones. During resolution, these abilities look for the object in the zone that it moved to. If the object is unable to be found in the zone it went to, the part of the ability attempting to do something to the object will fail to do anything. The ability could be unable to find the object because the object never entered the specified zone, because it left the zone before the ability resolved, or because it is in a zone that is hidden from a player, such as a library or an opponent\rquote s hand. (This rule applies even if the object leaves the zone and returns again before the ability resolves.) The most common types of zone-change triggers are comes-into-play triggers and leaves-play triggers.\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {410.10a Comes-into-play abilities trigger when a permanent enters the in-play zone. These are written, \ldblquote When [this card] comes into play, . . . \ldblquote  or \ldblquote Whenever a [type] comes into play, . . .\rdblquote  Each time an event puts one or more permanents into play, all permanents in play (including the newcomers) are checked for any comes-into-play triggers that match the event.\par \par 410.10b Continuous effects that modify characteristics of a permanent do so the moment the permanent is in play (and not before then). The permanent is never in play with its unmodified characteristics. Continuous effects don\rquote t apply before the permanent is in play, however (see rule 410.10e).\par }\pard\plain \s24\li1500\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ If an effect reads \ldblquote All lands are creatures\rdblquote  and a land card is played, the effect makes the land card into a creature the moment it enters play, so it would trigger abilities that trigger when a creature comes into play. Conversely, if an effect reads \ldblquote All creatures lose all abilities\rdblquote  and a creature card with a comes-into-play triggered ability enters play, that effect will cause it to lose its abilities the moment it enters play, so the comes-into-play ability won\rquote t trigger.\par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 410.10c Leaves-play abilities trigger when a permanent leaves the in-play zone. These are written as, but aren\rquote t limited to, \ldblquote When [this object] leaves play, . . .\rdblquote  or \ldblquote Whenever [something] is put into a graveyard from play, . . . .\rdblquote  An ability that attempts to do something to the card that left play checks for it only in the first zone that it went to.\par \par 410.10d Abilities that trigger on one or more permanents leaving play, or on a player losing control of a permanent, must be treated specially because the permanent with the ability may no longer be in play after the event. The game has to \ldblquote look back in time\rdblquote  to determine what triggered. Each time an event removes from play or changes who controls one or more permanents, all the permanents in play just before the event (with continuous effects that existed at that time) are checked for trigger events that match what just left play or changed control.\par }\pard\plain \s24\li1500\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ Two creatures are in play along with an artifact that has the ability \ldblquote Whenever a creature is put into a graveyard from play, you gain 1 life.\rdblquote  Someone plays a spell that destroys all artifacts, creatures, and enchantments. The artifact\rquote s ability triggers twice, even though the artifact goes to its owner\rquote s graveyard at the same time as the creatures.\par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 410.10e Some permanents have text that reads \ldblquote [This permanent] comes into play with . . . ,\rdblquote  \ldblquote As [this permanent] comes into play . . . ,\rdblquote  \ldblquote [This permanent] comes into play as . . . ,\rdblquote  or \ldblquote [This permanent] comes into play tapped.\rdblquote  Such text is a static ability\emdash not a triggered ability\emdash whose effect occurs as part of the event that puts the permanent into play.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 410.11. Some triggered abilities trigger on a game state, such as a player controlling no permanents of a particular type, rather than triggering when an event occurs. These abilities trigger as soon as the game state matches the condition. They\rquote ll go onto the stack at the next available opportunity. These are called state triggers. (Note that state triggers aren\rquote t the same as state-based effects.) A state-triggered ability doesn\rquote t trigger again until the ability has resolved, has been countered, or has otherwise left the stack. Then, if the object with the ability is still in the same zone and the game state still matches its trigger condition, the ability will trigger again.\par }\pard\plain \s23\li1200\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ A permanent\rquote s ability reads, \ldblquote Whenever you have no cards in hand, draw a card.\rdblquote  If its controller plays the last card from his or her hand, the ability will trigger once and won\rquote t trigger again until it has resolved. If its controller plays a spell that reads \ldblquote Discard your hand, then draw the same number of cards,\rdblquote  the ability will trigger during the spell\rquote s resolution because the player\rquote s hand was momentarily empty.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par }\pard\plain \s19\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {411. Playing Mana Abilities\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 411.1. To play a mana ability, the player announces that he or she is playing it and pays the activation cost, following the steps in rules 409.1b\endash i. It resolves immediately after it is played and doesn\rquote t go on the stack. (See rule 408.2e.)\par \par 411.2. A player may play an activated mana ability whenever he or she has priority. A player may also play one whenever a rule or effect asks for a mana payment, even in the middle of playing or resolving a spell or ability.\par \par 411.3. Triggered mana abilities trigger when an activated mana ability is played. These abilities resolve immediately after the mana ability that triggered them, without waiting for priority. If an activated or triggered ability produces both mana and another effect, both the mana and the other effect resolve immediately.\par }\pard\plain \s23\li1200\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ An enchantment reads, \ldblquote Whenever a player taps a land for mana, that land produces one additional mana of the same color.\rdblquote  If a player taps lands for mana while playing a spell, the additional mana is added to the player\rquote s mana pool immediately and can be used to pay for the spell.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {411.3a If a triggered mana ability adds mana \ldblquote of the same type\rdblquote  or \ldblquote of the same color\rdblquote  to a player\rquote s mana pool and the mana ability that triggered it produced more than one type or color of mana, the player to whose mana pool the mana is being added chooses which type or color of mana the triggered ability adds.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par }\pard\plain \s19\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {412. Handling Static Abilities\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 412.1. A static ability may generate a continuous effect or a prevention or replacement effect. These effects last as long as the object with the static ability remains in the appropriate zone.\par \par 412.2. Many local enchantments and Equipment have static abilities that modify the permanent they\rquote re attached to, but those abilities don\rquote t target that permanent. If a local enchantment or Equipment is moved to a different permanent, the ability stops applying to the original permanent and starts modifying the new one.\par \par 412.3. Some static abilities apply while a spell is on the stack. These are often abilities that refer to countering the spell. Also, abilities that say \ldblquote As an additional cost to play . . . ,\rdblquote  \ldblquote You may pay [cost] rather than pay [this object]\rquote s mana cost,\rdblquote  and \ldblquote You may play [this object] without paying its mana cost\rdblquote  work while a spell is on the stack.\par \par 412.4. Some static abilities apply while a card is in any zone that you could play it from (usually your hand). These are limited to those that read, \ldblquote You may play [this card] . . .\rdblquote  and \ldblquote You can\rquote t play [this card] . . . .\rdblquote \par \par 412.5. Unlike spells and other kinds of abilities, static abilities can\rquote t use an object\rquote s last known information for purposes of determining how their effects are applied.\par \par }\pard\plain \s19\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {413. Resolving Spells and Abilities\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 413.1. Each time both players pass in succession, the object (a spell, an ability, or combat damage) on top of the stack resolves. (See rule 416, \ldblquote Effects.\rdblquote )\par \par 413.2. Resolution of a spell or ability may involve several steps. These steps are followed in the order listed below.\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {413.2a If the spell or ability specifies targets, it checks whether the targets are still legal. A target that\rquote s removed from play, or from the zone designated by the spell or ability, is illegal. A target may also become illegal if its characteristics changed since the spell or ability was played or if an effect changed the text of the spell. If all targets are now illegal, the spell or ability is countered. If the spell or ability is not countered, it will resolve normally, affecting only the targets that are still legal. If a target is illegal, the spell or ability can\rquote t perform any actions on it or make the target perform any actions. If the spell or ability needs to know information about one or more targets that are now illegal, it will use the illegal targets\rquote  current or last known information.\par \par 413.2b The controller of the spell or ability follows its instructions in the order written. However, replacement effects may modify these actions. In some cases, later text on the card may modify the meaning of earlier text (for example, \ldblquote Destroy target creature. It can\rquote t be regenerated\rdblquote  or \ldblquote Counter target spell. If you do, put it on top of its owner\rquote s library instead of into its owner\rquote s graveyard.\rdblquote ) Don\rquote t just apply effects step by step without thinking in these cases\emdash read the whole text and apply the rules of English to the text.\par \par 413.2c If an effect offers any choices other than choices already made as part of playing the spell or ability, the player announces these while applying the effect. The player can\rquote t choose an option that\rquote s illegal or impossible. (For example, a player can\rquote t avoid the consequences of not taking an optional action if he or she can\rquote t meet all the immediate requirements of that action.)\par }\pard\plain \s24\li1500\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ A spell\rquote s instruction reads, \ldblquote You may sacrifice a creature. If you don\rquote t, you lose 4 life.\rdblquote  A player who controls no creatures can\rquote t choose the sacrifice option.\par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 413.2d If an effect requires both players to make choices or take actions at the same time, the active player makes and announces his or her choices first, and then the nonactive player does (knowing the active player\rquote s choices). Then the actions take place simultaneously. See rule 103.4. If a player must make more than one choice at a time, he or she makes the choices in the order written, or in the order he or she chooses if the choices aren\rquote t ordered. Then the actions are processed simultaneously.\par           Some spells and abilities have multiple steps or actions, denoted by separate sentences or clauses. In these cases, the active player makes any choices required for the first action, then the nonactive player makes any choices required for that action, then the first action is processed simultaneously. Then the active player makes any choices required for the second action, then the nonactive player makes any choices required for that action, then that action is processed simultaneously, and so on.\par }\pard\plain \s24\li1500\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ Stronghold Gambit reads, in part, \ldblquote Each player chooses a card in his or her hand. Then each player reveals his or her chosen card.\rdblquote  First the active player chooses a card, then the nonactive player does so. Each player reveals the cards simultaneously.\par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 413.2e If an effect gives a player the option to pay mana, he or she may play mana abilities as part of the action. No other spells or abilities can be played during resolution.\par \par 413.2f If an effect requires information from the game (such as the number of creatures in play), the answer is determined only once, when the effect is applied. The effect uses the current information of a specific permanent if that permanent is still in play, or of a specific card in the stated zone; otherwise, the effect uses the last known information the object had before leaving that zone. The exception is that static abilities can\rquote t use last known information; see rule 412.5. If the ability text states that an object does something, it\rquote s the object as it exists (or most recently existed) that does it, not the ability.\par \par 413.2g An effect that refers to characteristics of an object checks only for the value of the specified characteristics, regardless of any related ones the object may also have.\par }\pard\plain \s24\li1500\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ An effect that reads \ldblquote Destroy all black creatures\rdblquote  destroys a white-and-black creature, but one that reads \ldblquote Destroy all nonblack creatures\rdblquote  doesn\rquote t.\par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 413.2h A spell is put into play from the stack under the control of the spell\rquote s controller (for permanents) or is put into its owner\rquote s graveyard from the stack (for instants and sorceries) as the final step of the spell\rquote s resolution.\par \par 413.2i If an effect could result in a tie, the text of the spell or ability that created the effect will specify what to do in the event of a tie. The }{\b Magic}{ game has no default for ties.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par }\pard\plain \s19\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {414. Countering Spells and Abilities\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 414.1. To counter a spell is to move the spell from the stack to its owner\rquote s graveyard. Countering an ability removes it from the stack. Spells and abilities that are countered don\rquote t resolve and none of their effects occur.\par \par 414.2. The player who played the countered spell or ability doesn\rquote t get a \ldblquote refund\rdblquote  of any costs that were paid.\par \par }\pard\plain \s19\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {415. Targeted Spells and Abilities\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 415.1. An instant or sorcery spell is targeted if the text that will be followed when it resolves uses the phrase \ldblquote target [something],\rdblquote  where the \ldblquote something\rdblquote  is a phrase that describes an object or player. (If an activated or triggered ability of an instant or sorcery uses the word target, that ability is targeted, but the spell is not.)\par }\pard\plain \s23\li1200\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ A sorcery card has the ability \ldblquote When you cycle this card, target creature gets -1/-1 until end of turn.\rdblquote  This triggered ability is targeted, but that doesn\rquote t make the card it\rquote s on targeted.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 415.2. An activated or triggered ability is targeted if it uses the phrase \ldblquote target [something],\rdblquote  where the \ldblquote something\rdblquote  is a phrase that describes an object or player.\par \par 415.3. Local-enchantment spells are always targeted, even though they don\rquote t use the phrase \ldblquote target [something].\rdblquote  They target the permanent or player they will enchant. A local-enchantment permanent doesn\rquote t target anything; only the spell is targeted. An activated or triggered ability of the local-enchantment permanent can be targeted.\par           Neither Equipment spells nor Equipment permanents target anything. The equip ability is targeted; see rule 502.33, \ldblquote Equip.\rdblquote  An activated or triggered ability of an Equipment permanent can be targeted.\par \par 415.4. Spells and abilities that can have zero or more targets are targeted only if one or more targets have been chosen for them.\par \par 415.5. Only permanents are legal targets for spells and abilities, unless a spell or ability }{\i (a)}{ specifies that it can target an object in another zone or a player or }{\i (b)}{ targets an object that can\rquote t exist in the in-play zone, such as a spell or ability.\par \par 415.6. A spell or ability on the stack is an illegal target for itself.\par \par 415.7. Changing Targets\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {415.7a The target of a spell or ability can change only to another legal target. If the target can\rquote t be changed to another legal target, the original target is unchanged.\par \par 415.7b Modal spells and abilities may have different targeting requirements for each mode. Changing a spell or ability\rquote s target can\rquote t change its mode.\par \par 415.7c The word \ldblquote you\rdblquote  in an object\rquote s text isn\rquote t a target.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par }\pard\plain \s19\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {416. Effects\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 416.1. When a spell or ability resolves, it may create one or more one-shot or continuous effects. Static abilities may create one or more continuous effects. Some effects are replacement effects or prevention effects. State-based effects are not created by spells or abilities; they are generated by specific rules of the game.\par \par 416.2. Effects apply only to permanents unless the instruction\rquote s text states otherwise or they clearly can apply only to objects in one or more other zones.\par }\pard\plain \s23\li1200\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ An effect that changes all lands into creatures won\rquote t alter land cards in players\rquote  graveyards. But an effect that says spells cost more to play will apply only to spells on the stack, since a spell is always on the stack while you are playing it.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 416.3. If an effect attempts to do something impossible, it does only as much as possible.\par }\pard\plain \s23\li1200\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ If a player is holding only one card, an effect that reads \ldblquote Discard two cards\rdblquote  causes him or her to discard only that card. If an effect moves cards out of the library (as opposed to drawing), it moves as many as possible.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par }\pard\plain \s19\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {417. One-Shot Effects\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 417.1. A one-shot effect does something just once and doesn\rquote t have a duration. Examples include damage dealing, destruction of permanents, and moving objects between zones.\par \par 417.2. Some one-shot effects instruct a player to do something later in the game (usually at a specific time) rather than when they resolve. This kind of effect actually creates a new ability that waits to be triggered. (See rule 404.4.)\par \par }\pard\plain \s19\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {418. Continuous Effects\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 418.1. A continuous effect modifies characteristics of objects or modifies the rules of the game for a fixed or indefinite period. A continuous effect may be generated by the resolution of a spell or ability or by a static ability of an object.\par \par 418.2. Continuous effects that modify characteristics of permanents do so simultaneously with the permanent coming into play. They don\rquote t wait until the permanent is in play and then change it. Because such effects apply as the permanent comes into play, apply them before determining whether the permanent will cause an ability to trigger when it comes into play.\par \par 418.3. Continuous Effects from Spells or Abilities\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {418.3a A continuous effect generated by the resolution of a spell or ability lasts as long as stated by the spell or ability creating it (such as \ldblquote until end of turn\rdblquote ). If no duration is stated, it lasts until the end of the game.\par \par 418.3b Continuous effects from spells, activated abilities, and triggered abilities that modify the characteristics or change the controller of one or more objects don\rquote t affect objects that weren\rquote t affected when the continuous effect began. Note that these work differently than continuous effects from static abilities. Continuous effects that don\rquote t modify characteristics or change the controller of objects modify the rules of the game, so they can affect objects that weren\rquote t affected when the continuous effect began.\par }\pard\plain \s24\li1500\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ An effect that reads \ldblquote All white creatures get +1/+1 until end of turn\rdblquote  gives the bonus to all permanents that are white creatures when the spell or ability resolves\emdash even if they change color later\emdash and doesn\rquote t affect those that come into play or turn white afterward.\par }{\b Example:}{ An effect that reads \ldblquote Prevent all damage creatures would deal this turn\rdblquote  doesn\rquote t modify any object\rquote s characteristics, so it\rquote s modifying the rules of the game. That means the effect will apply even to damage from creatures that weren\rquote t in play when the continuous effect began. It also affects damage from permanents that become creatures later in the turn.\par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 418.3c If a resolving spell or ability that creates a continuous effect contains a variable, the value of that variable is determined only once, on resolution. See rule 413.2f.\par \par 418.3d Some effects from activated or triggered abilities have durations worded \ldblquote as long as . . . .\rdblquote  If the \ldblquote as long as\rdblquote  duration ends between the end of playing the activated ability or putting the triggered ability onto the stack and the moment when the effect would first be applied, the effect does nothing. It doesn\rquote t start and immediately stop again, and it doesn\rquote t last forever.\par }\pard\plain \s24\li1500\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ Endoskeleton is an artifact with an activated ability that reads \ldblquote \{o2\}, \{oT\}: Target creature gets +0/+3 as long as Endoskeleton remains tapped.\rdblquote  If you play this ability and then Endoskeleton becomes untapped before the ability resolves, it does nothing, because its duration\emdash remaining tapped\emdash was over before the effect began.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 418.4. Continuous Effects from Static Abilities\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {418.4a A continuous effect generated by a static ability isn\rquote t \ldblquote locked in\rdblquote ; it applies at any given moment to whatever its text indicates.\par \par 418.4b The effect applies at all times that the permanent generating it is in play or the object generating it is in the appropriate zone.\par }\pard\plain \s24\li1500\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ A permanent with the static ability \ldblquote All white creatures get +1/+1\rdblquote  generates an effect that continuously gives +1/+1 to each white creature in play. If a creature becomes white, it gets this bonus; a creature that stops being white loses it. A creature spell that would normally create a 1/1 white creature instead creates a 2/2 white creature. The creature doesn\rquote t come into play as 1/1 and then change to 2/2.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 418.5. Interaction of Continuous Effects\par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 418.5a The values of an object\rquote s characteristics are determined by starting with the actual object, then applying continuous effects in a series of layers in the following order: (1) copy effects (see rule 503, \ldblquote Copying Objects\rdblquote ), (2) control-changing effects, (3) text-changing effects, (4) type-, subtype-, and supertype-changing effects, (5) all other continuous effects, except those that change power or toughness, and (6) power- or toughness-changing effects.\par           Inside each layer, apply effects from characteristic-setting abilities first, then effects from all other abilities. For power- or toughness-changing effects, apply changes from counters after changes from characteristic-setting abilities. See also the rules for timestamp order and dependency (rules 418.5b\endash 418.5g).\par }\pard\plain \s24\li1500\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ Crusade is an enchantment that reads \ldblquote White creatures get +1/+1.\rdblquote  Crusade and a 2/2 black creature are in play. If an effect then turns the creature white, it gets +1/+1 from Crusade, becoming 3/3. If the creature\rquote s color is later changed to red, Crusade\rquote s effect stops applying to it, and it will return to being a 2/2.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {418.5b If an effect other than a type-, subtype-, and supertype-changing effect should be applied in different layers, the parts of the effect each apply in their appropriate layers. If a type-, subtype-, and supertype-changing effect should be applied in different layers, all are applied }{\i only}{ in layer four (type-, subtype- and supertype changing effects). \par }\pard\plain \s24\li1500\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ A player plays an ability that reads \ldblquote \{o2\}: Until end of turn, Chimeric Sphere becomes a 3/2 artifact creature,\rdblquote  which is a both a type-changing effect and a power- and toughness-changing effect. Since it\rquote s a type-changing effect, the entire effect is applied when type-changing effects are applied, in layer four, even though power- and toughness-changing effects are normally applied in layer six. Later in the turn, Chimeric Sphere is affected by an ability that reads \ldblquote Target creature becomes 0/2 until end of turn,\rdblquote  which is applied only in layer six since it\rquote s solely a power- and toughness-changing effect. At this point, playing Chimeric Sphere\rquote s (layer 4) ability again won\rquote t do anything, as the layer-six effect will always be applied after it. The artifact creature remains 0/2.\par }{\b Example:}{ An effect that reads \ldblquote Wild Mongrel gets +1/+1 and becomes the color of your choice until end of turn\rdblquote  is both a power- and toughness changing effect and an \ldblquote other\rdblquote  kind of effect. The \ldblquote becomes the color of your choice\rdblquote  part is applied in layer five, and then the \ldblquote gets +1/+1\rdblquote  part is applied in layer six.}{\cf2 \par }{\b Example:}{ Grab the Reins has an effect that reads \ldblquote Until end of turn, you gain control of target creature and it gains haste.\rdblquote  This is both a control-changing effect and an \ldblquote other\rdblquote  effect. The \ldblquote you gain control\rdblquote  part is applied in layer two, and then the \ldblquote it gains haste\rdblquote  part is applied in layer five.\par }\pard\plain \s21\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par }\pard \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 {418.5c An effect is said to \ldblquote depend on\rdblquote  another if }{\i (a) }{it is applied in the same layer as the other effect (see rule 418.5a) and }{\i (b) }{applying the other would change the text or the existence of the first effect, what it applies to, or what it does to any of the things it applies to. Otherwise, the effect is considered to be independent of the other effect.\par \par 418.5d Whenever one effect depends on another, the independent one is applied first. If several dependent effects form a loop, or if none depends on another, they\rquote re applied in \ldblquote timestamp order.\rdblquote \par \par 418.5e An object\rquote s timestamp is the time it entered the zone it\rquote s currently in, with three exceptions: (1) If two or more objects enter a zone (or zones) simultaneously, the active player determines their timestamp order at the time they enter that zone. (2) Whenever a local enchantment or Equipment becomes attached to a permanent, the enchantment or Equipment receives a new timestamp. (3) Permanents that phase in keep the same timestamps they had when they phased out.\par \par 418.5f Continuous effects generated by static abilities have the same timestamp as the objects that generate them.\par \par 418.5g Continuous effects generated by the resolution of a spell or ability receive a timestamp at the time they\rquote re created.\par \par 418.5h One continuous effect can override another. Sometimes the results of one effect determine whether another effect applies or what another effect does.\par }\pard\plain \s24\li1500\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ Two enchantments are played on the same creature: \ldblquote Enchanted creature gains flying\rdblquote  and \ldblquote Enchanted creature loses flying.\rdblquote  Neither of these depends on the other, since nothing changes what they affect or what they\rquote re doing to it. Applying them in timestamp order means the one that was generated last \ldblquote wins.\rdblquote  It\rquote s irrelevant whether an effect is temporary (such as \ldblquote Target creature loses flying until end of turn\rdblquote ) or global (such as \ldblquote All creatures lose flying\rdblquote ).\par }{\b Example:}{ One effect reads, \ldblquote White creatures get +1/+1,\rdblquote  and another, \ldblquote Enchanted creature is white.\rdblquote  The enchanted creature gets +1/+1 from the first effect, regardless of its previous color.\par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 418.5i Some effects can switch a creature\rquote s power and toughness. When they\rquote re applied, they take the value of power and apply it to the object\rquote s toughness, and take the object\rquote s toughness and apply it to the object\rquote s power. Any effects that are applied after the switching effect apply normally.\par }\pard\plain \s24\li1500\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ A 1/3 creature is given +0/+1 by an effect. Then another effect switches the creature\rquote s power and toughness. Its new power and toughness is 4/1. After the \ldblquote switch\rdblquote  effect resolves, another effect gives the creature +5/+0. Its power and toughness is 9/1.\par }{\b Example:}{ A 1/3 creature is given +0/+1 by an effect. Then another effect switches the creature\rquote s power and toughness. Its new power and toughness is 4/1. If the +0/+1 effect ends before the switch effect ends, the creature becomes a 3/1.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 418.6. Text-Changing Effects\par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 418.6a An effect that changes the text of an object changes only those words that are used in the correct way (for example, a }{\b Magic}{ color word being used as a color word, a land type word used as a land type, or a creature type word used as a creature type). The effect can\rquote t change a proper noun, such as a card name, even if that proper noun contains a word or a series of letters that is the same as a }{\b Magic}{ color word, basic land type, or creature type.\par \par 418.6b Effects that add or remove abilities don\rquote t change the text of the objects they affect, so any abilities that are granted to an object can\rquote t be changed by effects that change the text of that object.\par \par 418.6c Spells and abilities that create creature tokens use creature types to define both the creature types and the names of the tokens. These words can be changed, because they are being used as creature types, even though they\rquote re also being used as names.\par \par 418.6d A creature token\rquote s creature type and rules text are defined by the spell or ability that created the token. These characteristics can be changed by text-changing effects.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par }\pard\plain \s19\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {419. Replacement and Prevention Effects\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 419.1. Replacement and prevention effects are continuous effects that watch for a particular event to happen and then completely or partially replace that event. These effects act like \ldblquote shields\rdblquote  around whatever they\rquote re affecting.\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {419.1a Effects that use the word \ldblquote instead\rdblquote  are replacement effects. Most replacement effects use the word \ldblquote instead\rdblquote  to indicate what events will be replaced with other events and use the word \ldblquote skip\rdblquote  to indicate what events, steps, phases, or turns will be replaced with nothing.\par \par 419.1b Effects that read \ldblquote [This permanent] comes into play with . . . ,\rdblquote  \ldblquote As [this permanent] comes into play . . . ,\rdblquote  or \ldblquote [This permanent] comes into play as . . . \rdblquote  are replacement effects.\par \par 419.1c Continuous effects that read \ldblquote [This permanent] comes into play . . .\rdblquote  or \ldblquote [Objects] come into play . . .\rdblquote  are replacement effects.\par \par 419.1d Effects that use the word \ldblquote prevent\rdblquote  are prevention effects. Prevention effects use \ldblquote prevent\rdblquote  to indicate what events will not occur.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 419.2. Replacement and prevention effects apply continuously as events happen\emdash they aren\rquote t locked in ahead of time.\par \par 419.3. There are no special restrictions on playing a spell or ability that generates a replacement or prevention effect. Such effects last until they\rquote re used up or their duration has expired.\par \par 419.4. Replacement or prevention effects must exist before the appropriate event occurs\emdash they can\rquote t \ldblquote go back in time\rdblquote  and change something that\rquote s already happened. Usually spells and abilities that generate these effects are played in response to whatever would produce the event and thus resolve before that event would occur.\par }\pard\plain \s23\li1200\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ A player can play a regeneration ability in response to a spell that would destroy a creature he or she controls.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 419.5. If an event is prevented or replaced, it never happens. A modified event occurs instead, which may in turn trigger abilities. Note that the modified event may contain instructions that can\rquote t be carried out, in which case the player simply ignores the impossible instruction.\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {419.5a If a source would deal 0 damage, it does not deal damage at all. That means abilities that trigger on damage being dealt won\rquote t trigger. It also means that replacement effects that increase damage dealt have no event to replace when 0 damage is dealt, so they have no effect.\par \par 419.5b Some abilities read, \ldblquote Whenever [X], you may [Y]. If you do, [Z].\rdblquote  The \ldblquote if you do\rdblquote  clause refers to choosing to do the event Y, regardless of what events actually occur as a result of that decision. If Y is replaced entirely or in part by a different event, the \ldblquote if you do\rdblquote  clause refers to the event that replaced Y.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 419.6. Replacement Effects\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {419.6a A replacement effect doesn\rquote t invoke itself repeatedly and gets only one opportunity for each event.\par }\pard\plain \s24\li1500\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ A player controls two permanents, each with an ability that reads \ldblquote If a creature you control would deal damage to a creature or player, it deals double that damage to that creature or player instead.\rdblquote  A creature that normally deals 2 damage will deal 8 damage\emdash not just 4, and not an infinite amount.\par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 419.6b Regeneration is a destruction-replacement effect. The word \ldblquote instead\rdblquote  doesn\rquote t appear on the card but is implicit in the definition of regeneration. \ldblquote Regenerate [permanent]\rdblquote  means \ldblquote The next time [permanent] would be destroyed this turn, instead remove all damage from it, tap it, and (if it\rquote s in combat) remove it from combat.\rdblquote  Abilities that trigger from damage being dealt still trigger even if the permanent regenerates.\par \par 419.6c Some effects replace damage dealt to one creature or player with the same damage dealt to another creature or player; such effects are called \ldblquote redirection\rdblquote  effects. If either creature is no longer in play or is no longer a creature when the damage would be redirected, the effect does nothing.\par \par 419.6d Some spells and abilities replace part or all of their own effect(s) when they resolve. Such effects are called }{\i self-replacement effects}{. When applying replacement effects to an event, apply self-replacement effects first, then apply other replacement effects.\par \par 419.6e Skipping an action, step, phase, or turn is a replacement effect. \ldblquote Skip [something]\rdblquote  is the same as \ldblquote Instead of doing [something], do nothing.\rdblquote  Once a step, phase, or turn has started, it can no longer be skipped\emdash any skip effects will wait until the next occurrence.\par \par 419.6f Anything scheduled for a skipped step, phase, or turn won\rquote t happen. Anything scheduled for the \ldblquote next\rdblquote  occurrence of something waits for the first occurrence that isn\rquote t skipped. If two effects each cause a player to skip his or her next occurrence, that player must skip the next two; one effect will be satisfied in skipping the first occurrence, while the other will remain until another occurrence can be skipped.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 419.7. Prevention Effects\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {419.7a Prevention effects usually apply to damage that would be dealt.\par \par 419.7b Some prevention effects refer to a specific amount of damage\emdash for example, \ldblquote Prevent the next 3 damage that would be dealt to target creature or player this turn.\rdblquote  These work like shields. Each 1 damage that would be dealt to the \ldblquote shielded\rdblquote  creature or player is prevented. Preventing 1 damage reduces the remaining shield by 1. If damage would be dealt to the shielded creature or player by two or more sources at the same time, the player or the controller of the creature chooses which damage the shield prevents first. Once the shield has been reduced to 0, any remaining damage is dealt normally. Such effects count only the amount of damage; the number of events or sources dealing it doesn\rquote t matter.\par \par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {419.8. Sources of Damage\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {419.8a Some effects apply to damage from a source\emdash for example, \ldblquote The next time a red source of your choice would deal damage to you this turn, prevent that damage.\rdblquote  If an effect requires a player to choose a source, he or she may choose either a permanent, a spell on the stack (including an artifact, creature, or enchantment spell), or any card or permanent referred to by a spell or ability on the stack. The source is chosen when the effect is created. If the player chooses a permanent, the prevention will apply to the next damage from that permanent, regardless of whether it\rquote s from one of that permanent\rquote s abilities or combat damage dealt by it. If the player chooses an artifact, creature, or enchantment spell, the prevention will apply to any damage from that spell and from the permanent that it becomes when it resolves.\par \par 419.8b Some effects from spells and abilities prevent or replace damage from sources with certain properties, such as a creature or a source of a particular color. When the source would deal damage, the \ldblquote shield\rdblquote  rechecks the source\rquote s properties. If the properties no longer match, the damage isn\rquote t prevented or replaced. If for any reason the shield prevents no damage or replaces no damage, the shield isn\rquote t used up.\par \par 419.8c Some effects from static abilities prevent or replace damage from sources with certain properties. For these effects, the prevention or replacement applies to sources that are permanents with that property and to any sources that aren\rquote t in play that have that property.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 419.9. Interaction of Replacement or Prevention Effects\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {419.9a If two or more replacement or prevention effects are attempting to modify the way an event affects an object or player, the affected object\rquote s controller (or its owner if it has no controller) or the affected player chooses one to apply. Then the other effect applies if it is still appropriate. If one or more of the applicable replacement effects is a self-replacement effect (see rule 419.6d), that effect is applied before any other replacement effects. If both players have to make these choices at the same time, follow the \ldblquote Active Player, Nonactive Player rule\rdblquote  (see rule 103.4).\par }\pard\plain \s24\li1500\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ Two cards are in play. One is an enchantment that reads \ldblquote If a card would be put into a graveyard, instead remove it from the game,\rdblquote  and the other is a creature that reads \ldblquote If [this creature] would be put into a graveyard from play, instead shuffle it into its owner\rquote s library.\rdblquote  The controller of the creature that would be destroyed decides which replacement to apply first; the other does nothing.\par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 419.9b A replacement effect can become applicable to an event as the result of another replacement effect that modifies the event.\par }\pard\plain \s24\li1500\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ One effect reads \ldblquote For each 1 life you would gain, instead draw a card,\rdblquote  and another reads \ldblquote If you would draw a card, return a card from your graveyard to your hand instead.\rdblquote  Both effects combine (regardless of the order they came into existence): Instead of gaining 1 life, the player puts a card from his or her graveyard into his or her hand.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par }\pard\plain \s19\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {420. State-Based Effects\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 420.1. State-based effects are a special category that apply only to those conditions listed below. Abilities that watch for a specified game state are triggered abilities, not state-based effects. (See rule 404, \ldblquote Triggered Abilities.\rdblquote )\par \par 420.2. State-based effects are always active and are not controlled by either player.\par \par 420.3. Whenever a player would get priority (see rule 408, \ldblquote Timing of Spells and Abilities\rdblquote ), the game checks for any of the listed conditions for state-based effects. All applicable effects resolve as a single event, then the check is repeated. Once no more state-based effects have been generated, triggered abilities go on the stack, and then the appropriate player gets priority. This check is also made during the cleanup step (see rule 314); if any of the listed conditions apply, the active player receives priority.\par \par }\pard \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 {420.4. Unlike triggered abilities, state-based effects pay no attention to what happens during the resolution of a spell or ability.\par }\pard\plain \s23\li1200\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ A player controls a creature with the ability \ldblquote This creature\rquote s power and toughness are each equal to the number of cards in your hand\rdblquote  and plays a spell whose effect is \ldblquote Discard your hand, then draw seven cards.\rdblquote  The creature will temporarily have toughness 0 in the middle of the spell\rquote s resolution but will be back up to toughness 7 when the spell finishes resolving. Thus the creature will survive when state-based effects are checked. In contrast, an ability that triggers when the player has no cards in hand goes on the stack after the spell resolves, because its trigger event happened during resolution.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 420.5. The state-based effects are as follows:\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {420.5a A player with 0 or less life loses the game.\par \par 420.5b A creature with toughness 0 or less is put into its owner\rquote s graveyard. Regeneration can\rquote t replace this event.\par \par 420.5c A creature with lethal damage, but greater than 0 toughness, is destroyed. Lethal damage is an amount of damage greater than or equal to a creature\rquote s toughness. Regeneration does replace this event.\par \par 420.5d A local enchantment that enchants an illegal or nonexistent permanent is put into its owner\rquote s graveyard.\par \par 420.5e If two or more permanents with the same name have the subtype Legend or the supertype legendary, all except the one that has been a Legend or legendary permanent with that name the longest are put into their owners\rquote  graveyards. This is called \ldblquote the Legend rule.\rdblquote  In the event of a tie, each Legend or legendary permanent with the same name is put into its owner\rquote s graveyard. (If two permanents have the same name but only one is a Legend or is legendary, this rule doesn\rquote t apply.)\par \par 420.5f A token in a zone other than the in-play zone ceases to exist.\par \par 420.5g A player who was required to draw more cards than were in his or her library since the last time state-based effects were checked loses the game.\par \par 420.5h A player with ten or more poison counters loses the game.\par \par 420.5i If two or more enchant worlds are in play, all except the one that has been an enchant world in play for the shortest amount of time are put into their owners\rquote  graveyards. In the event of a tie for the shortest amount of time, all are put into their owners\rquote  graveyards.\par \par 420.5j A copy of a spell in a zone other than the stack ceases to exist. A copy of a card in any zone other than the stack or the in-play zone ceases to exist.\par \par 420.5k An Equipment that equips an illegal or nonexistent permanent stops equipping that permanent but remains in play.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par }\pard\plain \s19\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {421. Handling \ldblquote Infinite\rdblquote  Loops\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 421.1. Occasionally the game can get into a state in which a set of actions could be repeated forever. These rules (sometimes called the \ldblquote infinity rules\rdblquote ) govern how to break such loops.\par \par 421.2. If the loop contains one or more optional actions and one player controls them all, that player chooses a number. The loop is treated as repeating that many times or until the other player intervenes, whichever comes first.\par \par 421.3. If the loop contains at least one optional action controlled by each player and actions by both players are required to continue the loop, the active player chooses a number. The nonactive player then has two choices. He or she can choose a lower number, in which case the loop continues that number of times plus whatever fraction is necessary for the active player to \ldblquote have the last word.\rdblquote  Or he or she can agree to the number the active player chose, in which case the loop continues that number of times plus whatever fraction is necessary for the nonactive player to \ldblquote have the last word.\rdblquote  (Note that either fraction may be zero.)\par }\pard\plain \s23\li1200\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ One player controls a creature with the ability \ldblquote \{o0\}: [This creature] gains flying.\rdblquote  Another player controls a permanent with the ability \ldblquote \{o0\}: Target creature loses flying.\rdblquote  The \ldblquote infinity rule\rdblquote  ensures that regardless of which player initiated the gain/lose flying ability, the nonactive player will always have the final choice and therefore be able to determine whether the creature has flying. (Note that this assumes that the first player attempted to give the creature flying at least once.)\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 421.4. If the loop contains only mandatory actions, the game ends in a draw. (See rule 102.6.)\par \par 421.5. If the loop contains at least one optional action controlled by each player and these actions don\rquote t depend on one another, the active player chooses a number. The nonactive player can either agree to that number or choose a higher number. Note that this rule applies even if the actions could exist in separate loops rather than in a single loop.\par \par }\pard\plain \s19\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {422. Handling Illegal Actions\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 422.1. If a player realizes that he or she can\rquote t legally take an action after starting to do so, the entire action is reversed and any payments already made are canceled. No abilities trigger and no effects apply as a result of an undone action. If the action was playing a spell, the spell returns to the zone it came from. The player may also reverse any legal mana abilities played while making the illegal play, unless mana from them or from any triggered mana abilities they triggered was spent on another mana ability that wasn\rquote t reversed. Players may not reverse actions that moved cards to a library or from a library to any zone other than the stack. Players may not reverse actions that involved a random choice or random zone change.\par \par 422.2. When reversing illegal spells and abilities, the player who had priority retains it and may take another action or pass. The player may redo the reversed action in a legal way or take any other action allowed by the rules.\par \par }\pard\plain \s17\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\f4\lang1033\cgrid {\page 5. Additional Rules\par }\pard\plain \s16\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par }\pard\plain \s19\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {500. Legal Attacks and Blocks\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 500.1. Some effects restrict declaring attackers or blockers in combat or require certain creatures to be declared as attackers or blockers. (See rule 308, \ldblquote Declare Attackers Step,\rdblquote  and rule 309, \ldblquote Declare Blockers Step.\rdblquote ) A }{\i restriction}{ is an effect which says that a creature can\rquote t block (or attack) or that it can\rquote t block (or attack) unless some condition is met. A }{\i requirement}{ is an effect which says that a creature must block (or attack) or that it must block (or attack) if some condition is met.\par \par 500.2. As part of declaring attackers, the active player checks each creature he or she controls to see whether it must attack, can\rquote t attack, or has some other attacking restriction or requirement. If such a restriction or requirement conflicts with the proposed attack, the attack is illegal, and the active player must then propose another set of attacking creatures. (Tapped creatures and creatures with unpaid costs to attack are exempt from effects that would require them to attack.)\par }\pard\plain \s23\li1200\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ A player controls two creatures, each with a restriction that states \ldblquote [This creature] can\rquote t attack alone.\rdblquote  It\rquote s legal to declare both as attackers.\par }{\b Example:}{ A player controls two creatures: one that \ldblquote attacks if able\rdblquote  and one with no abilities. An effect states, \ldblquote No more than one creature may attack each turn.\rdblquote  The only legal attack is for just the creature that \ldblquote attacks if able\rdblquote  to attack. It\rquote s illegal to attack with the other creature, attack with both, or attack with neither.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 500.3. As part of declaring blockers, the defending player checks each creature he or she controls to see whether it must block, can\rquote t block, or has some other blocking restriction or requirement. If such a restriction or requirement conflicts with the proposed set of blocking creatures, the block is illegal, and the defending player must then propose another set of blocking creatures. (Tapped creatures and creatures with unpaid costs to block are exempt from effects that would require them to block.)\par \par 500.4. A restriction conflicts with a proposed set of attackers or blockers if it isn\rquote t being followed. A requirement conflicts with a proposed set of attackers or blockers if it isn\rquote t being followed and (1) the requirement could be obeyed without violating a restriction and (2) doing so will allow the total number of requirements that the set obeys to increase.\par \par 500.5. When determining what requirements could be obeyed without violating restrictions, you don\rquote t need to consider any options for a creature that don\rquote t satisfy a requirement on it. But you do need to consider any options for any creature(s) that will satisfy a requirement, as long as the total number of obeyed requirements is increased (even if the option means not obeying another requirement that was previously met).\par }\pard\plain \s23\li1200\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ A player controls one creature that \ldblquote blocks if able\rdblquote  and another creature with no abilities. An effect states, \ldblquote Creatures can\rquote t be blocked except by two or more creatures.\rdblquote  The creature with no abilities isn\rquote t required to block. It\rquote s legal to declare both creatures as blockers, or to declare neither creature as a blocker, but illegal to block with only one of the two.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par }\pard\plain \s19\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {501. Evasion Abilities\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 501.1. Evasion abilities restrict what can block an attacking creature. These are static abilities that modify the declare blockers step of combat.\par \par 501.2. Evasion abilities are cumulative.\par }\pard\plain \s23\li1200\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ A Wall without flying can\rquote t block a creature that can be blocked only by Walls and by creatures with flying.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 501.3. Some creatures have abilities that restrict how they can block. As with evasion abilities, these modify only the rules for the declare blockers step of combat. (If a creature gains or loses an evasion ability after a legal block has been declared, it doesn\rquote t affect that block.)\par \par }\pard\plain \s19\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {502. Keyword Abilities\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 502.1. Most abilities describe exactly what they do in the card\rquote s rules text. Some, though, are very common or would require too much space to define on the card. In these cases, the object lists only the name of the ability as a \ldblquote keyword\rdblquote ; sometimes reminder text summarizes the game rule.\par \par 502.2. First Strike\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {502.2a First strike is a static ability that modifies the rules for the combat damage step. (See rule 310, \ldblquote Combat Damage Step.\rdblquote )\par \par 502.2b At the start of the combat damage step, if at least one attacking or blocking creature has first strike or double strike (see rule 502.28), creatures without first strike or double strike don\rquote t assign combat damage. Instead of proceeding to end of combat, the phase gets a second combat damage step to handle the remaining creatures. In the second combat damage step, surviving attackers and blockers that didn\rquote t assign combat damage in the first step, plus any creatures with double strike, assign their combat damage.\par \par 502.2c Adding or removing first strike after the first combat damage step won\rquote t prevent a creature from dealing combat damage or allow it to deal combat damage twice.\par \par 502.2d Multiple instances of first strike on the same creature are redundant.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 502.3. Flanking\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {502.3a Flanking is a triggered ability that triggers during the declare blockers step. (See rule 309, \ldblquote Declare Blockers Step.\rdblquote ) \ldblquote Flanking\rdblquote  means \ldblquote Whenever this creature becomes blocked by a creature without flanking, the blocking creature gets -1/-1 until end of turn.\rdblquote \par \par 502.3b If a creature has multiple instances of flanking, each triggers separately.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 502.4. Flying\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {502.4a Flying is an evasion ability.\par \par 502.4b A creature with flying can\rquote t be blocked by creatures without flying. A creature with flying can block a creature with or without flying. (See rule 309, \ldblquote Declare Blockers Step.\rdblquote )\par \par 502.4c Multiple instances of flying on the same creature are redundant.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 502.5. Haste\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {502.5a Haste is a static ability.\par \par 502.5b A creature with haste can attack or use activated abilities whose cost includes the tap symbol even if it hasn\rquote t been controlled by its controller continuously since the beginning of his or her most recent turn. (See rule 212.3d.)\par \par 502.5c Multiple instances of haste on the same creature are redundant.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 502.6. Landwalk\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {502.6a Landwalk and snow-covered landwalk are generic terms; a card\rquote s rules text will give a specific subtype or supertype (such as in \ldblquote islandwalk,\rdblquote  \ldblquote snow-covered swampwalk,\rdblquote  or \ldblquote legendary landwalk\rdblquote ).\par \par 502.6b Landwalk and snow-covered landwalk are evasion abilities. A creature with landwalk is unblockable as long as the defending player controls at least one land with the specified subtype or supertype. (See rule 309, \ldblquote Declare Blockers Step.\rdblquote )\par \par 502.6c Snow-covered landwalk is a special type of landwalk. A creature with snow-covered landwalk is unblockable as long as the defending player controls at least one land with the specified subtype or supertype that has snow-covered. If a player is allowed to choose any landwalk ability, that player may choose a snow-covered landwalk ability. If an effect causes a permanent to lose all landwalk abilities, snow-covered landwalk abilities are removed as well.\par \par 502.6d Landwalk or snow-covered landwalk abilities don\rquote t \ldblquote cancel\rdblquote  one another.\par }\pard\plain \s24\li1500\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ If a player controls a snow-covered Forest, that player can\rquote t block an attacking creature with snow-covered forestwalk even if he or she also controls a creature with snow-covered forestwalk.\par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 502.6e Multiple instances of the same type of landwalk or snow-covered landwalk on the same creature are redundant.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 502.7. Protection\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {502.7a Protection is a static ability, written \ldblquote Protection from [quality].\rdblquote  This quality is usually a color (as in \ldblquote protection from black\rdblquote ) but can be any characteristic value. If the quality is a type, subtype, or supertype, the protection applies to sources that are permanents with that type, subtype, or supertype and to any sources not in play that are of that type, subtype, or supertype.\par \par 502.7b A permanent with protection can\rquote t be targeted by spells with the stated quality and can\rquote t be targeted by abilities from a source with the stated quality.\par \par 502.7c A permanent with protection can\rquote t be enchanted by enchantments that have the stated quality. Such enchantments enchanting the permanent with protection will be put into their owners\rquote  graveyards as a state-based effect. (See rule 420, \ldblquote State-Based Effects.\rdblquote )\par \par 502.7d A permanent with protection can\rquote t be equipped by Equipment that have the stated quality. Such an Equipment stops equipping that permanent, but remains in play. (See rule 420, \ldblquote State-Based Effects.\rdblquote )\par \par 502.7e Any damage that would be dealt by sources that have the stated quality to a permanent that has protection is prevented.\par \par 502.7f If a creature with protection attacks, it can\rquote t be blocked by creatures that have the stated quality.\par \par 502.7g Multiple instances of protection from the same quality on the same permanent are redundant.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 502.8. Shadow\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {502.8a Shadow is an evasion ability.\par \par 502.8b A creature with shadow can\rquote t be blocked by creatures without shadow, and a creature without shadow can\rquote t be blocked by creatures with shadow. (See rule 309, \ldblquote Declare Blockers Step.\rdblquote )\par \par 502.8c Multiple instances of shadow on the same creature are redundant.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 502.9. Trample\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {502.9a Trample is a static ability that modifies the rules for assigning an attacking creature\rquote s combat damage. A creature with trample has no special abilities when blocking or dealing noncombat damage. (See rule 310, \ldblquote Combat Damage Step.\rdblquote )\par \par 502.9b The controller of an attacking creature with trample first assigns damage to the creature(s) blocking it. If all those blocking creatures are assigned lethal damage, any remaining damage is assigned as its controller chooses among the blocking creatures and the defending player. When checking for assigned lethal damage, take into account damage already on the creature and damage from other creatures that is to be assigned at the same time (see rule 502.9e). The controller need not assign lethal damage to all blocking creatures but in that case can\rquote t assign any damage to the defending player.\par \par 502.9c If all the creatures blocking an attacking creature with trample are removed from combat before the combat damage step, all its damage is assigned to the defending player.\par \par 502.9d Assigning damage from a creature with trample considers only the actual toughness of a blocking creature, not any abilities or effects that might change the final amount of damage dealt.\par }\pard\plain \s24\li1500\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ A 6/6 green creature with trample is blocked by a 2/2 creature with protection from green. The attacking creature\rquote s controller must assign at least 2 damage to the blocker, even though that damage will be prevented by the blocker\rquote s protection ability. The attacking creature\rquote s controller can then choose to assign the rest of the damage to the defending player.\par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 502.9e When there are several attacking creatures, it\rquote s legal to assign damage from those without trample so as to maximize the damage of those with trample.\par }\pard\plain \s24\li1500\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ A 2/2 creature with an ability that enables it to block multiple attackers blocks two attackers: a 1/1 with no special abilities a 3/3 with trample. The attacking player could assign 1 damage from the first attacker and 1 damage from the second to the blocking creature, and 2 damage to the defending player from the creature with trample.\par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 502.9f Multiple instances of trample on the same creature are redundant.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 502.10. Banding\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {502.10a Banding is a static ability that modifies the rules for declaring attackers and assigning combat damage.\par \par 502.10b As a player declares attackers, he or she may declare that any number of those creatures with banding, and up to one of those creatures without banding, are all in a \ldblquote band.\rdblquote  (Defending players can\rquote t declare bands but may use banding in a different way; see rule 502.10h.)\par \par 502.10c A player may declare as many attacking bands as he or she wants, but each creature may be a member of only one of them.\par \par 502.10d Once an attacking band has been announced, it lasts for the rest of combat, even if something later removes the banding ability from one or more creatures. However, creatures in a band that are removed from combat are also removed from the band.\par \par 502.10e If an attacking creature becomes blocked by a creature, each other creature in the same band as the attacking creature becomes blocked by that same blocking creature.\par }\pard\plain \s24\li1500\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ A player attacks with a band consisting of a creature with flying and a creature with swampwalk. The defending player, who controls a Swamp, can block the flying creature if able. If he or she does, then the creature with swampwalk will also become blocked by the blocking creature(s).\par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 502.10f Banding doesn\rquote t cause attacking creatures to share abilities, nor does it remove any abilities. The attacking creatures in a band are separate permanents.\par \par 502.10g If one member of a band would become blocked due to an effect, the entire band becomes blocked.\par \par 502.10h A player who controls an attacking creature with banding chooses how combat damage is assigned by creatures blocking that creature. A player who controls a blocking creature with banding chooses how combat damage is assigned by creatures it blocks. If the creature had banding when it attacked or blocked, but the ability was removed before the combat damage step, damage is assigned normally.\par \par 502.10i Multiple instances of banding on the same creature are redundant.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 502.11. Bands with Other\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {502.11a Bands with other is a special form of banding. If an effect causes a permanent to lose banding, the permanent loses all bands with other abilities as well.\par \par 502.11b An attacking creature with \ldblquote bands with other [creature type]\rdblquote  can form an attacking band with other creatures that have the same \ldblquote bands with other [creature type]\rdblquote  ability. Creatures with banding can also join this band, but creatures without banding can\rquote t. The creatures in this band don\rquote t have to have the creature type specified in the \ldblquote bands with other [creature type]\rdblquote  ability. Blocking this band follows the same general rules as for banding.\par \par 502.11c If an attacking creature is blocked by at least two creatures with the same \ldblquote bands with other [creature type]\rdblquote  ability, the defending player chooses how the attacking creature\rquote s damage is assigned. Similarly, if a blocking creature blocks at least two attacking creatures with the same \ldblquote bands with other [creature type]\rdblquote  ability, the attacking player chooses how the blocking creature\rquote s damage is assigned.\par \par 502.11d Multiple instances of bands with other of the same type on the same creature are redundant.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 502.12. Rampage\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {502.12a Rampage is a triggered ability. \ldblquote Rampage [X]\rdblquote  means \ldblquote Whenever this creature becomes blocked, it gets +X/+X until end of turn for each creature blocking it beyond the first.\rdblquote  (See rule 309, \ldblquote Declare Blockers Step.\rdblquote )\par \par 502.12b The rampage bonus is calculated only once per combat, when the triggered ability resolves. Adding or removing blockers later in combat won\rquote t change the bonus.\par \par 502.12c If a creature has multiple instances of rampage, each triggers separately.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 502.13. Cumulative Upkeep\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {502.13a Cumulative upkeep is a triggered ability that imposes an increasing cost on a permanent. The phrase \ldblquote Cumulative upkeep [cost]\rdblquote  means \ldblquote At the beginning of your upkeep, put an age counter on this permanent, then sacrifice this permanent unless you pay [cost] for each age counter on it.\rdblquote \par \par 502.13b If a permanent has multiple instances of cumulative upkeep, each triggers separately. However, the age counters are not linked to any particular ability; each cumulative upkeep ability will count the total number of age counters on the permanent at the time that ability resolves.\par }\pard\plain \s24\li1500\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ A creature has two instances of \ldblquote Cumulative upkeep\emdash Pay 1 life.\rdblquote  The creature currently has no counters but both cumulative upkeep abilities trigger. When the first ability resolves, the controller adds a counter and then chooses to pay 1 life. When the second ability resolves, the controller adds another counter and then chooses to pay an additional 2 life.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 502.14. Snow-Covered\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {502.14a Snow-covered is an ability that doesn\rquote t do anything in its own right; it\rquote s simply a keyword that other cards look for. When a rule or an effect refers to a \ldblquote snow-covered land,\rdblquote  it means a land with the snow-covered ability. When a rule or an effect refers to a \ldblquote snow-covered Forest,\rdblquote  it means a Forest with the snow-covered ability, and so on.\par \par 502.14b Five snow-covered lands were printed in the }{\i Ice Age\u8482\'aa}{ expansion. Their names are Snow-Covered Plains, Snow-Covered Island, Snow-Covered Swamp, Snow-Covered Mountain, and Snow-Covered Forest. These lands are basic lands, even though they have a different name and they have the snow-covered ability.\par \par 502.14c Some effects can add or remove the snow-covered ability. This doesn\rquote t change the existing name of the land, or any types, subtypes, or supertypes it has. For example, a card named Snow-Covered Forest is named \ldblquote Snow-Covered Forest,\rdblquote  while a Forest that has been granted the snow-covered ability is still named \ldblquote Forest.\rdblquote \par \par 502.14d Multiple instances of snow-covered on the same land are redundant.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 502.15. Phasing\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {502.15a Phasing is a static ability that modifies the rules of the untap step.\par \par 502.15b During each player\rquote s untap step, before the active player untaps his or her permanents, all permanents with phasing the player controls phase out. Simultaneously, all objects that had phased out under that player\rquote s control phase in. (See rule 217.8, \ldblquote Phased-Out,\rdblquote  and rule 302.1.)\par \par 502.15c If an effect causes a player to skip his or her untap step, the phasing event simply doesn\rquote t occur that turn.\par \par 502.15d Permanents phasing in don\rquote t trigger any comes-into-play abilities, and effects that modify how a permanent comes into play are ignored. Abilities and effects that specifically mention phasing can modify or trigger on this event, however. Permanents phasing out trigger leaves-play abilities as usual. (Because no player receives priority during the untap step, any abilities triggering off of the phasing event won\rquote t go onto the stack until the upkeep step begins.)\par \par 502.15e When a permanent phases out, all damage dealt to it is removed.\par \par 502.15f A card that returns to play from the phased-out zone is considered the same permanent it was when it left. This is an exception to rule 217.1c, which stipulates that a permanent \ldblquote forgets\rdblquote  its previous existence when it changes zones.\par \par 502.15g Effects with limited duration and delayed triggered abilities that specifically reference a permanent will be unable to further affect that permanent if it phases out. However, other effects that reference the permanent (including effects with unlimited duration) can affect the permanent when it returns to play.\par }\pard\plain \s24\li1500\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ A creature is affected by Giant Growth and then phases out during the same turn. If the creature phases back in somehow before the turn is over, it won\rquote t get the +3/+3 bonus from the Giant Growth because its effect has a limited duration.\par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 502.15h Phased-out cards \ldblquote remember\rdblquote  their past histories and will return to play in the same state. They \ldblquote remember\rdblquote  any counters they had on them, any choices made when they first came into play, and whether they were tapped or untapped when they left play. They also \ldblquote remember\rdblquote  who controlled them when they phased out, although they may phase in under the control of a different player if a control effect with limited duration has expired.\par }\pard\plain \s24\li1500\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ Diseased Vermin reads, in part, \ldblquote At the beginning of your upkeep, Diseased Vermin deals X damage to target opponent previously dealt damage by it, where X is the number of infection counters on it.\rdblquote  If Diseased Vermin phases out, it \ldblquote remembers\rdblquote  how many counters it has and also which opponents it has previously damaged. When it phases back in, it will still be able to target those opponents with its upkeep-triggered ability.\par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 502.15i When a permanent phases out, any local enchantments or Equipment attached to that permanent phase out at the same time. This alternate way of phasing out is known as phasing out \ldblquote indirectly.\rdblquote  An enchantment or Equipment that phased out indirectly won\rquote t phase in by itself, but instead phases in along with the card it\rquote s attached to.\par \par 502.15j If a local enchantment or Equipment phased out directly (rather than phasing out along with the permanent it\rquote s attached to), then it \ldblquote remembers\rdblquote  the permanent it was enchanting or equipping and returns to play attached to that permanent. If a local enchantment phases in and the permanent has left play or is no longer legal to enchant, the enchantment returns to play and then is placed in its owner\rquote s graveyard afterwards. This is a state-based effect; see rule 420. If an Equipment phases in and the permanent has left play or is no longer legal to equip, the Equipment returns to play and then stays in play, not equipping anything. This is a state-based effect; see rule 420.\par \par 502.15k Permanents that phase in keep the same timestamps (see rules 418.5d and 418.5e) they had when they phased out. This doesn\rquote t change the fact that the permanents phase in simultaneously, however. For example, if two Legends with the same name phase in, they both go to their owners\rquote  graveyards.\par \par 502.15m A permanent that phases in can attack and tap to play abilities as though it had haste. This applies even if that permanent phased out and phased back in the turn it came into play. The permanent remains able to attack and tap to play abilities until it changes controllers or leaves play.\par \par 502.15n A spell or ability that targets a permanent will resolve normally with respect to that permanent if the permanent phases out and back in before the spell or ability resolves.\par \par 502.15p Multiple instances of phasing on the same permanent are redundant.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 502.16. Buyback\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {502.16a Buyback is a static ability of some instants and sorceries that functions while the spell is on the stack. The phrase \ldblquote Buyback [cost]\rdblquote  means \ldblquote You may pay an additional [cost] as you play this spell. If you do, put the spell into your hand instead of into your graveyard as it resolves.\rdblquote  Paying a spell\rquote s buyback cost follows the rules for paying additional costs in rules 409.1b and 409.1f\endash h.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 502.17. Horsemanship\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {502.17a Horsemanship is an evasion ability that appeared in the }{\i Portal Three Kingdoms\u8482\'aa}{ set.\par \par 502.17b A creature with horsemanship can\rquote t be blocked by creatures without horsemanship. A creature with horsemanship can block a creature with or without horsemanship. (See rule 309, \ldblquote Declare Blockers Step.\rdblquote )\par \par 502.17c Multiple instances of horsemanship on the same creature are redundant.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 502.18. Cycling\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {502.18a Cycling is an activated ability that functions only while the card with cycling is in a player\rquote s hand. The phrase \ldblquote Cycling [cost]\rdblquote  means \ldblquote [Cost], Discard this card from your hand: Draw a card.\rdblquote \par \par 502.18b Although the cycling ability is playable only if the card is in a player\rquote s hand, it continues to exist while the object is in play and in all other zones. Therefore objects with cycling will be affected by effects that depend on objects having one or more activated abilities.\par \par 502.18c Landcycling is a variant of the cycling ability. The phrase \ldblquote [Land type]cycling [cost]\rdblquote  means \ldblquote [Cost], Discard this card from your hand: Search your library for a [land type] card, reveal it, and put it into your hand. Then shuffle your library.\rdblquote  Any cards that trigger when a player cycles a card will trigger when a card\rquote s landcycling ability is played. Any effect that stops players from cycling cards will stop players from playing cards\rquote  landcycling abilities.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 502.19. Echo\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {502.19a Echo is a triggered ability. \ldblquote Echo\rdblquote  means \ldblquote At the beginning of your upkeep, if this permanent came under your control since the beginning of your last upkeep, sacrifice it unless you pay its mana cost.\rdblquote \par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 502.20. Fading\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {502.20a Fading is a keyword that represents two abilities. The phrase \ldblquote Fading [X]\rdblquote  means \ldblquote This permanent comes into play with X fade counters on it\rdblquote  and \ldblquote At the beginning of your upkeep, remove a fade counter from this permanent. If you can\rquote t, sacrifice the permanent.\rdblquote \par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 502.21. Kicker\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {502.21a Kicker is a static ability that functions while the spell is on the stack. The phrase \ldblquote Kicker [cost]\rdblquote  means \ldblquote You may pay an additional [cost] as you play this spell.\rdblquote  The phrase \ldblquote Kicker [cost 1] and/or [cost 2]\rdblquote  means the same thing as \ldblquote Kicker [cost 1], kicker [cost 2].\rdblquote  Paying a spell\rquote s kicker cost(s) follows the rules for paying additional costs in rules 409.1b and 409.1f\endash h.\par \par 502.21b Objects with kicker have additional abilities that specify what happens if the kicker cost is paid. Objects with more than one kicker cost have abilities that correspond to each kicker cost.\par \par 502.21c If the text that depends on a kicker cost being paid targets one or more permanents and/or players, the spell\rquote s controller chooses those targets only if he or she declared the intention to pay the appropriate kicker cost. Otherwise, the targets aren\rquote t chosen at all.\par \par 502.21d A card with kicker may contain the phrases \ldblquote if the [A] kicker cost was paid\rdblquote  and \ldblquote if the [B] kicker cost was paid,\rdblquote  where A and B are the first and second kicker costs listed on the card, respectively. This text just refers to one kicker cost or the other, regardless of what the spell\rquote s controller actually spent when paying the cost. In other words, read \ldblquote if the [A] kicker cost was paid\rdblquote  as \ldblquote if the first kicker cost listed was paid,\rdblquote  and read \ldblquote if the [B] kicker cost was paid\rdblquote  as \ldblquote if the second kicker cost listed was paid.\rdblquote \par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 502.22. Flashback\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {502.22a Flashback is a static ability of some instant and sorcery cards that functions while the card is in a player\rquote s graveyard. The phrase \ldblquote Flashback [cost]\rdblquote  means \ldblquote You may play this card from your graveyard by paying [cost] rather than paying its mana cost. If you do, remove this card from the game instead of putting it anywhere else any time it would leave the stack.\rdblquote  Playing a spell using its flashback ability follows the rules for paying alternative costs in rules 409.1b and 409.1f\endash h.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 502.23. Threshold\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {502.23a Threshold is a characteristic-setting ability, written \ldblquote Threshold \emdash  [text].\rdblquote  It alters the rules text of the object it\rquote s on, based on a condition. The text can create any kind of ability. The phrase \ldblquote Threshold \emdash  [text]\rdblquote  means \ldblquote As long as you have seven or more cards in your graveyard, [this object] has \lquote [text].\rquote \rdblquote \par \par 502.23b Spells and permanents with threshold have the threshold text only if their controller has seven or more cards in his or her graveyard. Otherwise, the text after \ldblquote Threshold \emdash \rdblquote  is treated as though it did not appear on the spell or permanent.\par \par 502.23c An instant or sorcery with threshold has the threshold text only while the spell is on the stack. An artifact, creature, enchantment, or land with threshold has the threshold text only if the permanent is in play. \par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 502.24. Madness\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {502.24a Madness is a keyword that represents two abilities. The first is a static ability that functions while the card with madness is in a player\rquote s hand. The second is a triggered ability that functions when the first ability is applied. The phrase \ldblquote Madness [cost]\rdblquote  means \ldblquote If a player would discard this card from his or her hand, that player discards it, but may remove it from the game instead of putting it into his or her graveyard\rdblquote  and \ldblquote When this card is removed from the game this way, until that player passes next, the player may play it any time he or she could play an instant as though it were in his or her hand by paying [cost] rather than paying its mana cost. When the player passes next, he or she puts this card into his or her graveyard.\rdblquote \par \par 502.24b Playing a spell using its madness ability follows the rules for paying alternative costs in rules 409.1b and 409.1f\endash h.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 502.25. Fear\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {502.25a Fear is an evasion ability.\par \par 502.25b A creature with fear can\rquote t be blocked except by artifact creatures and/or black creatures. (See rule 309, \ldblquote Declare Blockers Step.\rdblquote )\par \par 502.25c Multiple instances of fear on the same creature are redundant.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 502.26. Morph\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {502.26a Morph is a static ability that functions in any zone from which you could play the card it\rquote s on, and the morph effect works any time the card is face down. The phrase \ldblquote Morph [cost]\rdblquote  means \ldblquote You may play this card as a 2/2 face-down creature, with no text, no name, no subtypes, no expansion symbol, and a mana cost of \{o0\} by paying \{o3\} rather than its mana cost.\rdblquote  Any time you could play an instant, you may show all players the morph cost for any face-down permanent you control, pay that cost, then turn the permanent face up. This action does not use the stack. (See rule 504, \ldblquote Face-Down Spells and Permanents.\rdblquote )\par \par 502.26b To play a card using its morph ability, turn it face down. It becomes a 2/2 face-down creature card, with no text, no name, no subtypes, no expansion symbol, and a mana cost of \{o0\}. These values are the copiable values of that object\rquote s characteristics. (See rule 418.5, \ldblquote Interaction of Continuous Effects,\rdblquote  and rule 503, \ldblquote Copying Objects.\rdblquote ) Put it onto the stack (as a face-down spell with the same characteristics), and pay \{o3\} rather than pay its mana cost. This follows the rules for paying alternative costs. You can use morph to play a card from any zone from which you could normally play it. When the spell resolves, it comes into play with the same characteristics the spell had. The morph effect applies to the face-down object wherever it is, and it ends when the permanent is turned face up.\par \par 502.26c You can\rquote t play a card face down if it doesn\rquote t have morph.\par \par 502.26d Any time you could play an instant, you may turn a face-down permanent you control face up. To do this, show all players what the permanent\rquote s morph cost will be when the effect ends, pay that cost, then turn the permanent face up. The morph effect on it ends, and it regains its normal characteristics. Any abilities relating to the permanent coming into play don\rquote t trigger when it\rquote s turned face up and don\rquote t have any effect, because the permanent has already come into play.\par \par 502.26e If a face-up permanent is turned face down by a spell or ability, it becomes a 2/2 face-down creature, with no text, no name, no subtypes, no expansion symbol, and a mana cost of \{o0\}. These values are the copiable values of that object\rquote s characteristics. (See rule 418.5, \ldblquote Interaction of Continuous Effects,\rdblquote  and rule 503, \ldblquote Copying Objects.\rdblquote ) The rules for morph and face-down permanents apply to it normally.\par \par 502.26f See rule 504, \ldblquote Face-Down Spells and Permanents,\rdblquote  for more information on how to play cards with morph.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 502.27. Amplify\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {502.27a Amplify is a static ability. \ldblquote Amplify [X]\rdblquote  means \ldblquote As this object comes into play, reveal any number of cards from your hand that share a creature type with it. This permanent comes into play with X +1/+1 counters on it for each card revealed this way. You can\rquote t reveal this card or any other cards that are coming into play at the same time as this card.\rdblquote \par \par 502.27b If a creature has multiple instances of amplify, each one works separately.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 502.28. Double Strike\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {502.28a Double strike is a static ability that modifies the rules for the combat damage step. (See rule 310, \ldblquote Combat Damage Step.\rdblquote )\par \par 502.28b At the start of the combat damage step, if at least one attacking or blocking creature has double strike or first strike, creatures without double strike or first strike (see rule 502.2, \ldblquote First Strike\rdblquote ) don\rquote t assign combat damage. Instead of proceeding to end of combat, the phase gets a second combat damage step to handle the remaining creatures. In the second combat damage step, surviving attackers and blockers that didn\rquote t assign combat damage in the first step, plus any creatures with double strike, assign their combat damage.\par \par 502.28c Removing double strike from a creature during the first combat damage step will stop it from assigning combat damage in the second combat damage step.\par \par 502.28d Giving double strike to a creature with first strike after it has already put first strike combat damage onto the stack in the first combat damage step will allow the creature to assign combat damage in the second combat damage step.\par \par 502.28e Multiple instances of double strike on the same creature are redundant.\par \par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {502.29. Provoke\par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 502.29a Provoke is a triggered ability. \ldblquote Provoke\rdblquote  means \ldblquote Whenever this creature attacks, you may choose to have target creature defending player controls block this creature this combat if able. If you do, untap that creature.\rdblquote \par \par 502.29b If a creature has multiple instances of provoke, each triggers separately.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 502.30. Storm\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {502.30a Storm is a triggered ability that functions while the spell is on the stack. \ldblquote Storm\rdblquote  means \ldblquote When you play this spell, put a copy of it onto the stack for each other spell that was played before it this turn. If the spell has any targets, you may choose new targets for any number of the copies.\rdblquote \par \par 502.30b If a spell has multiple instances of storm, each triggers separately.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 502.31. Affinity\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {502.31a Affinity is a static ability that functions while the spell is on the stack. \ldblquote Affinity for [text]\rdblquote  means \ldblquote This spell costs you \{o1\} less to play for each [text] you control.\rdblquote \par \par 502.31b The affinity ability reduces only generic mana costs; it doesn\rquote t reduce how much colored mana you have to pay for a spell. Affinity can\rquote t reduce the cost to play a spell to less than 0.\par \par 502.31c If a spell has multiple instances of affinity, each of them applies.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 502.32. Entwine\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {502.32a Entwine is a static ability that functions while the spell is on the stack. The phrase \ldblquote Entwine [cost]\rdblquote  means \ldblquote You may choose to use all modes of this spell instead of just one. If you do, you pay an additional [cost].\rdblquote  Using the entwine ability follows the rules for choosing modes and paying additional costs in rules 409.1b and 409.1f\endash h.\par \par 502.32b If the entwine cost was paid, follow the text of each of the modes in the order written on the card when the spell resolves.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 502.33. Equip\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {502.33a Equip is an activated ability of artifact Equipment cards. The phrase \ldblquote Equip [cost]\rdblquote  means \ldblquote [cost]: Move this Equipment onto target creature you control. Play this ability only any time you could play a sorcery.\rdblquote \par \par 502.33b For more information about Equipment, see rule 212.2, \ldblquote Artifacts.\rdblquote \par \par 502.33c If an artifact has multiple instances of equip, any of its equip abilities may be used.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 502.34. Imprint\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {502.34a Imprint is an activated or triggered ability, written \ldblquote Imprint \emdash  [text],\rdblquote  where \ldblquote [text]\rdblquote  is a triggered or activated ability. Cards that are in the removed-from-game zone because they were removed from the game by an imprint ability are imprinted on the source of that ability.\par \par 502.34b The phrase \ldblquote imprinted [type] card\rdblquote  means the card of that type that\rquote s imprinted on the permanent. If a permanent has more than one card of that type imprinted on it, each of those cards is an \ldblquote imprinted [type] card.\rdblquote \par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 502.35. Modular\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {502.35a Modular represents both a static ability and a triggered ability. \ldblquote Modular X\rdblquote  means \ldblquote This permanent comes into play with X +1/+1 counters on it\rdblquote  and \ldblquote When this permanent is put into a graveyard from play, you may put a +1/+1 counter on target artifact creature for each +1/+1 counter on this permanent.\rdblquote \par \par 502.35b If a creature has multiple instances of modular, each one works separately.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par }\pard\plain \s19\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {503. Copying Objects\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 503.1. Some objects create or become a \ldblquote copy\rdblquote  of a spell, permanent, or card. (Certain older cards were printed with the phrase \ldblquote search for a copy.\rdblquote  This section doesn\rquote t cover those cards, which have received new text in the Oracle card reference.)\par \par 503.2. When copying an object, the copy acquires the copiable values of the original object\rquote s characteristics (name, mana cost, color, type, supertype, subtype, expansion symbol, rules text, power, and toughness) and, for an object on the stack, choices made when playing it (mode, targets, the value of X, whether a kicker cost was paid, how it will affect multiple targets, and so on). The \ldblquote copiable values\rdblquote  are the values that are printed on the object, as modified by other copy effects, plus any values set for face-down spells or permanents. Other effects (including type-changing effects) and counters are not copied.\par }\pard\plain \s23\li1200\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ Chimeric Staff is an artifact that reads \ldblquote \{oX\}: Chimeric Staff becomes an X/X artifact creature until end of turn.\rdblquote  Clone is a creature that reads, \ldblquote As Clone comes into play, you may choose a creature in play. If you do, Clone comes into play as a copy of that creature.\rdblquote  After a Staff has become a 5/5 artifact creature, a Clone comes into play as a copy of it. The Clone is an artifact, not a 5/5 artifact creature. (The copy has the Staff\rquote s ability, however, and will become a creature if that ability is activated.)\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 503.3. The copied information becomes the copiable values for the copy, replacing its previous copiable values. Objects that copy the object will use the new copiable values.\par }\pard\plain \s23\li1200\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ Vesuvan Doppelganger reads, \ldblquote As Vesuvan Doppelganger comes into play, you may choose a creature in play. If you do, Vesuvan Doppelganger comes into play as a copy of that creature except for its color and gains \lquote At the beginning of your upkeep, you may have this creature become a copy of target creature except for its color. If you do, this creature gains this ability.\rquote \rdblquote  A Vesuvan Doppelganger comes into play as a copy of Grizzly Bears (a 2/2 green creature with no abilities). Then a Clone comes into play as a copy of the Doppelganger. The Clone is a 2/2 blue Bear named Grizzly Bears that has the Doppelganger\rquote s upkeep-triggered ability.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 503.4. Some effects cause a permanent that\rquote s copying a permanent to copy a different permanent while remaining in play. The change doesn\rquote t trigger comes-into-play or leaves-play abilities. This also doesn\rquote t change any noncopy effects presently affecting the permanent.\par }\pard\plain \s23\li1200\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ Unstable Shapeshifter reads, \ldblquote Whenever a creature comes into play, Unstable Shapeshifter becomes a copy of that creature and gains this ability.\rdblquote  A Shapeshifter is affected by Giant Growth, which reads \ldblquote Target creature gets +3/+3 until end of turn.\rdblquote  If a creature comes into play later this turn, the Shapeshifter will become a copy of that creature, but it will still get +3/+3 from the Giant Growth.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 503.5. An object that comes into play \ldblquote as a copy\rdblquote  of another permanent becomes a copy as it comes into play. It doesn\rquote t come into play, and then become a copy of that permanent. If the text that\rquote s being copied includes any abilities that replace the comes-into-play event (such as \ldblquote comes into play with\rdblquote  or \ldblquote as [this] comes into play\rdblquote  abilities), those abilities will take effect. Also, any comes-into-play triggered abilities of the copy will have a chance to trigger.\par }\pard\plain \s23\li1200\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ Skyshroud Behemoth reads, \ldblquote Fading 2 (This creature comes into play with two fade counters on it. At the beginning of your upkeep, remove a fade counter from it. If you can\rquote t, sacrifice it.) / Skyshroud Behemoth comes into play tapped.\rdblquote  A Clone that comes into play as a copy of a Skyshroud Behemoth will also come into play tapped with two fade counters on it.\par }{\b Example:}{ Striped Bears reads, \ldblquote When Striped Bears comes into play, draw a card.\rdblquote  A Clone comes into play as a copy of Striped Bears. The Clone has the Bears\rquote  comes-into-play triggered ability, so the Clone\rquote s controller draws a card.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 503.6. When copying a permanent, any choices that have been made for that permanent aren\rquote t copied. Instead, if an object comes into play as a copy of another permanent, the object\rquote s controller will get to make any \ldblquote as comes into play\rdblquote  choices for it.\par }\pard\plain \s23\li1200\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ A Clone comes into play as a copy of Chameleon Spirit. Chameleon Spirit reads, in part, \ldblquote As Chameleon Spirit comes into play, choose a color.\rdblquote  The Clone won\rquote t copy the color choice of the Spirit; rather, the controller of the Clone will get to make a new choice.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 503.7. Because any choices that have been made for a permanent aren\rquote t copied, sometimes a copy card will gain an ability that refers to a choice that was never made. In that case, the choice is considered to be \ldblquote zero\rdblquote  or \ldblquote undefined.\rdblquote \par }\pard\plain \s23\li1200\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ Voice of All comes into play and Unstable Shapeshifter copies it. Voice of All reads, in part, \ldblquote As Voice of All comes into play, choose a color. / Voice of All has protection from the chosen color.\rdblquote  Unstable Shapeshifter never got a chance to choose a color, because it didn\rquote t come into play as a Voice of All card, so the Shapeshifter\rquote s protection ability doesn\rquote t protect it from anything at all.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 503.8. If an ability causes a player to make a choice as a copy comes into play, the copy will \ldblquote remember\rdblquote  that choice and continue to use it for its abilities if appropriate. If the choice is not appropriate, it is considered to be \ldblquote zero\rdblquote  or \ldblquote undefined.\rdblquote \par }\pard\plain \s23\li1200\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ A Vesuvan Doppelganger comes into play as a copy of Chameleon Spirit, and the Doppelganger\rquote s controller chooses blue. Later, the Doppelganger copies Quirion Elves. The Elves has the ability, \ldblquote \{oT\}: Add one mana of the chosen color to your mana pool.\rdblquote  If the mana ability of the Doppelganger is played, it will produce blue mana.\par }{\b Example:}{ A Vesuvan Doppelganger comes into play as a copy of Caller of the Hunt. Caller of the Hunt reads, in part, \ldblquote As Caller of the Hunt comes into play, choose a creature type.\rdblquote  The Doppelganger\rquote s controller chooses Goblin. Later, the Doppelganger copies Quirion Elves. If the mana ability of the Doppelganger is played, it will fail to produce any mana. It won\rquote t produce Goblin mana.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 503.9. Some copy effects give an ability to the copy as part of the copying process. This ability becomes part of the copiable values for the copy, along with any other abilities that were copied. Also, some copy effects specifically state that they don\rquote t copy certain characteristics; they retain their original values instead.\par }\pard\plain \s23\li1200\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ Quirion Elves comes into play and an Unstable Shapeshifter copies it. The copiable values of the Shapeshifter now match those of the Elves, except that the Shapeshifter also has the ability \ldblquote Whenever a creature comes into play, Unstable Shapeshifter becomes a copy of that creature and gains this ability.\rdblquote  Then a Clone comes into play as a copy of the Unstable Shapeshifter. The Clone copies the new copiable values of the Shapeshifter, including the ability that the Shapeshifter gave itself when it copied the Elves.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 503.10. To copy a spell means to put a copy of the spell onto the stack; a copy of a spell isn\rquote t \ldblquote played.\rdblquote  In addition to copying the characteristics of the spell, all decisions made when the spell was played are copied. These include mode, targets, the value of X, and optional additional costs such as buyback. (See rule 409, \ldblquote Playing Spells and Activated Abilities.\rdblquote ) Choices that are normally made on resolution are not copied. A copy of a spell is itself a spell, but it has no spell card associated with it. It works just like a normal spell: it can be countered or it can resolve, and it uses the same timing rules as normal spells.\par }\pard\plain \s23\li1200\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ A player plays Fork, targeting an Emerald Charm. Fork reads, \ldblquote Put a copy of target instant or sorcery spell onto the stack, except that it copies Fork\rquote s color and you may choose new targets for the copy.\rdblquote  Emerald Charm reads, \ldblquote Choose one \emdash  Untap target permanent; or destroy target global enchantment; or target creature loses flying until end of turn.\rdblquote  When the Fork resolves, it puts a copy of the Emerald Charm on the stack. The copy has the same mode that was chosen for the original Emerald Charm. It does not necessarily have the same target, but only because Fork allows choosing of new targets.\par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 503.10a A copy of a spell in a zone other than the stack ceases to exist. This is a state-based effect. See rule 420.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 503.11. If an effect refers to a permanent by name, the effect still tracks that permanent even if it changes names or becomes a copy of something else.\par }\pard\plain \s23\li1200\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ An Unstable Shapeshifter copies a Crazed Armodon. Crazed Armodon reads, \ldblquote \{oG\}: Crazed Armodon gets +3/+0 and gains trample until end of turn. Destroy Crazed Armodon at end of turn. Play this ability only once each turn.\rdblquote  If this activated ability of the Shapeshifter is played, the Shapeshifter will be destroyed at end of turn, even if it\rquote s no longer a copy of Crazed Armodon at that time.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par }{\cf1 503.12. An effect that instructs a player to \ldblquote play a copy\rdblquote  of an object follows the rules for playing spells and abilities, except that the copy is played while another spell or ability is resolving. Playing a copy of a nonland object follows steps 409.1a-409.1h of rule 409, \ldblquote Playing Spells and Activated Abilities," then the copy becomes played. The played copy is a spell on the stack, and just like any other spell it can resolve or be countered.}{\par \par }\pard\plain \s19\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {504. Face-Down Spells and Permanents\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 504.1. One old card (Illusionary Mask) and the morph ability (see rule 502.26) allow spells and permanents to be face down.\par \par 504.2. Face-down spells on the stack, face-down permanents in play, and face-down cards in the phased-out zone have no characteristics other than those listed by the ability or rules that allow the card, spell, or permanent to be face down. Any listed characteristics are the copiable values of that object\rquote s characteristics. (See rule 418.5, \ldblquote Interaction of Continuous Effects,\rdblquote  and rule 503, \ldblquote Copying Objects.\rdblquote ) Objects that are put into play face down are turned face down before they come into play, so the permanent\rquote s comes-into-play abilities won\rquote t trigger (if triggered) or have any effect (if static). Objects that are played face down are turned face down before they are put onto the stack, so effects that care about the characteristics of a spell will see only the face-down spell\rquote s characteristics.\par \par 504.3. You may look at a face-down spell you control on the stack or a face-down permanent you control at any time. You can\rquote t look at face-down cards in any other zone or face-down spells or permanents controlled by another player. The ability or rules that allow a permanent to be face down may also allow the permanent\rquote s controller to turn it face up. Spells normally can\rquote t be turned face up.\par \par 504.4. If you control multiple face-down spells on the stack or face-down permanents in play, you must ensure at all times that your face-down spells and permanents can be easily differentiated from each other. This includes, but is not limited to, knowing the order spells were played, the order that face-down permanents came into play, which creature attacked last turn, and any other differences between face-down spells or permanents. Common methods for distinguishing between face-down objects include using counters or dice to mark the different objects, or clearly placing those objects in order on the table.\par \par 504.5. As a face-down permanent is turned face up, its copiable values revert to its normal copiable values. Any effects that have been applied to the face-down permanent still apply to the face-up permanent. Any abilities relating to the permanent coming into play don\rquote t trigger and don\rquote t have any effect, because the permanent has already come into play.\par \par 504.6. If a face-down permanent moves from the in-play zone to any zone other than the phased-out zone, its owner must reveal it to all players as he or she moves it. If a phased-out face-down object moves to any zone other than the in-play zone, its owner must reveal it as he or she moves it. If a face-down spell moves from the stack to any zone other than the in-play zone, its owner must reveal it to all players as he or she moves it. At the end of each game, all face-down objects in play, in the phased-out zone, or on the stack must be revealed to all players.\par \par }\pard\plain \s19\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {505. Split Cards\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 505.1. Split cards have two card faces on a single card. The back of a split card is the normal }{\b Magic: The Gathering }{card back.\par \par 505.2. In every zone except the stack, split cards have two sets of characteristics. As long as a split card is a spell on the stack, only the characteristics of the half being played exist. The other half\rquote s characteristics are treated as though they didn\rquote t exist.\par \par 505.3. Because every split card consists of two halves with different colored mana symbols in their mana costs, each split card is a multicolored card except while it\rquote s a spell on the stack. While it\rquote s a spell on the stack, it\rquote s only the color of the half being played.\par \par 505.4. Although split cards have two playable halves, each split card is only one card. For example, a player who has drawn or discarded a split card has drawn or discarded one card, not two.\par \par 505.5. Effects that ask for a particular characteristic of a split card while it\rquote s in a zone other than the stack get an answer that consists of a combination of the split card\rquote s two halves.\par }\pard\plain \s23\li1200\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ Infernal Genesis has an ability that reads, \ldblquote At the beginning of each player\rquote s upkeep, that player puts the top card from his or her library into his or her graveyard. He or she then puts X 1/1 black Minion creature tokens into play, where X is that card\rquote s converted mana cost.\rdblquote  If the top card of your library is Assault/Battery when this ability resolves, you get five 1/1 creature tokens because Assault\rquote s converted mana cost is 1 and Battery\rquote s is 4, for a total of 5.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 505.6. Effects that ask if a split card\rquote s characteristic (in any zone other than the stack) matches a given value get only one answer. This answer is \ldblquote yes\rdblquote  if either side of the split card matches the given value.\par }\pard\plain \s23\li1200\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ Void reads, \ldblquote Choose a number. Destroy all artifacts and creatures with converted mana cost equal to that number. Then target player reveals his or her hand and discards from it all nonland cards with converted mana cost equal to the number.\rdblquote  If a player plays Void and chooses 1 or 4, his or her opponent would discard Assault/Battery. If the player chooses 5, Assault/Battery would be unaffected, because neither half has a converted mana cost of 5.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 505.7. If an effect instructs a player to name a card and the player wants to name a split card, the player must name both halves of the split card.\par \par }\pard\plain \s19\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {506. Subgames\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 506.1. One card (Shahrazad) allows players to play a }{\b Magic}{ subgame. A \ldblquote subgame\rdblquote  is the game created by Shahrazad. The \ldblquote main game\rdblquote  is the game in which Shahrazad was played. The main game is suspended while the subgame is in progress. It resumes when the subgame ends.\par \par 506.2. Any main-game abilities that trigger while the subgame is in progress aren\rquote t put onto the stack until the subgame is completed.\par \par 506.3. To start the subgame, each player removes his or her library from the game face down. It becomes that player\rquote s deck in the subgame. Abilities that trigger on cards being removed from the main game face down will trigger.\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {506.3a A player\rquote s deck in the subgame may have less than the minimum number of cards. If a player\rquote s deck contains less than seven cards, the player will lose the game as soon as it starts, even if he or she mulligans. (See rule 420, \ldblquote State-Based Effects.\rdblquote )\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 506.4. The subgame proceeds like a normal game. Randomly determine which player goes first.\par \par 506.5. All objects in the main game and all cards outside the main game are considered outside the subgame (except those specifically brought into the subgame).\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {506.5a Some effects can bring cards into a game from outside of it. Cards brought into a subgame from a main game are considered to be removed from the main game. Abilities in the main game that trigger on objects being removed from the main game will trigger.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 506.6. At the end of a subgame, each player puts all objects that were brought into the subgame into his or her library in the main game, then shuffles that library. Cards removed from the game in the subgame are not put into the player\rquote s main-game library. Instead they remain removed from the game in the main game.\par }\pard\plain \s23\li1200\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ If a card was brought into the subgame either from the main game or from outside the main game, that card will be put into its owner\rquote s main-game library when the subgame ends.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 506.7. If another subgame is created during a subgame, there can be multiple subgames and main games. Each main game has one subgame, and each subgame has one main game. In this case, some games will be considered both a main game and a subgame at the same time.\par \par }\pard\plain \s19\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {507. Controlling Another Player\rquote s Turn\par \par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {507.1. One card (Mindslaver) allows a player\rquote s turn to be controlled by another player. This effect applies to the next turn that the affected player actually takes. The entire turn is controlled; the effect doesn\rquote t end until the beginning of the next turn.\par \par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {507.1a Multiple turn-controlling effects that affect the same player overwrite each other. The last one to be created is the one that works.\par \par 507.1b If a turn is skipped, any pending turn-controlling effects wait until the player who would be affected actually takes a turn.\par \par 507.1c Only the control of the turn changes. All objects are controlled by their normal controllers.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 507.2. If information about an object would be visible to the player whose turn is controlled, it\rquote s visible to both that player and the controller of the turn.\par }\pard\plain \s23\li1200\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ The controller of a player\rquote s turn can see that player\rquote s hand and the identity of any face-down creatures he or she controls.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 507.3. The controller of another player\rquote s turn makes all choices and decisions that player is allowed to make or is told to make during that turn by the rules or by any objects. This includes choices and decisions about what to play, and choices and decisions called for by spells and abilities.\par }\pard\plain \s23\li1200\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ The controller of the turn decides which spells to play and what those spells target, and makes any required decisions when those spells resolve.\par }{\b Example:}{ The controller of the turn decides which of the player\rquote s creatures attack, and how those creatures assign their combat damage.\par }{\b Example:}{ The controller of the turn decides which card the player chooses from outside the game with one of the }{\i0 Judgment\u8482\'aa}{ Wishes. The player can\rquote t choose a card of the wrong type.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {507.3a The controller of another player\rquote s turn can use only that player\rquote s resources (cards, mana, and so on) to pay costs for that player.\par }\pard\plain \s24\li1500\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ If the controller of the turn decides that the player will play a spell with an additional cost}{\i0  }{of discarding cards from hand, the cards are discarded from the player\rquote s hand.\par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 507.3b The controller of another player\rquote s turn can\rquote t make that player concede. A player may concede the game at any time, even if his or her turn is controlled by another player. See rule 102.7.\par \par 507.3c The controller of another player\rquote s turn can\rquote t make choices or decisions for that player that aren\rquote t called for by the rules, or by any objects. The controller also can\rquote t make any choices or decisions for the player that would be called for by the tournament rules.\par }\pard\plain \s24\li1500\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example: }{The player whose turn it is still chooses whether he or she leaves to visit the restroom, trades a card to someone else, takes an intentional draw, or calls a judge about an error or infraction.\par }\pard\plain \s21\fi-300\li900\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 507.3d A player who controls another player\rquote s turn also continues to make his or her own choices and decisions.\par }\pard\plain \s20\fi-300\li600\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par 507.4. A player doesn\rquote t lose life due to mana burn while another player controls his or her turn. (Unused mana in players\rquote  mana pools is still lost when a phase ends. See rule 300.3.)\par }\pard\plain \s17\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\f4\lang1033\cgrid {\page Glossary\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Ability\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\ldblquote Ability\rdblquote  and \ldblquote effect\rdblquote  are often confused with one another. An instruction in an object\rquote s text is an ability. The result of following such an instruction is an effect. For more information, see section 4, \ldblquote Spells, Abilities, and Effects.\rdblquote \par      When an activated ability is played, it goes onto the stack and stays there until it resolves or is countered.\par      When an effect states that an object \ldblquote gains\rdblquote  or \ldblquote has\rdblquote  an ability, it\rquote s granting that object an ability. If an effect defines a property of an object (\ldblquote [card or permanent] is [property]\rdblquote ), it\rquote s not granting an ability. For example, an enchant creature might read, \ldblquote Enchanted creature is red.\rdblquote  The enchantment isn\rquote t granting an ability of any kind; it\rquote s simply changing the enchanted creature\rquote s color to red.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Activated Ability\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {An activated ability is written as \ldblquote activation cost: effect.\rdblquote  By paying the activation cost, a player may play such an ability whenever he or she has priority. See rule 403, \ldblquote Activated Abilities.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Activation Cost\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {The activation cost of an activated ability is everything before the colon in \ldblquote activation cost: effect.\rdblquote  It must be paid to play the ability. See rule 403, \ldblquote Activated Abilities.\rdblquote \par }\pard\plain \s28\li400\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin400\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ The activation cost of an ability that reads \ldblquote \{o2\}, \{oT\}: You gain 1 life\rdblquote  is two mana of any color plus tapping the permanent.\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Active Player\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {The active player is the player whose turn it is. The active player gets priority at the start of each phase or step (except for the untap and cleanup steps), after any spell or ability (except a mana ability) resolves, and after combat damage resolves. See rule 200.3.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Active Player, Nonactive Player Rule\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Whenever both players are instructed to make choices at the same time, the active player makes all his or her choices first, then the nonactive player. This is called the \ldblquote Active Player, Nonactive Player\rdblquote  rule, or \ldblquote APNAP\rdblquote  rule. See rule 103.4.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Additional Cost\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Some spells have additional costs listed in their text. These are paid at the same time the player pays the spell\rquote s mana cost. See rule 409, \ldblquote Playing Spells and Activated Abilities.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Affinity\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Affinity is a static ability that functions while the spell is on the stack. \ldblquote Affinity [text]\rdblquote  means \ldblquote This spell costs you \{o1\} less to play for each [text] you control.\rdblquote  The affinity ability only reduces generic mana costs. It doesn\rquote t reduce how much colored mana you have to pay for a spell. It can\rquote t reduce the cost to play a spell to less than 0. See rule 502.31, \ldblquote Affinity.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Alternative Cost\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {The rules text of some spells reads, \ldblquote You may [action] rather than pay [this object\rquote s] mana cost,\rdblquote  or include the phrase, \ldblquote you may play [this object] without paying its mana cost.\rdblquote  These are alternative costs. Only one such alternative cost can be applied to any one spell. Other spells and abilities that refer to a spell\rquote s mana cost don\rquote t consider the alternative cost. If an effect requires paying additional costs to play a spell, it still applies to the alternative cost. See rule 409, \ldblquote Playing Spells and Activated Abilities.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Amplify\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Amplify is a static ability. \ldblquote Amplify [X]\rdblquote  means \ldblquote As this object comes into play, reveal any number of cards from your hand that share a creature type with this object. This object comes into play with X +1/+1 counters on it for each card revealed this way. You can\rquote t reveal this card or any other cards that are coming into play at the same time as this card.\rdblquote  See rule 502.27, \ldblquote Amplify.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Ante (Obsolete)\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Earlier versions of the }{\b Magic}{ rules included an ante rule as a way of playing \ldblquote for keeps.\rdblquote  Playing }{\b Magic}{ games for ante is now considered an optional variation on the game, and it is allowed only where it\rquote s not forbidden by law or by other rules. Playing for ante is strictly forbidden under DCI tournament rules. When using the ante rule, each player puts one random card from his or her deck into his or her ante zone at the beginning of the game. At the end of the game, the winner becomes the owner of the cards in each player\rquote s ante zone. See rule 217.9, \ldblquote Ante.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {APNAP\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {See Active Player, Nonactive Player Rule.\par }\pard \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Artifact\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Artifact is a type. The active player can play artifacts only during his or her main phase when the stack is empty. When an artifact spell resolves, its controller puts it into play under his or her control. See rule 212.2, \ldblquote Artifacts.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Artifact Creature\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {An artifact creature is a combination of artifact and creature, and it\rquote s subject to the rules for both. (See rule 212.2, \ldblquote Artifacts.\rdblquote ) Some artifact creatures don\rquote t have a creature type. Those that do will say \ldblquote Artifact Creature \emdash  [creature type]\rdblquote ; for example, \ldblquote Artifact Creature \emdash  Golem.\rdblquote  \ldblquote Artifact\rdblquote  isn\rquote t a creature type.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Artifact Land\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {An artifact land is a combination of artifact and land, and it\rquote s subject to the rules for both. (See rule 212.2, \ldblquote Artifacts.\rdblquote ) Artifact lands can only be played as lands. They can\rquote t be played as spells. Some artifact lands don\rquote t have a land type. Those that do will say \ldblquote Artifact Land \emdash  [land type].\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\ldblquote As though\rdblquote \par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Text that states a player or card may do something \ldblquote as though\rdblquote  some condition were true applies only to the stated action. For purposes of that action, treat the game exactly as if the stated condition is true. For all other purposes, treat the game normally.\par }\pard\plain \s28\li400\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin400\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ Giant Spider reads, \ldblquote Giant Spider may block as though it had flying.\rdblquote  You may treat the Spider as a creature with flying, but only for the purpose of declaring blockers. This allows Giant Spider to block a creature with flying (and creatures that \ldblquote can\rquote t be blocked except by creatures with flying\rdblquote ), assuming no other blocking restrictions apply. For example, Giant Spider can\rquote t normally block a creature with both flying and shadow.\par }{\b Example:}{ Future Sight reads, \ldblquote Play with the top card of your library revealed. / You may play the top card of your library as though it were in your hand.\rdblquote  The revealed card may be played by the usual rules. If it\rquote s a spell, it\rquote s placed on the stack as the first step of playing it (see rule 409, \ldblquote Playing Spells and Activated Abilities\rdblquote ); if it\rquote s a land, it\rquote s put directly into play. Because the card isn\rquote t actually in your hand, it can\rquote t be discarded, removed from the game to pay a cost, cycled, or counted toward the number of cards in your hand.\par }{\b Example:}{ Rolling Stones reads, \ldblquote Walls may attack as though they weren\rquote t Walls.\rdblquote  As long as this effect is active, Walls are treated exactly like creatures that don\rquote t have the Wall creature type for the purposes of declaring attackers. They\rquote re still subject to all other rules and effects that determine whether an attack is legal.\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {     If two cards state that a player or card may do the same thing \ldblquote as though\rdblquote  different conditions were true, both conditions could apply. If one \ldblquote as though\rdblquote  effect satisfies the requirements for another \ldblquote as though\rdblquote  effect, then both effects will apply.\par }\pard\plain \s28\li400\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin400\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ Two effects read, \ldblquote You may play cards in your graveyard as though they were in your hand,\rdblquote  and \ldblquote You may play cards from other players\rquote  graveyards as though they were in your graveyard.\rdblquote  Both effects apply. You may play cards in your graveyard and cards in your opponents\rquote  graveyards. (The cards may be played by the usual rules.)\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Assign Combat Damage\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {As the combat damage step begins, the active player announces how each attacking creature will assign its combat damage. Then the defending player announces how each blocking creature will assign its combat damage. All assignments of combat damage go on the stack as a single entry. See rule 310, \ldblquote Combat Damage Step.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Attack\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {A creature attacks when it is declared as an attacker during the combat phase. (See rule 308, \ldblquote Declare Attackers Step.\rdblquote ) Playing a spell or ability (even during the combat phase) is never considered to be an attack.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Attack Alone\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {A creature is attacking alone when it\rquote s the only creature declared as an attacker in a given combat phase. See rule 306.4.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Attacked\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Some triggered abilities trigger when a player is \ldblquote attacked.\rdblquote  At least one creature must actually be attacking that player for such abilities to trigger. Also, \ldblquote attacked\rdblquote  means \ldblquote attacked by one or more creatures,\rdblquote  so such abilities can trigger only once each combat phase. See rule 306.3.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Attacking Creature\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 