utside of the combat phase. See rule 309, \ldblquote Declare Blockers Step.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Bury (Obsolete)\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Some older cards were printed with the term \ldblquote bury,\rdblquote  which meant to put a permanent into its owner\rquote s graveyard. In general, cards that were printed with the term \ldblquote bury\rdblquote  now read, \ldblquote Destroy [a permanent]. It can\rquote t be regenerated.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Buyback\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Buyback is a replacement effect modifying rule 413.2h. When playing a spell with buyback, the controller of the spell may pay an additional cost specified on the card. If he or she does, when the spell resolves, the spell is put into his or her hand instead of into his or her graveyard. If the spell goes to some zone other than its owner\rquote s graveyard as it resolves, buyback\rquote s effect \ldblquote loses track\rdblquote  of it, and it isn\rquote t returned to its owner\rquote s hand. See rule 502.16, \ldblquote Buyback.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Cantrip (Informal)\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {This is a nickname for any spell that has \ldblquote Draw a card\rdblquote  as part of its effect.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Card\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {When a rule or 