ht\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Damage\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Damage can be dealt to creatures and/or players.\par      Damage dealt to a player is subtracted from his or her life total.\par      Damage dealt to a creature stays on the permanent until end of turn, even if it stops being a creature. A creature with damage greater than or equal to its toughness has been dealt lethal damage and is destroyed. (See rule 420, \ldblquote State-Based Effects.\rdblquote ) Damage doesn\rquote t alter a creature\rquote s toughness. A noncreature permanent isn\rquote t affected by damage (but if it becomes a creature again before the damage is removed, the creature may be destroyed). During the cleanup step, all damage is removed from permanents.\par      Costs and effects that read \ldblquote lose life\rdblquote  or \ldblquote pay life\rdblquote  don\rquote t deal damage, and that loss of life can\rquote t be prevented or otherwise altered by damage-prevention effects.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Damage-Prevention Ability\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {A damage-prevention ability is a static or activated ability that generates a damage-prevention effect. See rule 419.7, \ldblquote Prevention Effects.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Deck\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {A player\rquote s deck is the collection of cards that player starts the game with. When the game begins, each player\rquote s deck becomes his or her library.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Declare Attackers\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {To declare attackers, the active player chooses a set of creatures that will attack and pays any costs they require to attack. Only creatures can attack, and the following creatures can\rquote t attack: tapped creatures (even those that can attack without tapping), creatures with creature type \ldblquote Wall,\rdblquote  and creatures the active player didn\rquote t control continuously since the beginning of the turn (except those with haste). Other effects may also affect whether or not a set of creatures could attack. See rule 500, \ldblquote Legal Attacks and Blocks.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Declare Attackers Step\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {The declare attackers step is the second step of the combat phase. The active player declares attackers during this step. Then the active player gets priority and players may play spells and abilities. See rule 308, \ldblquote Declare Attackers Step.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Declare Blockers\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {To declare blockers, the defending player chooses a set of creatures that will block and pays any costs they require to block. Only untapped creatures can block, but blocking doesn\rquote t cause creatures to tap. Other effects may also affect whether or not a set of creatures could block. See rule 500, \ldblquote Legal Attacks and Blocks.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Declare Blockers Step\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {The declare blockers step is the third step of the combat phase. The defending player declares blockers during this step. Then the active player gets priority and players may play spells and abilities. See rule 309, \ldblquote Declare Blockers Step.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Defending Player\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {During the combat phase, from the start of the declare attackers step until the end of the combat phase, the active player\rquote s opponent is the defending player. Creatures can attack only the defending player; they can\rquote t attack other players or creatures. During phases other than combat, there is no defending player. See rule 306.3.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Delayed Triggered Ability\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {A delayed triggered ability is created by effects generated when some spells or abilities resolve. See rule 404.4.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Depend On\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {An effect is said to \ldblquote depend on\rdblquote  another if it is applied at the same time as the other effect and applying the other would change the text or the existence of the first effect, what it applies to, or what it does to any of the things it applies to. See rule 418.5, \ldblquote Interaction of Continuous Effects.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Destroy\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {To destroy a permanent is to move it from the in-play zone to its owner\rquote s graveyard. Regeneration or other destruction-replacement effects can replace this action. See rule 419, \ldblquote Replacement and Prevention Effects.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Discard\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {A player discards a card by putting a card from his or her hand into his or her graveyard. By default, effects that cause a player to discard a card allow the affected player to choose which card to discard. Some effects, however, require a random discard or allow another player to choose which card is discarded.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Distribute\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Distribute has its normal English meaning in the }{\b Magic}{ game. If a spell or ability requires a player to distribute something (such as counters) as he or she chooses among one or more targets, or among any number of untargeted objects or players, each of these targets, objects, or players must receive at least one of whatever is being distributed. See rules 409.1e and 310.2.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Divide\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Divide has its normal English meaning in the }{\b Magic}{ game. If a spell or ability requires a player to divide something (such as damage or counters) as he or she chooses among one or more targets, or any number of untargeted objects or players, each of these targets, objects, or players must receive at least one of whatever is being divided. This doesn\rquote t apply to dividing combat damage. See rules 409.1e and 310.2.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Double Strike\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Double strike is a static ability that modifies the rules for the combat damage step. Creatures with double strike deal combat damage in both the first-strike combat damage step and the normal combat damage step. See rule 502.28, \ldblquote Double Strike.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Draw\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Draw has two meanings in the }{\b Magic}{ game.\par      1. A player draws a card by putting the top card of his or her library into his or her hand. If an instruction tells a player to draw more than one card, the cards are drawn one at a time. An effect may move cards from a player\rquote s library to that player\rquote s hand without the player \ldblquote drawing\rdblquote  them; this makes a difference for abilities that trigger on drawing cards or that replace card draws.\par      2. A drawn game is a game where the game ends, and there is no winner. A game ends in a draw if both players lose simultaneously. See rule 102.4.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Draw Step\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {The draw step is the third step of the beginning phase. As the draw step begins, the active player draws a card (this game action does not use the stack). Then the active player gets priority and players may play spells and abilities. See rule 304, \ldblquote Draw Step.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Dual Land (Informal)\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Ten \ldblquote dual land\rdblquote  cards were printed in early }{\b Magic}{ editions; each of these has two basic land types. For example, Taiga has the land types Forest and Mountain. Dual land cards have the default abilities of both basic land types and are treated as both by all spells and abilities that specifically refer to those types. However, they are not basic lands. A dual land card doesn\rquote t count as two lands while in play\emdash it\rquote s just one land with multiple land types. \par }{\highlight3 \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {During (Obsolete)\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Some older cards used the phrase \ldblquote during [phase], [action].\rdblquote  These abilities were called \ldblquote phase abilities. In general, cards that were printed with phase abilities now have abilities that trigger at the beginning of a step or phase. \ldblquote During\rdblquote  still appears in current card text, but only in its normal English sense and not as game terminology.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Echo\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Echo is a triggered ability. \ldblquote Echo\rdblquote  means \ldblquote At the beginning of your upkeep, if this permanent came under your control since the beginning of your last upkeep, sacrifice it unless you pay its mana cost.\rdblquote  See rule 502.19, \ldblquote Echo.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Effect\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\ldblquote Ability\rdblquote  and \ldblquote effect\rdblquote  are often confused with one another. When a spell or ability resolves, it may create one or more one-shot or continuous effects. Static abilities may create one or more continuous effects. Some effects are replacement effects or prevention effects. State-based effects are not created by spells or abilities; they are generated by specific states of the game. See rule 416, \ldblquote Effects.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Enchant Artifact\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {An enchant artifact is a local enchantment. It can enchant only a permanent that\rquote s an artifact. See also Local Enchantment.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Enchant Artifact Creature\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {An enchant artifact creature is a local enchantment. It can enchant only a permanent that\rquote s both an artifact and a creature. It is treated as an enchant artifact creature, an enchant artifact, and an enchant creature. See also Local Enchantment.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Enchant Creature \par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {An enchant creature is a local enchantment. It can enchant only a permanent that\rquote s a creature. See also Local Enchantment.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Enchant Enchantment \par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {An enchant enchantment is a local enchantment. It can enchant only a permanent that\rquote s an enchantment. See also Local Enchantment.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Enchant Land \par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {An enchant land is a local enchantment. It can enchant only a permanent that\rquote s a land. See also Local Enchantment.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Enchant Permanent \par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {An enchant permanent is a local enchantment. It can enchant any type of permanent. See also Local Enchantment.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Enchant Player \par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {An enchant player is a local enchantment. It can enchant only a player. See also Local Enchantment.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Enchant World\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {An object that is an \ldblquote enchant world\rdblquote  is a global enchantment. See rule 212.4, \ldblquote Enchantments.\rdblquote  If two or more enchant worlds are in play, all except for the one that has been an enchant world for the shortest amount of time are put into their owners\rquote  graveyards. This is a state-based effect; see rule 420.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Enchantment\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Enchantment is a type. The active player can play enchantments only during his or her main phase when the stack is empty. See rule 212.4, \ldblquote Enchantments.\rdblquote  See also Global Enchantment, Local Enchantment.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {End of Combat Step\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {The end of combat step is the fifth step of the combat phase. A player may play spells and abilities during this step whenever he or she has priority. See rule 311, \ldblquote End of Combat Step.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {End of Turn Step\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {This is the first step of the end phase. A player may play spells and abilities during this step whenever he or she has priority. See rule 313, \ldblquote End of Turn Step.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {End Phase\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {The end phase is the fifth and final phase of the turn. It has two steps: end of turn and cleanup. See rule 312, \ldblquote End Phase.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Entwine\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Entwine is a static ability that functions while the spell is on the stack. The phrase \ldblquote Entwine [cost]\rdblquote  means \ldblquote You may choose to use all modes of this spell instead of just one. If you do, you pay an additional [cost].\rdblquote  When the spell resolves, if the entwine cost was paid, follow the text of each of the modes in the order they\rquote re written on the card. See rule 502.32, \ldblquote Entwine.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Equip\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Equip is an activated ability. The phrase \ldblquote Equip [cost]\rdblquote  means \ldblquote [cost]: Move this Equipment onto target creature you control. Play this ability only any time you could play a sorcery.\rdblquote  See rule 502.33, \ldblquote Equip,\rdblquote  and rule 212.2, \ldblquote Artifacts.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Equipment\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Some artifacts have the subtype \ldblquote Equipment.\rdblquote  These artifacts can be attached to (can \ldblquote equip\rdblquote ) creatures. They can\rquote t equip objects that aren\rquote t creatures. An Equipment is played and comes into play just like any other artifact. Equipment doesn\rquote t come into play equipping a creature. The equip keyword ability moves the Equipment onto a creature you control. (See rule 502.33, \ldblquote Equip.\rdblquote ) The creature an Equipment is attached to is called \ldblquote equipped.\rdblquote  The Equipment is attached to, or \ldblquote equips,\rdblquote  that creature.\par      An Equipment that\rquote s also a creature or an Equipment that loses the subtype \ldblquote Equipment\rdblquote  can\rquote t equip a creature. An Equipment can\rquote t equip itself. An Equipment that equips an illegal or nonexistent permanent stops equipping that permanent, but remains in play. (This is a state-based effect. See rule 420.)\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Evasion Ability\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Evasion abilities restrict what creatures can block an attacking creature. These are static abilities that modify the declare blockers step of the combat phase. See rule 501, \ldblquote Evasion Abilities.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Event\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Anything that happens in a game is an event. Multiple events may take place during the resolution of a spell or ability. The text of triggered abilities and replacement effects defines the event they\rquote re looking for. One \ldblquote happening\rdblquote  may be treated as a single event by one ability and as multiple events by another.\par }\pard\plain \s28\li400\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin400\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ If an attacking creature is blocked by two defending creatures, this is one event for a triggered ability that reads \ldblquote Whenever [name] becomes blocked\rdblquote  but two events for a triggered ability that reads \ldblquote Whenever [name] becomes blocked by a creature.\rdblquote \par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Exchange\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {A spell or ability may instruct two players to exchange something (for example, life totals or control of two permanents) as part of its resolution. When such a spell or ability resolves, if it can\rquote t exchange the chosen things, it has no effect on them.\par }\pard\plain \s28\li400\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin400\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ If a spell attempts to exchange control of two target creatures but one of those creatures is destroyed before the spell resolves, the spell does nothing to the other creature. Or if a spell attempts to exchange control of two target creatures but both of those creatures are controlled by the same player, the spell does nothing to the two creatures.\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {     When control of two permanents is exchanged, each player simultaneously gains control of the permanent that was controlled by the other player.\par      When life totals are exchanged, each player gains or loses the amount of life necessary to equal the other player\rquote s previous life total. Replacement effects may modify these gains and losses, and triggered abilities may trigger on them.\par      Some spells or abilities may instruct a player to exchange cards in one zone with cards in a different zone (for example, cards removed from the game and cards in a player\rquote s hand). These spells and abilities work the same as other \ldblquote exchange\rdblquote  spells and abilities, except they can exchange the cards only if all the cards are owned by the same player.\par      If a spell or ability instructs a player to simply exchange two zones, and one of the zones is empty, the cards in the zones are still exchanged.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Expansion Symbol\par }\pard\pl