e-based effect (see rule 420.5c). Rules or effects may cause an indestructible permanent to be sacrificed, put into a graveyard, or removed from the game.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Infinity Rule (Informal)\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {There\rquote s no such thing as \ldblquote infinity\rdblquote  in }{\b Magic}{ rules. Occasionally the game can get into a state where a set of actions could be repeated forever. The \ldblquote infinity rule\rdblquote  governs how to break such loops. See rule 421, \ldblquote Handling \lquote Infinite\rquote  Loops.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Instant\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Instant is a type. A player may play instants whenever he or she has priority. An instant spell is put into its owner\rquote s graveyard as the last step of its resolution. See rule 212.5, \ldblquote Instants,\rdblquote  and rule 409, \ldblquote Playing Spells and Activated Abilities.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Instead\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Effects that use the word \ldblquote instead\rdblquote  are replacement effects. Most replacement effects use the word \ldblquote instead\rdblquote  to indicate what events will be replaced with other events. See rule 419, \ldblquote Replacement and Prevention Effects.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Interrupt (Obsolete)\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Some older cards used the term \ldblquote interrupt\rdblquote  on the card\rquote s type line. All interrupt cards are now instant cards. All abilities that were played as interrupts are now played like normal activated abilities (and are mana abilities if they produce mana).\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Intervening \ldblquote If\rdblquote  Clause\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Triggered abilities with a condition directly following the trigger event (for example, \ldblquote When/Whenever/At [trigger], if [condition], [effect]\rdblquote ) check for the condition to be true as part of the trigger event; if it isn\rquote t, the ability doesn\rquote t trigger. The ability checks the condition again on resolution. If it\rquote s not satisfied, the ability does nothing. Note that this mirrors the check for legal targets. Note that this rule doesn\rquote t apply to any triggered ability with an \ldblquote if\rdblquote  condition elsewhere within its text. See rule 404.3.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Island\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\ldblquote Island\rdblquote  is one of the five basic land types. Any land with the land type Island has the ability \ldblquote \{oT\}: Add \{oU\} to your mana pool.\rdblquote  See rule 212.6d.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Islandcycling\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {See Landcycling.\par \par Islandhome (Obsolete)\par Some older cards were printed with the term islandhome, which means \ldblquote This creature can\rquote t attack unless the defending player controls an Island\rdblquote  and \ldblquote When you control no Islands, sacrifice this creature.\rdblquote  Cards that previously had islandhome now simply have the two parts of islandhome written out without using the keyword.\par }\pard \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Islandwalk\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {See Landwalk.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Keyword Ability\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Some abilities are very common or would require too much space to define on a card. These abilities list only the name of the ability as a \ldblquote keyword\rdblquote ; sometimes reminder text summarizes the game rule. See rule 502, \ldblquote Keyword Abilities.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Kicker\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Kicker is a keyword ability with a cost and an effect. Paying a spell\rquote s kicker cost causes the spell to have an additional or alternative effect. See rule 502.21, \ldblquote Kicker.\rdblquote \par      A kicker cost is an additional cost to play a spell. You declare whether you intend to pay a spell\rquote s kicker cost at the same time you would choose the spell\rquote s mode (see rule 409.1b), and you actually pay the cost when you pay the rest of the spell\rquote s costs (see rule 409.1f\endash h). Paying a kicker cost is always optional.\par      A spell\rquote s controller chooses targets (see rule 409.1d) for a kicker effect only if he or she declared the intention to pay the kicker cost for that effect. If the spell\rquote s controller declared that he or she wouldn\rquote t pay a particular kicker cost, he or she doesn\rquote t choose the targets for the effect associated with that kicker cost.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Land\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Land is a type. Lands aren\rquote t spells and don\rquote t go on the stack; they are simply played from the hand. The active player may play a land once each turn during his or her main phase when he or she has priority and the stack is empty. If an object is both a land and another type, it can only be played as a land. It can\rquote t be played as a spell. See rule 212.6, \ldblquote Lands.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Land Type\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {A land\rquote s subtype (its \ldblquote land type\rdblquote ) is listed after a long dash on the land\rquote s type line. Note that \ldblquote basic,\rdblquote  \ldblquote legendary,\rdblquote  and \ldblquote nonbasic\rdblquote  aren\rquote t land types. See rule 212.6, \ldblquote Lands.\rdblquote  See also Basic Land Type.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Landcycling\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\ldblquote Landcycling\rdblquote  is a generic term; a card\rquote s rules text usually names a specific type of land, such as \ldblquote plainscycling.\rdblquote \par      Landcycling is an activated ability. \ldblquote Plainscycling [cost]\rdblquote  means \ldblquote [Cost], Discard this card from your hand: Search your library for a plains card, reveal it, and put it into your hand. Then shuffle your library.\rdblquote  See rule 502.18, \ldblquote Cycling.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Landwalk\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\ldblquote Landwalk\rdblquote  is a generic term; a card\rquote s rules text will give a specific property to look for, such as \ldblquote islandwalk.\rdblquote \par      Landwalk is an evasion ability. A creature with landwalk is unblockable as long as the defending player controls at least one land which has the specified subtype or supertype. See rule 502.6, \ldblquote Landwalk.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Last Known Information\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {The last known information about an object is the information that it had just before it left the zone it was in. Effects from resolving spells and abilities use last known information if the object they require information from is not in the zone it was expected to be in. See rule 413.2f.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Layer\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Continuous effects are applied in order, in six layers: (1) copy effects (see rule 503, \ldblquote Copying Objects\rdblquote ), (2) control-changing effects, (3) text-changing effects, (4) type-, subtype-, and supertype-changing effects, (5) all other continuous effects, except those that change power or toughness, and (6) power- or toughness-changing effects. See rule 418.5, \ldblquote Interaction of Continuous Effects.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Leaves Play\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {A permanent leaves play when it moves from the in-play zone to any other zone. See rule 410.10c.\par      If a token leaves play, it ceases to exist. This is a state-based effect. See rule 420.5.\par      If a permanent leaves play and later returns to play, it\rquote s treated as an entirely new permanent with no \ldblquote memory\rdblquote  of anything from its former existence. (Phasing is an exception to this; see rule 502.15, \ldblquote Phasing.\rdblquote )\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Legal Text\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Legal text (the fine print at the bottom of the card) lists the copyright information. It has no effect on game play. See rule 210, \ldblquote Legal Text.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Legend, Legendary\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Legend is a special creature type. Legendary is a supertype that may apply to any type (\ldblquote Legendary Land,\rdblquote  \ldblquote Legendary Artifact,\rdblquote  and so on).\par      If two or more permanents with the same name have the subtype Legend or the supertype legendary, all except the one that has been a Legend or legendary permanent with that name the longest are put into their owners\rquote  graveyards. This \ldblquote Legend rule\rdblquote  is a state-based effect. See rule 420.5.\par      Legend is a creature type; legendary is not. If a legendary noncreature permanent becomes a creature, it\rquote s still \ldblquote legendary,\rdblquote  but it doesn\rquote t get the creature type Legend. If a creature of type Legend becomes a noncreature permanent, it loses the creature type Legend, but it doesn\rquote t become legendary.\par      A Legend whose creature type changes to a creature type other than Legend is no longer a Legend and is no longer subject to the Legend rule. A creature that changes creature type to Legend is now a Legend and is subject to the Legend rule.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Lethal Damage\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Lethal damage is an amount of damage greater than or equal to a creature\rquote s toughness. A creature with lethal damage, but greater than 0 toughness, is destroyed. This is a state-based effect. See rule 420.5.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Library\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {The library is the zone from which a player draws cards. When a game begins, each player\rquote s deck becomes his or her library. See rule 217.2, \ldblquote Library.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Life, Life Total\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Life total is a sort of score. Each player starts the game with 20 life. Any increase in a player\rquote s life total is considered to be gaining life. Any decrease in a player\rquote s life total is considered to be losing life. A player whose life total drops to 0 or less loses. This is a state-based effect. See rule 420.5.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {LIFO (Informal)\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {An acronym for \ldblquote Last In, First Out,\rdblquote  LIFO is the order in which spells and abilities resolve after going on the stack. The last played is resolved first. See rule 409, \ldblquote Playing Spells and Activated Abilities,\rdblquote  and rule 413, \ldblquote Resolving Spells and Abilities.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Local Enchantment\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Local enchantments are a category of enchantments. A local enchantment is labeled \ldblquote Enchant [something]\rdblquote  and is attached to that [something] while in play. See rule 212.4, \ldblquote Enchantments.\rdblquote \par      If a local enchantment is enchanting an illegal permanent or player, the permanent it was attached to no longer exists, or the player it was attached to has left the game, the enchantment is put into its owner\rquote s graveyard. This is a state-based effect. See rule 420.5.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Lose the Game\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {A game immediately ends when a player loses. See rule 102, \ldblquote Winning and Losing.\rdblquote \par }\pard \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Madness\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Madness is a keyword that represents two abilities. The phrase \ldblquote Madness [cost]\rdblquote  means \ldblquote If a player would discard this card from his or her hand, that player discards it, but may remove it from the game instead of putting it into his or her graveyard\rdblquote  and \ldblquote When this card is removed from the game this way, until that player passes next, the player may play it any time he or she could play an instant as though it were in his or her hand by paying [cost] rather than paying its mana cost. When the player passes next, he or she puts it into his or her graveyard.\rdblquote  See rule 502.24, \ldblquote Madness.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Main Game\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {One card (Shahrazad) allows players to play a }{\b Magic}{ subgame. The \ldblquote main game\rdblquote  is the game in which Shahrazad was played. See rule 506, \ldblquote Subgames.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Main Phase\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {The term \ldblquote main phase\rdblquote  comprises the first main and second main phases, also called the \ldblquote precombat\rdblquote  and \ldblquote postcombat\rdblquote  main phases. Artifact, creature, enchantment, and sorcery spells may be played only by the active player during his or her main phase, and only when the stack is empty. A player may also play one land each turn during his or her main phase.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Mana\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Mana is the energy used to play spells and is usually produced by lands. Mana is created by mana abilities (and sometimes by spells), and it can be used to pay costs immediately or can stay in the player\rquote s mana pool. See rule 406, \ldblquote Mana Abilities.\rdblquote \par      Colored mana costs, represented by colored mana symbols, can be paid only with the appropriate color of mana. Generic mana costs can be paid with any color of, or with colorless, mana. See rule 104.3.\par      The spell or ability that adds mana to a mana pool may restrict how it can be used. An ability might produce mana that can be used only to play creature spells or only to pay activation costs.\par      The type of mana a permanent \ldblquote could produce\rdblquote  is the type of mana that any ability of that permanent can generate, taking into account any applicable replacement effects. If the type of mana can\rquote t be defined, there\rquote s no type of mana that that permanent could produce. The \ldblquote type\rdblquote  of mana includes both its color (if any) and any restrictions placed upon it.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Mana Ability\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {A mana ability is either activated or triggered. A mana ability doesn\rquote t go on the stack\emdash it resolves immediately. See rule 411, \ldblquote Playing Mana Abilities.\rdblquote \par      A player may play an activated mana ability whenever he or she has priority and whenever a rule or effect asks for a mana payment. This is the only type of ability that can be played in the middle of playing or resolving a spell or ability. See rule 406, \ldblquote Mana Abilities.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Mana Burn\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {When a phase ends, any unused mana remaining in a player\rquote s mana pool is lost. The player loses 1 life for each mana lost this way. This is called \ldblquote mana burn.\rdblquote  See rule 300.3.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Mana Cost\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {The mana cost of a nonland card is indicated by the mana symbols printed on its upper right corner. The mana cost of a land card, token, or face-down creature is 0. See rule 203, \ldblquote Mana Cost and Color.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Mana Pool\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {When an effect creates mana, that mana goes into the player\rquote s mana pool. From there, it can be used to pay for spells and abilities. The mana can be used immediately to pay a cost, or stored in the mana pool for use later in the phase. The mana pool is cleared at the end of each phase. See also Mana Burn.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Mana Source (Obsolete)\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Some older cards were printed with the type \ldblquote mana source.\rdblquote  All mana source cards are now instant cards. Abilities that read \ldblquote Play this ability as a mana source\rdblquote  are now mana abilities.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Mana Symbol\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {The mana symbols are \{oW\}, \{oU\}, \{oB\}, \{oR\}, \{oG\}, \{oX\}, \{oY\}, \{oZ\} and the numerals \{o0\}, \{o1\}, \{o2\}, \{o3\}, \{o4\}, and so on. See rule 104.3.\par      Each of the colored mana symbols represents one colored mana: \{oW\} white, \{oU\} blue, \{oB\} black, \{oR\} red, and \{oG\} green. See rule 104.3a.\par      Numeral symbols (such as \{o1\}) are generic mana costs and represent an amount of mana that can be paid with any color of, or colorless, mana. See rule 104.3b.\par      The symbols \{oX\}, \{oY\} and \{oZ\} represent unspecified amounts of mana; when playing a spell or activated ability with \{oX\}, \{oY\}, or \{oZ\} in its cost, its controller decides the value of that variable. See rule 104.3c.\par      Numeral symbols and variable symbols can also represent colorless mana if they appear in the effect of a spell or of a mana ability that reads \ldblquote add [mana symbol] to your mana pool\rdblquote  or something similar. See rule 104.3d.\par      The symbol \{o0\} represents zero mana and is used as a placeholder when a spell or activated ability costs nothing to play. A spell or ability whose cost is \{o0\} must still be played the same way as one with a cost greater than zero; it won\rquote t play itself automatically. See rule 104.3e.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Match\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {A match is a series of }{\b Magic}{ games and is important only for tournament or league play. A match usually consists of the best two of three games, or sometimes the best three of five. For more information, consult the DCI }{\b Magic}{ Floor Rules (}{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst { HYPERLINK "http://www.wizards.com/default.asp?x=dci/utr/intro" 