c ability and a triggered ability. \ldblquote Modular X\rdblquote  means \ldblquote This permanent comes into play with X +1/+1 counters on it\rdblquote  and \ldblquote When this permanent is put into a graveyard from play, you may put a +1/+1 counter on target artifact creature for each +1/+1 counter on this permanent.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Mono Artifact (Obsolete)\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Some older cards  used the term \ldblquote mono artifact\rdblquote  on the card\rquote s type line. They were artifacts that had activated abilities that included the tap symbol. Cards that were printed with the term \ldblquote mono artifact\rdblquote  now simply use \ldblquote artifact.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Morph\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Morph is a static ability that functions any time you could play the card it\rquote s on, and the morph effect works any time the card is face down. The phrase \ldblquote Morph [cost]\rdblquote  means \ldblquote You may play this card as a 2/2 face-down creature, with no text, no name, no subtypes, no expansion symbol, and a mana cost of 0 by paying 3 rather than its mana cost.\rdblquote  Any time you could play an instant, you may show all players the morph cost for any face-down permanent you control, pay that cost, then turn the permanent face up. This action does not use the stack. See rule 502.26, \ldblquote Morph.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Mountain\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\ldblquote Mountain\rdblquote  is one of the five basic land types. Any land with the land type Mountain has the ability \ldblquote \{oT\}: Add \{oR\} to your mana pool.\rdblquote  See rule 212.6d.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Mountaincycling\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {See Landcycling.\par }\pard \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Mountainwalk\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {See Landwalk.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Move\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {To move a local enchantment, Equipment, or a counter means to take it from one object and put it onto another. If the enchantment, Equipment, or counter no longer exists or the new permanent is no longer in play when the effect would move it, nothing happens. Similarly, an enchantment or Equipment can\rquote t be moved onto a permanent it couldn\rquote t enchant or equip; if this kind of move is attempted, the enchantment or Equipment stays where it is.\par      A moved enchantment stops enchanting the previous permanent and starts enchanting the new one, and it receives a new timestamp. Nothing else about the enchantment changes. The enchantment never left play, so no comes-into-play or leaves-play triggered abilities will trigger. If an ability of the moved enchantment affecting \ldblquote enchanted [permanent]\rdblquote  was on the stack when the enchantment moved, it will affect the new enchanted permanent when it resolves, not the old one. The same is true for moved Equipment.\par      The equip ability can move Equipment onto a creature or from one creature to another.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Mulligan\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {A player can \ldblquote mulligan\rdblquote  by shuffling his or her hand back into his or her library and drawing a new hand with one fewer card before taking the first turn. Any player dissatisfied with his or her starting hand may mulligan as often as he or she wishes, drawing one fewer card each time. See rule 101.4.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Multicolored\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {A multicolored card has two or more colors. Multicolored cards are printed with gold frames to reinforce this. See rule 203.2.\par      A multicolored object is affected by anything that singles out any of its colors. For example, a black-and-green creature is destroyed by a spell that reads, \ldblquote Destroy all green creatures.\rdblquote  Something that can\rquote t affect a particular color doesn\rquote t affect a multicolored object with that color, so that same creature can\rquote t be targeted by a spell or ability that reads, \ldblquote Destroy target nonblack creature.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Name\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {The name of a card is printed on its upper left corner. See rule 202, \ldblquote Name.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Nonbasic Land\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Any land that doesn\rquote t have the supertype \ldblquote basic\rdblquote  is nonbasic. Use the Oracle reference to determine whether a land has the supertype \ldblquote basic.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Number\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {The }{\b Magic}{ game uses only natural numbers. You may not choose a fractional number, deal fractional damage, and so on. When a spell or ability could generate a fractional number, the spell or ability will tell you whether to round up or down. See rule 104, \ldblquote Numbers and Symbols.\rdblquote \par      If a creature\rquote s power or toughness, a mana cost, a player\rquote s life total, or an amount of damage is less than zero, it\rquote s treated as zero for all purposes except adding to or subtracting from that total. If anything needs to use a number that can\rquote t be determined, it uses 0 instead.\par }\pard\plain \s28\li400\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin400\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ If a 3/3 creature gets -5/-0, it deals 0 damage in combat. But to raise its power back to 1, you\rquote d have to give it +3/+0 (3 minus 5 plus 3 is 1).\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Object\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {An \ldblquote object\rdblquote  is a card, a copy of a card, a token, a spell, a permanent, an ability on the stack, or combat damage on the stack. The term \ldblquote object\rdblquote  is used in these rules when a rule applies to cards, copies of cards, tokens, spells, permanents, abilities on the stack, and combat damage on the stack. See rule 200.8.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Obsolete\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Terms marked \ldblquote (Obsolete)\rdblquote  in this glossary were used only on older cards. Updated wordings for all cards that used these terms are available in the Oracle card reference.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {One-Shot Effect\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {One-shot effects do something only once and then end. See rule 417, \ldblquote One-Shot Effects.\rdblquote  See also Continuous Effects.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Opponent\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {A player\rquote s opponent is the other player.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Oracle\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Use the Oracle card reference when determining a card\rquote s wording. It can be found at }{\field\fldedit{\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK "http://www.wizards.com/default.asp?x=dci/oracle"}{{\*\datafield 00d0c9ea79f9bace118c8200aa004ba90b0200000003000000e0c9ea79f9bace118c8200aa004ba90b6000000068007400740070003a002f002f007700770077002e00770069007a0061007200640073002e0063006f006d002f00640065006600610075006c0074002e006100730070003f0078003d006400630069002f006f007200610063006c0065000000}}