have the text \ldblquote Remove [this card] from your deck before playing if you\rquote re not playing for ante.\rdblquote  These are the only cards that can change a card\rquote s owner. See rule 217.9, \ldblquote Ante.\rdblquote )\par      A card is always put into its owner\rquote s library, hand, or graveyard, regardless of who controlled the card in its previous zone. See rule 217.1a.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Pass\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {To pass is to decline to take any action (usually playing a spell or ability) when you have priority. When a player passes, his or her opponent receives priority. See rule 408.1, \ldblquote Timing, Priority, and the Stack.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Pass in Succession\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {To pass in succession means that both players pass without playing any spells, playing any abilities, or performing any special actions in between. If both players pass in succession, the spell, ability, or combat damage on top of the stack resolves. If the stack is empty, the phase or step ends. See rule 408.1, \ldblquote Timing, Priority, and the Stack.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Pay\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Playing most spells and activated abilities requires paying costs; see rule 409, \ldblquote Playing Spells and Activated Abilities.\rdblquote  Declaring attackers (see rule 308, \ldblquote Declare Attackers Step\rdblquote ) and declaring blockers (see rule 309, \ldblquote Declare Blockers Step\rdblquote ) can also require paying costs.\par      Paying mana is done by removing the indicated amount of mana from the player\rquote s mana pool. Any time a player is asked to pay mana, mana abilities may be played. Mana abilities must be played before the costs are paid. Paying life subtracts the indicated amount of life from the player\rquote s life total. A player can\rquote t pay more mana than the amount of mana in his or her mana pool or more life than his or her life total. Zero life or zero mana can always be paid, even if the player has less than zero life.\par      To pay any cost, the player carries out the instructions specified by the spell, ability, or effect. It\rquote s illegal to attempt paying a cost when unable to successfully follow the instructions. For example, a player can\rquote t pay a cost that requires tapping a creature if that creature is already tapped.\par      Each payment applies to only one spell or ability. For example, a player can\rquote t sacrifice just one creature to play the activated abilities of two permanents that require sacrificing a creature as a cost. Also, the resolution of a spell or ability doesn\rquote t pay another spell or ability\rquote s cost, even if part of its effect is doing the same thing the other cost asks for.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Permanent\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {A permanent is any card or token in the in-play zone. See rule 214, \ldblquote Permanents.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Permanently (Obsolete)\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Certain older cards were printed with the term \ldblquote permanently\rdblquote  to indicate effects with no expiration. In general, cards that were printed with the term \ldblquote permanently\rdblquote  now instead use reminder text to indicate that the effect lasts past the end of the turn.\par }\pard\plain \s28\li400\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin400\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ An ability that originally read \ldblquote Gain control of target creature permanently\rdblquote  would now read as follows: \ldblquote Gain control of target creature. (This effect doesn\rquote t end at end of turn.)\rdblquote  This effect grants control of the permanent until something else changes the controller or it leaves play. It doesn\rquote t make the permanent immune to other control effects.\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Phase\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Each turn is divided into five phases: beginning, precombat main, combat, postcombat main, and end. See section 3, \ldblquote Turn Structure.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Phased-Out\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {The phased-out zone is a special zone for permanents with phasing that are temporarily out of play. See rule 502.15, \ldblquote Phasing.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Phasing\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Phasing is a static ability that causes a permanent to leave play and later return, without losing its \ldblquote memory.\rdblquote 