d ability requires paying any costs and choosing any required modes and/or targets. See rule 409, \ldblquote Playing Spells and Activated Abilities.\rdblquote \par      Playing a land simply requires choosing a land card from the hand and putting it into play. See rule 212.6, \ldblquote Lands.\rdblquote \par      Playing a mana ability requires paying any costs, then immediately resolving the ability. See rule 411, \ldblquote Playing Mana Abilities.\rdblquote \par      Triggered abilities and static abilities aren\rquote t played\emdash they happen automatically. See rule 410, \ldblquote Handling Triggered Abilities.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Play/Draw (Informal)\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {At the start of a game, one player gets to choose the order of play. Whoever plays first skips his or her first draw step. This is referred to as the play/draw rule. See rule 101, \ldblquote Starting the Game.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Player\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {A player is one of the two people in the game. A player\rquote s opponent is the other player. The active player is the player whose turn it is. The other player is the nonactive player. See rule 200.3.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Poison Counter\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Some cards give poison counters to players. If a player has ten or more poison counters, he or she loses the game the next time a player would receive priority. See rule 420, \ldblquote State-Based Effects.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Poly Artifact (Obsolete)\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Some older cards used the term \ldblquote poly artifact\rdblquote  on the card\rquote s type line. They were artifacts that had activated abilities that don\rquote t include the tap symbol. Cards that were printed with the term \ldblquote poly artifact\rdblquote  now simply use \ldblquote artifact.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Postcombat\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {The second main phase in each turn is called the postcombat main phase. If an effect causes a turn to have an extra combat phase and another main phase, the additional one is also a postcombat main phase. See rule 305, \ldblquote Main Phase.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Power\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {The number before the slash printed on the lower right corner of a creature card is the creature\rquote s power. See rule 208, \ldblquote Power/Toughness.\rdblquote \par      Creatures that attack or block assign combat damage equal to their power. See rule 310, \ldblquote Combat Damage Step.\rdblquote \par      Some objects have power represented by * instead of a number. The object has a characteristic-setting ability that sets its power according to some stated condition. The * is 0 while the object isn\rquote t in play.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Precombat\par }\pard\plain 