ccession, the spell, ability, or combat damage on top of the stack resolves or, if the stack is empty, the phase or step ends.\par      Each time a player would get priority, all applicable state-based effects resolve first as a single event (see rule 420). Then, if any new state-based effects have been generated, they resolve as a single event. This process repeats until no more applicable state-based effects are generated. Then triggered abilities are added to the stack (see rule 410). These steps repeat in order until no further state-based effects or triggered abilities are generated. \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Protection\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Protection is a static ability, written \ldblquote Protection from [quality].\rdblquote  See rule 502.7, \ldblquote Protection.\rdblquote \par      A permanent with protection can\rquote t be targeted by spells with the stated quality and can\rquote t be targeted by abilities from a source with the stated quality.\par      A permanent with protection can\rquote t be enchanted by enchantments that have the stated quality. Such enchantments enchanting the permanent with protection will be put into their owners\rquote  graveyards as a state-based effect. (See rule 420, \ldblquote State-Based Effects.\rdblquote )\par      A permanent with protection can\rquote t be equipped by Equipment that has the stated quality. Such Equipment stops equipping that permanent, but remains in play. (See rule 420, \ldblquote State-Based Effects.\rdblquote )\par      Any damage that would be dealt by sources that have the stated quality to a permanent that has protection is prevented. \par      Any damage that would be dealt to a permanent with protection from sources having that quality is prevented.\par      If a creature with protection attacks, it can\rquote t be blocked by creatures that have the stated quality.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Provoke\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Provoke is a triggered ability. \ldblquote Provoke\rdblquote  means \ldblquote Whenever this creature attacks, you may choose to have target creature defending player controls block this creature this combat if able. If you do, untap that creature.\rdblquote  See rule 502.29, \ldblquote Provoke.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Put Into Play\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {If an effect instructs a player to put an object into play, that object is not considered \ldblquote played.\rdblquote \par }\pard \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Rampage\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Rampage is a triggered ability. \ldblquote Rampage X\rdblquote  means \ldblquote When this creature becomes blocked, it gets +X/+X until end of turn for each creature blocking it beyond the first.\rdblquote  See rule 502.12, \ldblquote Rampage.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Random\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {If a spell, ability, or effect requires a player to choose something at random, that player can use any method of making a random choice (rolling dice, flipping a coin, and so on). The outcome must be truly random.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Redirect (Obsolete)\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Some older cards were printed with the term \ldblquote redirect\rdblquote  to describe the act of dealing damage to a different player or creature than originally specified by a spell, ability, or combat-damage assignment, without changing the source or type of damage. In general, cards that were printed with the term \ldblquote redirect\rdblquote  now create replacement effects that modify where the damage will be dealt. \ldblquote Redirect\rdblquote  is still used informally to describe what these replacement effects do.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Regenerate\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Regeneration is a destruction-replacement effect. \ldblquote Regenerate [permanent]\rdblquote  means \ldblquote The next time [permanent] would be destroyed this turn, instead remove all damage from it, tap it, and (if it\rquote s in combat) remove it from combat.\rdblquote  Because it\rquote s a replacement effect, it must be active before the attempted destruction event. Abilities that trigger from damage being dealt still trigger even if the permanent regenerates. See rule 419.6b.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Reminder Text\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Reminder text appears after a keyword ability printed on a card and on cards that might otherwise be commonly misunderstood. Reminder text is text that is italicized and in parentheses in the text box of a card. This text provides a summary of the game rule or clarifies what the card does, but it isn\rquote t itself considered rules text. See rule 207.2.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Removed from Combat\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {An attacking or blocking creature is removed from combat if it leaves play (such as by being destroyed or removed from the game), if it regenerates (see rule 419.6b), if its controller changes, if it stops being a creature, or if an effect removes it from combat. A creature that is removed from combat stops being an attacking or blocking creature and can no longer assign combat damage or have combat damage assigned to it. Any combat damage that\rquote s already on the stack assigned to or by the creature will still resolve normally. See rule 306.2 and rule 310.4a.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Removed from the Game\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {A card removed from the game is out of play and can\rquote t be affected by spells or abilities. However, the effect that removed the card may specify a way for it to return. Some objects use the expression \ldblquote set aside\rdblquote  for situations in which a card removed from the game can return to play. See rule 217.7, \ldblquote Removed from the Game.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Replacement Effect\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {A replacement effect is a type of continuous effect that \ldblquote watches\rdblquote  for a specified event and replaces it with a different one. See rule 419, \ldblquote Replacement and Prevention Effects.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Requirement\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {A requirement to attack or block is any effect that forces one or more creatures to attack or block. All attacks and blocks must still be legal. See rule 500, \ldblquote Legal Attacks and Blocks.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Resolve\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {When a spell or ability on top of the stack resolves, its controller carries out the instructions printed on the card, in the order written. When combat damage resolves, it\rquote s dealt as previously assigned to the fullest extent possible. See rule 413, \ldblquote Resolving Spells and Abilities.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Respond, Response (Informal)\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {A player can choose to play an instant spell or activated ability when something else is already on the stack, rather than waiting for the earlier spell or ability to resolve first. The spell or ability is said to be played \ldblquote in response to\rdblquote  the earlier spell or ability. See rule 408, \ldblquote Timing of Spells and Abilities.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Restriction\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {A restriction on attacking or blocking is any effect that could prevent a creature from attacking or blocking. All attacks and blocks must still be legal. See rule 500, \ldblquote Legal Attacks and Blocks.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Reveal\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {To reveal an object is to show that object to all players. If a one-shot effect reveals a card, the card is returned to its former state after all players have seen it.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Rules Text\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {An object\rquote s rules text defines many of that object\rquote s properties. Changing an object\rquote s rules text changes the object\rquote s properties.\par }\pard \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Sacrifice\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {To sacrifice a permanent, its controller moves it from the in-play zone directly to its owner\rquote s graveyard. A player can\rquote t sacrifice something that isn\rquote t a permanent, or something that\rquote s a permanent he or she doesn\rquote t control. If an effect instructs a player to sacrifice a permanent that he or she doesn\rquote t control, nothing happens. Sacrificing a permanent doesn\rquote t destroy it, so regeneration or other effects that replace destruction can\rquote t affect it.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Sealed-Deck\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {For sealed deck or draft play, only forty cards are required in a deck, and a player may use as many duplicates of a card as he or she has. Each player still needs small items to represent any tokens and counters, and some way to clearly track life totals. See rule 100.3.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Search\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {If you\rquote re required to search a zone not revealed to all players for cards matching some criteria, you aren\rquote t required to find those cards even if they\rquote re present; however, if you do choose to find cards, you must reveal those cards to all players. Even if you don\rquote t find any cards, you are still considered to have searched the zone.\par      If you\rquote re simply searching for \ldblquote any card,\rdblquote  you must find a card (if possible).\par      If you\rquote re required to search for a specific number of cards, you must choose that many cards (or as many as possible.)\par }\pard\plain \s28\li400\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin400\itap0 \i\fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\b Example:}{ If an effect causes you to search a player\rquote s library for all duplicates of a particular card and remove them from the game, you may choose to leave some of them alone, but if an effect causes you to search your library for three cards and it contains at least three, you can\rquote t choose less than three.\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {     If an effects states to search for a [type, supertype, or subtype] card, it can only find cards that have that type, supertype, or subtype. It can\rquote t find a card that has a name equal to that type, supertype, or subtype unless that card also has the type, supertype, or subtype.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Set Aside\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {To set aside a card is to remove it from the game; however, the effect will specify some condition that allows the set-aside card to return to the game. See also Removed from the Game.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Shadow\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Shadow is an evasion ability. Attacking creatures with shadow can\rquote t be blocked by creatures without shadow, and attacking creatures without shadow can\rquote t be blocked by creatures with shadow. See rule 502.8, \ldblquote Shadow.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Shield\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Replacement and prevention effects act like \ldblquote shields\rdblquote  around whatever they\rquote re affecting. See rule 419, \ldblquote Replacement and Prevention Effects.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Shuffle\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {To shuffle a deck, library, or pile is to make the order of that deck, library, or pile random. After a player shuffles a deck, library, or pile, he or she owns, the opponent has the option to shuffle or cut that pile. See rule 101.1.\par }\pard \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Skip\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {To skip an event, step, phase, or turn is to proceed past it as though it didn\rquote t exist. Skipping an event, step, phase, or turn is a replacement effect. \ldblquote Skip [something]\rdblquote  is the same as \ldblquote Instead of doing [something], do nothing.\rdblquote  See rule 300.9 and rule 419.6e.\par      Once a step, phase, or turn has started, it can no longer be skipped\emdash any skip effects will wait until the next occurrence.\par      Anything scheduled for a skipped step, phase, or turn won\rquote t happen. Anything scheduled for the \ldblquote next\rdblquote  occurrence of something waits for the first occurrence that isn\rquote t skipped. If two effects each cause a player to skip his or her next occurrence, that player must skip the next two; one effect will be satisfied in skipping the first occurrence, while the other will remain until another occurrence can be skipped. See rule 419.6f.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Snow-Covered\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Snow-covered is an ability that doesn\rquote t do anything in its own right; it\rquote s simply a keyword that other cards look for. When a card refers to a \ldblquote snow-covered land,\rdblquote  it means a land with the snow-covered ability. When a card refers to a \ldblquote snow-covered Forest,\rdblquote  it means a Forest with the snow-covered ability, and so on. See rule 502.14, \ldblquote Snow-Covered.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Snow-Covered Landwalk\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Snow-covered landwalk is a special form of landwalk. A creature with snow-covered landwalk is unblockable as long as the defending player controls at least one land of the specified subtype or supertype that has the snow-covered ability. See rule 502.6, \ldblquote Landwalk.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Sorcery\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Sorcery is a type. The active player can play sorceries only during his or her main phase when the stack is empty. A sorcery spell is put into its owner\rquote s graveyard as part of its resolution. See rule 212.7, \ldblquote Sorceries.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Source of an Ability\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {The source of an ability is the object that generated it. See rule 402, \ldblquote Abilities.\rdblquote \par }\pard \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Source of Damage\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {The source of damage is the object that dealt it. If an effect requires a player to choose a source of damage, he or she may choose either a permanent or a spell on the stack (including one that creates a permanent) or any object referred to by a spell or ability on the stack. A source doesn\rquote t need to be capable of dealing damage to be a legal choice. See rule 419.8, \ldblquote Sources of Damage.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Special Action\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Special actions don\rquote t use the stack. The special actions are playing a land, turning a face-down creature face up, ending continuous effects or preventing delayed triggered abilities, and suspending or ignoring continuous effects. See rule 408.1i and rule 408.2, \ldblquote Actions That Don\rquote t Use the Stack.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Spell\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {A nonland card becomes a spell when it\rquote s played and remains a spell until it\rquote s countered, it resolves, or it otherwise leaves the stack. A copy of a spell is also a spell, even if it has no card associated with it. See rule 213, \ldblquote Spells,\rdblquote  and rule 401, \ldblquote Spells on the Stack.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Split Cards\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Split cards have two card faces on a single card. The back of a split card is the normal, full-size }{\b Magic}{ card back. Split cards have two sets of characteristics: two names, two mana costs, and so on. They always have both sets, except when they\rquote re spells on the stack. When you play a split card, you announce which side you\rquote re playing. While it\rquote s on the stack, the other side is ignored completely. See rule 505, \ldblquote Split Cards.\rdblquote \par      Split cards have two mana costs with different colors of mana in them. That means they are multicolored cards, except while they\rquote re on the stack.\par      If an effect tells you to name a card, you must name all of a split card\rquote s names.\par      Effects that ask for a split card\rquote s characteristic get both answers. Effects that ask if a split card\rquote s characteristic matches a given value get only one answer. This answer is \ldblquote yes\rdblquote  if either side of the split card matches the given value.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Stack\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {A spell or ability goes on top of the stack when it\rquote s played or put onto the stack. Combat-damage assignments also go on top of the stack as though they were a single object. Whenever both players pass in succession, the spell, ability, or combat damage on top of the stack resolves and the active player receives priority again. See rule 217.6, \ldblquote Stack,\rdblquote  and rule 408.1, \ldblquote Timing, Priority, and the Stack.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {State-Based Effects\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {State-based effects continually \ldblquote watch\rdblquote  the game for a particular state. Whenever a player would receive priority, state-based effects are checked and applied. See rule 420, \ldblquote State-Based Effects.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {State Triggers\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {State triggers are triggered abilities that watch for a game state rather than an event and trigger as soon as the game state matches the condition. Once a state trigger has triggered, it won\rquote t trigger again until the ability it created has resolved or been countered. See rule 410.11.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Static Ability\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Static abilities do something all the time rather than being played at specific times. Static abilities create continuous effects, which are active as long as the permanent with the ability remains in play and has the ability, or as long as the object with the ability remains in the appropriate zone. A spell or ability can also create a continuous effect that doesn\rquote t depend on a permanent; these may last a specified length of time or for the rest of the game. See rule 412, \ldblquote Handling Static Abilities.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Step\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Some phases of the turn are further subdivided into steps. See section 3, \ldblquote Turn Structure.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Storm\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Storm is a triggered ability that functions while the spell is on the stack. \ldblquote Storm\rdblquote  means \ldblquote When you play this spell, put a copy of it onto the stack for each other spell that was played before it this turn. If the spell has any targets, you may choose new targets for any number of the copies.\rdblquote  See rule 502.30, \ldblquote Storm.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Subgame\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {One card (Shahrazad) allows players to play a }{\b Magic}{ subgame. A \ldblquote subgame\rdblquote  is the game created by Shahrazad. See rule 506, \ldblquote Subgames.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Subtype\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {A card can have one or more subtypes printed on its type line. Artifact, creature, and land subtypes are always single words and are listed after a long dash. Each word after the dash is a separate subtype. Artifact subtypes are also called \ldblquote artifact types.\rdblquote  Creature subtypes are also called \ldblquote creature types.\rdblquote  Land subtypes are also called \ldblquote land types.\rdblquote  Artifacts, creatures, and lands may have multiple subtypes. If an artifact creature card has subtypes printed on its type line, those subtypes are creature types. If an artifact land card has subtypes printed on its type line, those types are land types. Enchantment subtypes consist of the word \ldblquote enchant\rdblquote  and the word(s) that follows it: \ldblquote enchant creature,\rdblquote  \ldblquote enchant land,\rdblquote  etc. A card with the type \ldblquote enchantment\rdblquote  has no subtype. Instants and sorceries don\rquote t have subtypes. See rule 205.3, \ldblquote Subtypes,\rdblquote  and rule 212, \ldblquote Type, Supertype, and Subtype.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Successfully Cast (Obsolete)\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Some older cards were printed with the term \ldblquote successfully cast.\rdblquote  In general, any ability that\rquote s written as triggering when a spell is \ldblquote successfully cast\rdblquote  should be read as triggering when the spell is played.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Summon (Obsolete)\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Older creature cards were printed with the type \ldblquote Summon [creature type].\rdblquote  All \ldblquote Summon [creature type]\rdblquote  cards should be read as \ldblquote Creature \emdash  [creature type].\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Summoning Sickness (Informal)\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {The term \ldblquote summoning sickness\rdblquote  is an informal term which describes a creature\rquote s inability to attack or to use activated abilities that include the tap symbol when it has come under a player\rquote s control since the beginning of that player\rquote s most recent turn. See rule 212.3d. See also Haste.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Supertype\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {A card can have one or more \ldblquote supertypes.\rdblquote  These are printed directly before the card\rquote s types. If an object\rquote s types or subtypes change, any supertypes it has are kept, although they may not be relevant to the new type. See rule 205.4, \ldblquote Supertypes.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Swamp\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {\ldblquote Swamp\rdblquote  is one of the five basic land types. Any land with the land type Swamp has the ability \ldblquote \{oT\}: Add \{oB\} to your mana pool.\rdblquote  See rule 212.6d.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Swampcycling\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {See Landcycling.\par }\pard \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Swampwalk\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {See Landwalk.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Tap\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {To tap a permanent is to turn it sideways. The tap symbol (\{oT\} in these rules) in an activation cost means \ldblquote Tap this permanent\rdblquote \emdash a permanent that\rquote s already tapped can\rquote t be tapped again to pay the cost. Creatures that haven\rquote t been under a player\rquote s control continuously since the beginning of his or her most recent turn can\rquote t use any ability of theirs with the tap symbol in the cost. See rule 104.4.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Tapped\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {A permanent that\rquote s turned sideways is tapped. Tapping permanents shows that they\rquote ve been used. Permanents untap during their controllers\rquote  untap steps. See also Tap, Untap, and Untapped.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Target\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Whenever the phrase \ldblquote target [something],\rdblquote  where [something] is a phrase that describes an object or player, appears in a spell or ability, the controller of the spell or ability chooses something that matches whatever follows that word. The choice of a spell or ability\rquote s targets is made when the spell or ability is played. See rule 415, \ldblquote Targeted Spells and Abilities.\rdblquote \par      An instant or sorcery is targeted if the text that will be followed when it resolves uses the phrase \ldblquote target [something],\rdblquote  where the \ldblquote something\rdblquote  is a phrase that describes an object or player. (If an activated or triggered ability of an instant or sorcery uses the word target, that ability is targeted, but the spell is not.)\par      An activated or triggered ability is targeted if it uses the phrase \ldblquote target [something],\rdblquote  where the \ldblquote something\rdblquote  is a phrase that describes an object or player.\par      Local-enchantment spells are always targeted, even though they don\rquote t use the phrase \ldblquote target [something].\rdblquote  They target the permanent or player they will enchant. (See rule 415.3.) A local-enchantment permanent doesn\rquote t target anything.\par      Neither Equipment spells nor Equipment permanents are targeted. (See rule 415.3.) An Equipment may have abilities which are targeted.\par      A spell or ability on the stack can\rquote t target itself.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Text Box\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {The text box is printed below the illustration on a }{\b Magic}{ card and contains rules text that defines the card\rquote s abilities, reminder text, and flavor text. See rule 207, \ldblquote Text Box.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Text-Changing Effect\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {An effect that changes the text of an object changes only words that are used in the correct way. The effect can\rquote t change a proper noun, such as a card name, even if that proper noun contains a word or a series of letters that is the same as a }{\b Magic}{ color word, basic land type, or creature type. See rule 418.6, \ldblquote Text-Changing Effects.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Threshold\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Threshold is a characteristic-setting ability. An object with threshold has the text after \ldblquote Threshold \emdash \rdblquote  if its controller has seven or more cards in his or her graveyard. Otherwise, the text after \ldblquote Threshold \emdash \rdblquote  is treated as though it did not appear on the object. An instant or sorcery with threshold has the threshold text only if it\rquote s on the stack. An artifact, creature, enchantment, or land with threshold has the threshold text only if it\rquote s in play. See rule 502.23, \ldblquote Threshold.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Tie\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {If an effect could result in a tie, the text of the spell or ability that created the effect will specify what to do in the event of a tie. The }{\b Magic}{ game has no default for ties.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Timestamp Order\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {An object\rquote s timestamp is the time it entered the zone it\rquote s currently in, with three exceptions: (1) If two or more objects enter a zone simultaneously, the active player determines their timestamp order at the time they enter that zone. (2) Whenever a local enchantment or Equipment becomes attached to a permanent, the enchantment or Equipment receives a new timestamp. (3) Permanents that phase in keep the same timestamps they had when they phased out. See rule 418.5e. See also Depend On.\par      Continuous effects generated by static abilities have the same timestamp as the object that generated them. Continuous effects generated by the resolution of a spell or ability receive a timestamp at the time they\rquote re created.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Token\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {A token is a marker used to represent any permanent that isn\rquote t represented by a card. Tokens are created by effects. Tokens can be tapped and untapped just like cards, though an alternative to rotation might be needed to distinguish their status. See rule 216, \ldblquote Tokens.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Tombstone Icon\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {A tombstone icon appears to the left of the name of many }{\i Odyssey}{ block cards with abilities that are relevant in a player\rquote s graveyard. The purpose of the icon is to make those cards stand out when they\rquote re in a graveyard. This icon has no effect on game play. See rule 104.5.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Total Cost\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {The total cost of a spell or activated ability is the mana cost, activation cost, or alternative cost, plus all cost increases and minus all cost reductions. See rule 409.1f\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Total Casting Cost (Obsolete)\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Some older cards were printed with the term \ldblquote total casting cost\rdblquote  to describe the converted mana cost of a spell. In general, cards that were printed with the term \ldblquote total casting cost\rdblquote  now use the term \ldblquote converted mana cost.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Toughness\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {The number after the slash printed on the lower right corner of a creature card is the creature\rquote s toughness. See rule 208, \ldblquote Power/Toughness.\rdblquote \par      A creature that\rquote s been dealt damage greater than or equal to its toughness (and greater than 0) has lethal damage and will be destroyed the next time any player would receive priority. This is a state-based effect.\par      Some objects have toughness represented by * instead of a number. The object has a characteristic-setting ability that sets its toughness according to some stated condition. The * is 0 while the object isn\rquote t in play.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Tournament\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustri