ang1033\cgrid {Type Line\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {The type (and subtype and supertype, if applicable) of a card is printed directly below the illustration. See rule 205, \ldblquote Type Line,\rdblquote  and rule 212, \ldblquote Type, Supertype, and Subtype.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Unblockable\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {If an attacking creature \ldblquote is unblockable,\rdblquote  no creature can legally block it. Spells or abilities may still cause it to become blocked.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Unblocked Creature\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {An attacking creature becomes an unblocked creature during the declare blockers step of the combat phase if no creature blocks it. It remains an unblocked creature until an effect causes it to become blocked, it\rquote s removed from combat, it stops being a creature, its controller changes, or the combat phase ends. Unblocked creatures don\rquote t exist outside of the combat phase or before the declare blockers step. See rule 309, \ldblquote Declare Blockers Step.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Universal Tournament Rules\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {The DCI Universal Tournament Rules (}{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst { HYPERLINK "http://www.wizards.com/default.asp?x=dci/utr/intro" }{{\*\datafield 00d0c9ea79f9bace118c8200aa004ba90b0200000003000000e0c9ea79f9bace118c8200aa004ba90b6600000068007400740070003a