reature that can\rquote t be declared as an attacker. In all other respects, a Wall is the same as any other creature. See rule 308.2a.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Win the Game\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {A game immediately ends when a player wins. See rule 102, \ldblquote Winning and Losing.\rdblquote \par }\pard \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {X\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {If a cost has an \ldblquote X\rdblquote  in it, the value of X must be announced as part of playing the spell or ability. (See rule 409, \ldblquote Playing Spells and Activated Abilities.\rdblquote ) While the spell or ability is on the stack, the \{oX\} in its mana cost equals the amount announced as part of playing the spell or ability. If a card in any other zone has \{oX\} in its mana cost, the amount is treated as 0. If you\rquote re playing a spell that has X in its mana cost and an effect lets you play it without paying any cost that includes X, the only legal choice for X is 0. This does not apply to effects that only reduce a cost, even if they reduce it to zero. See rule 409, \ldblquote Playing Spells and Activated Abilities.\rdblquote \par      In triggered abilities, X is defined when the ability resolves. It may be defined by the text of the ability, by a keyword ability of the card, or by the trigger event. See rule 410, \ldblquote Handling Triggered Abilities.\rdblquote \par      In other cases, X is defined by the text of a spell or ability. If X isn\rquote t defined, the controller of the spell or ability chooses the value of X. All Xs on an object have the same value.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Y, Z\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {See X.\par }\pard \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {You, Your\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {The words \ldblquote you\rdblquote  and \ldblquote your\rdblquote  on an object refer to the object\rquote s controller (or its owner if it has no controller). For static abilities, this is the current controller of the object it\rquote s on. For activated abilities, this is the player who played the ability. For triggered abilities, this is the controller of the object when the ability triggered. See also Controller, Owner.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Zone\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {A zone is any place that }{\b Magic}{ cards can be during a game. See rule 217, \ldblquote Zones.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Zone-Change Triggers\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\cgrid {Trigger events that involve objects changing zones are called \ldblquote zone-change triggers.\rdblquote  Many abilities with zone-change triggers attempt to do something to that object after it changes zones. During resolution, these abilities look for the object in the zone that it moved to. If the object is unable to be found in the zone it went to, the part of the ability 